<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Anti-SemitismReport     05-31 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Semitism Report,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ADL Reports Upswing in Israel-Related Anti-Semitism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There has been a sharp rise in anti-Semitic
incidents that stem from opposition to Israel, the Anti-Defamation
League of B'nai B'rith reported Tuesday.
   So far this year, 88 out of 443 anti-Semitic incidents reported
in the United States have had an element of anti-Israeli sentiment,
according to a report by the ADL, which monitors outbreaks of
racism and anti-Semitism.
   By contrast, there were only three such incidents out of 1,018
anti-Semitic episodes reported for all of last year.
   This year's anti-Israeli incidents appeared to be prompted by
Palestinian unrest in the occupied territories, the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, the ADL report said.
   Abraham Foxman, the group's national director, said the
incidents represented ``the first time since the founding of the
state of Israel 40 years ago that there has been a significant
outbreak of Middle East-related anti-Semitic incidents in this
country.''
   The incidents included vandalism and arson attacks on
synagogues, telephone threats to Jewish organizations and other
forms of verbal harassment.
   California led all states in reports of politically motivated
anti-Semitism with 12 vandalism cases and 13 harassment incidents,
followed by Illinois, Florida, Minnesota, Massachusetts and
Pennsylvania, the ADL said.
   The figures are based on reports gathered by the ADL's 31
regional offices.
</TEXT>
