<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WelfareEntrepreneurs     05-31 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Welfare Entrepreneurs,0728</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Welfare Recipients Become Entrepreneurs in Pilot Projects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A program targeted at low-income women in
Minnesota is helping welfare recipients create their own jobs and
build successful businesses, and promoters hope its success will
spread to the rest of the country.
   ``A lot of people told me this was going to fail miserably,''
said Kathryn S. Keeley, president of the 5-year-old Women's
Economic Development Corp., which was graduating its first class of
18 fledgling entrepreneurs today.
   Under the plan, welfare recipients receive training and then
continue receiving public assistance while receiving subsidized
loans to help them start businesses ranging from cleaning companies
to hair-styling salons.
   ``The first hurdle we had to cross in this area was skepticism.
Can poor women do it?'' said Robert Friedman, president of the
Corporation for Enterprise Development.
   The organization began its first class for welfare entrepreneurs
in March under the federal Self Employment Investment
Demonstration. Keeley said she hopes 90 people will graduate by the
end of the year.
   Minnesota is the first of five states to launch the program,
which is coordinated by the private, nonprofit Corporation for
Enterprise Development in Washington, Friedman said. The other
states are Iowa, Michigan, Mississippi and New Jersey.
   The corporation persuaded federal officials to waive regulations
which reduce or eliminate benefits when recipients get jobs,
Friedman said. Participants continue receiving assistance even
after they start their own businesses so they can re-invest profits.
   At the Women's Economic Development Corp., recipients devise a
business plan, learn about marketing, financial management and
other skills and are encouraged to start thinking like
entrepreneurs.
   They can borrow up to $5,000, to be loaned in small increments
as their businesses progress at 1 percent above the prime lending
rate, said Joyce Yamamoto, who directs the organization's pilot
project known as the Self Employment Training Opportunities Program.
   Once a month for at least a year, recipients are required to
work with the organization's accountant to do bookkeeping.
   ``The whole point of that is to get them off on the right
foot,'' Ms. Yamamoto said.
   Women's Economic Development Corp. received nearly all its
current annual budget of $600,000 from foundations and other
private sources, Ms. Keeley said.
   Organizers hope to help other states begin similar projects, she
said.
   An aspiring filmmaker, one of the few men to complete the
program, said welfare recipients face challenges other
entrepreneurs don't.
   ``Most of us who have been down and out have had our self-esteem
shattered. They realized it was important to build that up,'' he
said of the program, asking not to be identified for fear it might
hurt his business.
   Promoters point out that the program isn't a cure-all for
welfare problems.
   ``People get poor for different reasons. They are going to
escape in different ways,'' Friedman reasoned.
   Only 10 percent to 15 percent of Minnesota's 57,000 AFDC
recipients are likely candidates for the program, said Stephen R.
Rhodes, planning director for the state Office of Jobs Policy.
Nationally, the percentage is 2 percent to 5 percent, he said.
   A forerunner to the current program was launched three years
ago. In that time, 22 women started businesses and three have
already repaid their loans, Ms. Keeley said.
   ``They don't hand the business to you. You have to work for
it,'' said Ellie Richardson, who has cleaned homes and businesses
most of her life and started a janitorial service in late 1986.
``They give you the right contacts. If you don't follow through,
it's your fault.''
   Ms. Richardson, who had been on and off assistance for 30 years,
is self-supporting now and employs about 10 people. ``I'm glad I'm
off. Welfare makes you feel depressed and down,'' she said.
   Before the pilot program ends in 1992, Friedman hopes to
persuade federal officials to waive permanently regulations that
bar welfare recipients who turn a business profit from keeping
their benefits while they get their companies off the ground.
   ``We need the federal government to let go a little to let it
succeed,'' Friedman said. ``I must say the Department of Health and
Human Services has been very cooperative, but right now the waiver
process is onerous.''
</TEXT>
