<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 0119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Arson     05-31 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Arson,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Shopkeepers Sentenced to Death for Arson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four shopkeepers have been sentenced to death for
arson and 49 Communist Party members disciplined for helping the
merchants defraud insurance companies, an official report said
today.
   The China Daily said the four merchants, in two cities of the
northeastern Heilongjiang province, set fire to their shops after
taking out large insurance policies obtained through bribes to
local officials.
   Five people were killed in one of the fires.
   The newspaper said two brothers, Lu Guangcai and Lu Guangde,
falsified documents in Qitaihe City to insure their stationery
store and restaurant for $224,000. Two days later, they set fire to
a bag filled with gasoline, starting a blaze that killed five
people and caused $27,000 in damage, the paper said.
   The report said Wang Shuli of Yichun City took out insurance
worth $192,000 on a hardware store he managed after the store lost
$72,000 over a 10-month period as a result of waste and
mismanagement.
   And it said Yu Xibin rented a storehouse from Wang and insured
it for $84,000, although it had only two counters and a sofa.
   The two set fire to the stores five times in May and June of
last year, damaging six nearby stores and causing $24,000 in
losses, the report said.
   The four provided local officials with high-quality cigarettes,
wine, refrigerators, motorcycles and other goods to obtain
contracts for the stores and the expensive insurance policies, it
said.
   The report did not say if the death sentences had been carried
out.
</TEXT>
