<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Soviet-Rights     05-31 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Soviet-Rights,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Media Highlighting US Human Rights Abuses</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit-Dissidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN FRIEDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet media are highlighting cases the Kremlin
perceives as U.S. human rights abuses, in an apparent bid to
counterbalance President Reagan's meeting with dissidents and
refuseniks.
   The official news agency Tass carried a critical commentary in
advance of Reagan's meeting Monday at Spaso House, quoting Deputy
Foreign Minister Vladimir Petrovsky as saying such an action ``is
hardly aimed at improving understanding between the Soviet Union
and the United States.''
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda told its readers that
although the United States is a land of scientific and
technological marvels, it is also a land of homelessness, hunger
and repression of minorities.
   On a day when news of the summit meeting dominated the pages of
the newspaper, it printed a photograph of blacks in shabby clothes
lining up for a free Thanksgiving Day meal at Lafayette Park in
Washington, D.C., noting it was across the street from the White
House.
   On the bottom of the same page, it printed a story about Leonard
Peltier, an American Indian convicted of killing two FBI agents in
1975 at the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation in South Dakota.
   Peltier's case has been cited by Soviet officials as an example
of U.S. human rights violations. Civil rights lawyer William
Kunstler said recently that the treatment of American Indians in
the United States should be raised as a human rights issue at the
summit.
   Radio Moscow in one of its newscasts Monday mentioned a May 23
report by a panel of 40 prominent Americans that said minorities in
the United States were failing to make progress in efforts to
achieve full participation ``in the life and prosperity of the
nation.''
   Tass also publicized a news conference Monday by four Americans
who came to Moscow to speak about alleged U.S. human rights abuses
involving minorities. The four ``wanted to make human rights part
of the agenda'' at the Moscow summit and provide ``a balanced
view,'' said one of the participants, lawyer Karen Parker, in an
interview with The Associated Press.
   The Tass commentary said the Soviet government is ``seriously
concerned'' about the human rights situation in the United States,
especially ``discrimination against national minorities,
persecution of people because of their political views and the
passing of death sentences on minors.''
   It also said that ideological disputes between the superpowers
are inevitable, but ``one cannot put up with the fact that the
subject of human rights is exploited for purposes of whipping up
hostility in inter-state relations, for impeding the processes of
disarmament and detente.''
   The Soviet Peace Committee was the setting for the news
conference by the four American human rights activists, but Parker
said they all paid their own way to Moscow.
   Parker and Indian rights activist Anthony Gonzales, both of San
Francisco, said that besides Peltier, the activists wanted to
publicize the human rights cases of racial minorities, the
homeless, the hungry, institutionalized disabled people, and those
refugees and asylum-seekers who have been forcibly returned to the
country from which they fled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
