<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 0202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Drugs     05-31 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Drugs,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Priest Can't Get Mrs. Reagan Interested In `Just Say Nyet'
Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.W. Canty, an American Episcopal priest working
against alcoholism and drug abuse in the Soviet Union, could not
get Nancy Reagan interested in his ``Just Say Nyet'' campaign, so
he'll try her husband.
   Canty, 41, chairman of the Soviet-U.S. Joint Conference on
Alcoholism and Drug Addiction, wants to deliver a letter to
President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev asking them
to issue a joint statement on the need to fight addictions.
   ``Alcoholism and drug addiction is an extremely serious problem
in both of our countries,'' Canty's letter says. ``May history
remember these days as a summit for sobriety.''
   One question Canty thinks Gorbachev and Reagan should address is
why the cultures in the two countries seem to spawn alcoholism, a
disease which robs both societies of their human resources.
   ``Why do these two countries share these drinking problems?''
Canty asked. In both countries, Canty thinks there is a certain
``macho'' image associated with drinking.
   Canty has spent two years working on and off in the Soviet Union
setting up the conference.
   Since 1986, Canty has established an Alcoholics Anonymous
chapter in Moscow, persuaded the Moscow city government to give him
a building for a fellowship house, taken Soviet physicians on a
tour of the United States to study alcoholism and arranged for
Americans to visit the Soviet Union.
   But the White House turned down Canty's invitation to have Mrs.
Reagan visit the site of his soon-to-be-opened fellowship house.
Since 1981, Mrs. Reagan has campaigned against drugs, adopting the
slogan ``Just Say No.''
   The fellowship house in downtown Moscow will be a place for
people to meet, read in the library and see videos. ``It will be a
club to celebrate sobriety.'' he said.
   Undeterred by the reaction of Mrs. Reagan's staff, Canty decided
to solicit help from the superpower leaders in writing.
   Canty has already eaten dinner with Gorbachev and received help
from the Soviet leaders' aides who are committed to the country's
anti-drinking policy. Since he took office, Gorbachev has raised
the drinking age from 18 to 21, reduced the number of liquor stores
and cut back on the production of alcohol.
   ``Gorbachev has challenged his people to do something but the
follow-through has been a joke,'' Canty said. The Soviets say there
are officially 4.3 million alcoholics in the country of about 284
million, but Canty thinks the figure is closer to about 10 million
_ the same as in the United States.
   The Communist Party daily Pravda reported on Nov. 15, 1987 that
there are more than 4.5 million registered alcoholics in the Soviet
Union and that about 1 million of them need compulsory care. There
has been no official estimate of the number of unregistered
alcoholics.
   Though a drug problem exists in the Soviet Union, it is far less
severe than in the United States, Canty said. Drugs like cocaine
and crack are not prevalent here, but Russian women often abuse
tranquilizers and teen-agers sniff Benzene, he said.
   Canty acknowledges that people in the United States and the
Soviet Union find his efforts to reach global peace through
sobriety somewhat off-beat. But he says he has been effective.
   ``I`ve been told we are the first non-profit joint venture,'' he
said.
   The low-budget conference is funded with money from foundations
and gifts. The Soviet government has provided in-kind help such as
donating a building and paying for its doctors to travel abroad.
Canty receives no money from the U.S. government and declines to
take a salary.
   Since 1986, Canty has made seven trips to the Soviet Union, and
he has been here since January, staying at the National Hotel, a
plush historic building overlooking the Kremlin. He operates out of
his hotel room.
   The Russians seem perplexed by his ``grassroots, Scotch-tape
operation,'' he said. ``The new party line is profit, and here we
are saying, `Do this for free,''' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
