<1ST_LINE>r i PM-StrategicBalance     05-31 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Strategic Balance,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weapons In Superpowers' Arsenals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit-Arms Negotiations Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev are talking about strategic, or long-range, nuclear arms
at their summit meeting.
   Here are the numbers of these weapons in the superpowers'
arsenals as of the end of 1987. The sources are the Defense
Department and the Natural Resources Defense Council, a private
research organization.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   INTERCONTINENTAL BALLISTIC MISSILES
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The United States has three types, 450 Minuteman IIs, 520
Minuteman IIIs and 30 MX-Peacekeepers. Total warheads, 2,310.
   The Soviet Union has 1,400 of seven types, SS11, SS13, SS17,
SS18, SS19, SS24, SS25. Total warheads, 6,846.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SUBMARINE LAUNCHED BALLISTIC MISSILES
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The United States has 256 Poseidons and 384 Tridents. Total
warheads, about 5,630.
   The Soviet Union has six types, totalling 928 missiles with
3,232 warheads.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WEAPONS CARRIED ON BOMBERS
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The United States has three types of long-range nuclear bombers,
64 B-1Bs, 241 B-52s and 56 FB111s, totalling 361. These are capable
of carrying about 5,070 warheads.
   The Soviet Union has four types of Bear bombers, totalling 155,
capable of carrying about 1,170 warheads.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TOTAL WARHEADS
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The United States has about 13,000 warheads and the Soviets have
about 11,200 warheads.
</TEXT>
