<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Jazz 1stLd-Writethru a0435 05-31 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Jazz, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0435,740</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf pvs, bgng Tuesday night, to change time
element; picks up 3rd graf pvs, One thing; In last graf, album
title ``Moscow Night'' is cq.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Brubeck to Test the Jazz Waters with the Gorbachevs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nikita Khrushchev used to say jazz gave him gas,
but no one seems to know what effect it has on Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Tonight, pianist Dave Brubeck plans to find out when he gives
the general secretary and his wife Raisa a taste of ``Take Five''
and other American jazz classics.
   One thing is for sure, says Brubeck: the Reagans like jazz. They
have chosen him to perform with his quintet at a state dinner for
the Gorbachevs at Spaso House, the U.S. ambassador's residence
where the Reagans are staying during the summit.
   ``The Reagans really seem to appreciate American music in
general. Nancy seems to know all the standards. You can see her
mouthing the words,'' the gray-haired 67-year-old Brubeck said in
an interview Monday.
   As for the president, a former Hollywood actor, Brubeck recalled
that at a Feb. 21 performance at the White House for governors,
``He told me how much he loved the big bands and how much they were
a part of American history.''
   Brubeck is no stranger to the halls of power. He was the first
jazz musician to play at the White House and has entertained every
president since John F. Kennedy.
   He met the Gorbachevs but didn't have a chance to talk to them
or play for them at the previous summit state dinner at the White
House last December. That dinner produced one of the most memorable
moments of the Washington summit _ the Gorbachevs singing along as
the American classical pianist Van Cliburn played the Russian
standard ``Moscow Nights.''
   Asked if he would follow in Van Cliburn's footsteps with the
dixieland jazz version of the song, renamed ``Midnight in Moscow,''
Brubeck said: ``We're prepared to play it if someone asks, but it's
been done so many times.''
   But in typical Brubeckian manner, if it's played, it'll be with
a twist, in five-four rhythm. ``It can be done,'' he assured a
doubting reporter.
   In honor of the occasion, Brubeck has dug up ``The Real
Ambassadors,'' a song he wrote in 1958 for a musical that featured
trumpeter Louis Armstrong running the world for a day.
   Although the Gorbachevs won't hear it because Brubeck plans to
play only an instrumental version of the song, one line speaks of
Armstrong using music to bring peace: ``The next time around, it's
a session where we jam the blues. Khrushchev pounding both his
shoes couldn't have the final say if I was king for a day.''
   Khrushchev, who pounded a shoe on a desk at the United Nations
in 1960, was no jazz lover. ``When I hear jazz, it's as if I had
gas on the stomach,'' he said in December 1963.
   At the other extreme, Yuri Andropov, the former KGB chief who
led the Soviet Union from November 1982 until his death in February
1984, was reputed to be a jazz fan.
   But although Mrs. Gorbachev has showed up at several classical
music concerts, little is known about the Kremlin couple's musical
tastes.
   ``I keep asking everyone if Gorbachev likes jazz, but no one
seems to know,'' says Brubeck's 36-year-old son Chris, who plays
bass guitar and trombone in the group. ``They all say Andropov
liked jazz and had a huge record collection.''
   The elder Brubeck, who says he's played in most countries of the
world, from ``the dance halls to all the joints'' during his
50-year career, believes jazz is a unique medium for espousing the
American ideal of freedom.
   ``To play jazz, you have to have tremendous discipline and you
are expected to use it in a free way. There's no art form that
represents America better than jazz,'' he said.
   And to many jazz lovers, there is no single jazz standard better
known than ``Take Five,'' Brubeck's 1958 tune that was the first
jazz single to go gold.
   The Wilton, Conn., resident gave Soviets who had heard him only
on Voice of America shortwave broadcasts and records a chance to
hear him in person in March and April of last year. He played 13
concerts in Moscow, Leningrad and Tallinn, the capital of Soviet
Estonia.
   The Soviet record label Melodiya plans to release a recording
from last year's tour. It has already come out in the United
States, under the title ``Moscow Night.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 0216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names SUB a0421 05-31 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names, SUB, a0421,0195</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st and 4th grafs of first item to specify that the
honorary degree Newman received was a doctorate</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Newman, awarded an honorary
doctorate by Yale University, had some advice for graduates about
the importance of uncertainty.
   ``Just try to keep yourself off balance. Never know what you're
doing the next day and you'll be all right,'' Newman said Monday
after Yale's 287th commencement.
   Newman, an actor, director and philanthropist, attended the Yale
School of Drama in 1951.
   ``In the midst of a demanding career you dedicate a large
portion of your great gifts to the service of others,'' Yale
President Benno C. Schmidt Jr. told Newman is bestowing doctorate
of humane letters on the actor.
   Newman said after the ceremony that he was ``honored, very
honored'' with the award.
   Newman will soon dedicate a summer camp for seriously ill
children that is being funded in large part by proceeds from his
food company, Newman's Own Inc. The Connecticut company gives all
its profits to charity. Yale is helping to support the camp by
providing medical services and advice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
