<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Reformers     05-31 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Reformers,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Conservatives Preventing Reformers From Attending Crucial
Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading reformer says he expects Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's liberalization drive to prevail at next month's crucial
party conference despite conservatives' success at blocking some of
its backers from attending.
   The Soviet leader's ``policies and programs are sufficiently
strong to carry the conference,'' prominent political scientist
Fyodor M. Burlatsky said Monday. He is among those who have been
excluded.
   The Communist Party conference, the first since 1941, will lay
out a a slate of policy decisions and proposals forming a blueprint
for legislative changes. It will amount to passing judgment on
Gorbachev's wide-ranging program of social and economic reforms
known as ``perestroika.''
   The selection of the 5,000 delegates to the June 28 conference
has already turned into a showdown between backers of reform and
those who seek to limit change _ often to preserve their privileges.
   Burlatsky said the conference will not name any new people to
the 300-member, policy-making Central Committee, in part to protect
the committee headed by Gorbachev from changes viewed as harmful.
   ``If elections to the party conference have become so difficult,
how do we know elections to the Central Committee won't be tied up
by some of these negative factors?'' he asked.
   Burlatsky fell with the fortunes of Nikita S. Khrushchev, the
late former premier, but resurfaced to back Gorbachev's
``perestroika'' campaign.
   He said the party's charter does not spell out procedures for
selecting delegates to party conferences: ``We are learning
democracy, finding a style as we go. It is certainly experimental.''
   Since the last party conference was in 1941, times have changed
radically and old ways of choosing delegates are no longer
relevant, the political scientist said.
   Instances where Gorbachev's backers failed to get elected as
delegates were sometimes the result of individual party officials
striking the backers' names from lists forwarded by factories,
institutes and local party organizations, Burlatsky said.
   ``There were cases where regional secretaries themselves, for
formalistic reasons, withdrew certain names,'' he said, using a
term that suggests conservatism.
   Burlatsky; historian Yuri Afanasyev; and Tatyana Zaslavskaya, a
prominent sociologist are among those turned down by regional party
authorities after being selected by their local groups as
candidates to attend the conference.
   Exclusion of such noted backers of reform prompted
demonstrations in Moscow and Leningrad over the weekend and
accusations that the selection process was rigged.
   Ms. Zaslavskaya criticized the delegate selection process at a
news conference last week, saying the choices had not in every case
been beneficial for the fate of Gorbachev's reforms.
   Burlatsky joked that his own absence would take its toll at the
party conference, ``but I don't think it is dangerous to
perestroika.''
   Among the proposals are suggestions for jury trials; relaxation
of restrictions on religion; reform of the criminal justice system;
limits on the political terms of party officials, and some formal
sanctioning of the informal groups springing up in the Soviet
Union, which Burlatsky said now number about 30,000. The groups,
which are unofficial but sometimes tolerated, have come together to
press causes like environmental protection and individual freedoms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0043 </DOCNO>
