<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PrivateEyeCrane     05-31 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Private Eye Crane,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING To Correct Cycle Designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wife Of Congressman Works As Sleuth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Arlene Crane mingles with some of the
seedier characters in the nation's capital, it's all in a day's
work.
   As the wife of Rep. Philip Crane, R-Ill., she does what is
expected of a congressional spouse: showing up at parties and
receptions, posing for pictures and answering reporters' questions.
   But the mother of eight has another life in what seems like
another world.
   Arlene Crane is a private detective.
   ``So much for stereotypes,'' she said, laughing about the
contrast of life in the public eye and work as a private eye. ``I
guess I must be a maverick.''
   ``But if my life had to revolve strictly around Phil, waiting
for him to come home every night, I think I'd go crazy,'' she
added. ``You have to have diversion, and I get plenty of it.''
   Since graduating from a detective school in suburban Washington
seven years ago, Mrs. Crane said she has handled at least 50 cases
ranging from the search for a missing person to gathering evidence
for a divorce case.
   ``It can be dirty. It's often seedy. But it's always
challenging,'' she said recently. ``It's also amazing who you have
to consort with.
   ``I could recall a few unsavory characters along the way. But
you have to do it. ... If you don't ingratiate yourself to some of
these low-lives, there are times you just won't get the answers you
need.''
   She said another part of the job, surveillance, dispels any
impression that detective work is glamorous.
   ``In one case, the husband knew his wife was having an affair,
and he was certainly right. We got the goods,'' she said. ``But it
was 23{ hours straight, sitting in a car _ not getting out, not
even to go to the bathroom.
   ``I'll never forget it as long as I live. In fact, I don't think
I'll ever wear those clothes again.''
   Mrs. Crane began as a full-time detective with an agency when
she received her diploma. She now works part time as a freelance
investigator, often for lawyers, because she wanted more freedom.
   She was reluctant to talk about most of her recent
investigations, largely background checks, but said her clients
never include members of Congress.
   Does she carry a gun?
   ``I could, but I don't. I can't even think of a time when I
needed to,'' she said. ``Ironically, you can't carry one in D.C.,
period, unless you get a special dispensation and, even then, it
has to be seen. So I'd look a little silly going to a reception
with a holster on my belt.''
   Crane said he is proud of his wife's atypical occupation, but
also finds humor in the situation.
   ``I bet I'm the only guy on the Hill who wouldn't get mad if his
wife was caught standing outside some stranger's hotel room,'' he
said recently.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
