<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese     05-31 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Leaves Open Possibility Of Resignation Prior To Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III says he may
resign before the November election, but not before he has a chance
to ``set the record straight.''
   Meese said in an interview broadcast Monday night that before he
steps aside, he wants to respond to the allegations that have been
made against him concerning his ties to scandal-plagued Wedtech
Corp. and a $1 billion Iraqi pipeline project.
   An independent counsel who has been investigating Meese for the
past year is expected to issue a report in several weeks. Meese is
not expected to be indicted but the report will raise questions
about his ethical conduct, according to sources familiar with the
probe.
   Those questions will be investigated by the Justice Department's
Office of Professional Responsibility, in an examination that could
continue for months.
   Once he has had an opportunity to respond to the independent
counsel's report and ``set the record straight,'' Meese said, ``my
own personal plans are going to be the deciding point as to when
the proper time is to step down.''
   He said that time could be next Jan. 20, when President Reagan
leaves office, or ``sometime before that.''
   Meese was interviewed on Cable News Network's ``Larry King
Live'' show. When asked by former White House aide Pat Buchanan,
who was guest host on the show, whether he might resign before
Labor Day, Meese replied: ``I don't think I'd rule anything in or
anything out.''
   Meese refused to discuss any details of his newly disclosed
meeting with Vice President George Bush earlier this month.
   But he said, ``If I were to quit now, for example, it would be a
real liability (to Bush) because people would say there was
something wrong.''
   Meese told Bush he would do nothing to hurt the vice president's
campaign for president, Bush said Monday under questioning by
reporters at his summer home in Kennebunkport, Maine.
   Meese blamed the news media for polling results showing the
public views him unfavorably, and promised a strong counter-attack
once the independent counsel issues his report.
   In the wake of a ``one-sided barrage from the media...I'm
surprised, actually, it wasn't worse than that,'' Meese said of the
poll results.
   An ABC-Washington Post poll last week showed a majority of the
public thinks Meese is not doing a good job as attorney general.
   Meese predicted adverse public opinion would change ``when I'm
unleashed'' following the issuance of independent counsel James
McKay's report.
   The attorney general also said ``it wasn't a crippling blow''
when two of his top aides resigned March 29 in protest of his
continued tenure at the Justice Department.
   Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns and criminal division chief
William Weld quit out of concern that Meese was hurting the Justice
Department's operations, morale and public image.

</TEXT>
