<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Unemployment     05-31 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Unemployment,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Unemployment Rate Falls to 2.6 Percent in April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's jobless rate fell to 2.6 percent in
April, down from 3 percent for the same month last year, the
government reported today.
   Japan's unemployment rate would be about twice as high if
calculated by Western methods.
   The seasonally adjusted jobless rate for April was the same as
for March of this year, the Management and Coordination Agency said
in its monthly report.
   Government officials said April's figure reflected a continuing
steady economic recovery since last summer following a major shift
in Japan's economic structure. The nation has been pushing domestic
demand expansion over previously export-led growth.
   The number of Japanese with jobs in April was 60.38 million, an
increase of 1.08 million over the same month last year, according
to the report, which was presented to the Cabinet today.
   It was the first time that the number of employed Japanese
topped 60 million, the report said. At the same time, there were
1.66 million people out of work.
   Japan's population is about 121 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
