<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Floods     05-31 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Floods,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Death Toll At 41 in Week Of Flooding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a week of flooding in
northern Bangladesh has claimed 41 lives and left about 15,000
people homeless, a Bengali language newspaper reported today.
   The Khabar newspaper said all the deaths occurred in the Sylhet
district, about 62 miles north of Dhaka, but did not give details.
   A Sylhet district government official told The Associated Press
by telephone that only 10 deaths had been reported.
   But the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that
at least 50,000 people had been trapped by flood waters in the
district.
   The flooding has been caused by the Brahmaputra river bursting
its banks. The Brahmaputra flows through Bangladesh and into the
Bay of Bengal.
   Local newspapers say at least 1.5 million people have had their
homes or crops inundated by the floodwaters.
   Flooding is common at this time of year, when the monsoon rains
begin, in this nation of 105 million people. The government says at
least 1,500 people were killed in floods last year.
</TEXT>
