<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Fiji-Arms     05-31 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fiji-Arms,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australia Seizes Huge Arms Cache Bound For Fiji</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs officers said today that they
seized a huge cache of weapons bound for Fiji that could have
started a small war in the South Pacific nation, scene of two coups
last year.
   The cache, including submachine guns, automatic rifles, hand
grenades, mortars and anti-tank mines, arrived on a ship from Port
Hodeidah in North Yemen via Sri Lanka and Singapore, said Customs
spokesman Alastair Wilson.
   He said the shipment, discovered Monday in Sydney's downtown
Darling Harbor, was bound for Lautoka, in eastern Fiji, stronghold
of deposed Prime Minister Timoci Bavadra.
   A Foreign Ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said all the weapons were Soviet-made.
   ``It has nasty connotations,'' the official said.
   News reports said it was the biggest illegal haul of military
equipment in Australian history. Wilson said consigment papers
listed the contents of a more than one-ton container as used
machinery.
   ``Customs officers located the container, opened a number of
sealed boxes, and instead of used machinery they found weapons,''
he told a news conference.
   Wilson said an army demolition squad was brought in to remove
the weapons and officials were doing an inventory. He said the
shipment contained enough arms to have ``started a small war in
Fiji.''
   News reports said the consignment was intercepted after being
loaded onto the french ship Capitaine Cook. The reports said the
captain and his crew were being questioned but had not been
arrested.
   The Foreign Ministry official said authorities in Fiji, which is
about 2,000 miles northeast of Sydney, had been informed of the
seizure.
   Australian officials said they had no immediate indication of
for whom the weapons were bound.
   In Suva, the Fijian capital, authorities expressed surprise at
the seizure. Bavadra, who was ousted in a coup a year ago, was not
available for comment.
   There has been no armed resistance by the majority Indian
community to the coups, which Sitiveni Rabuka said he staged to
protect the rights of ethnic Fijians, who comprise a 43 percent
minority of the islands' 715,000 people.
   Bavadra's Indian-dominated elected government was ousted on May
14, 1987, just one month after it came to power.
   Rabuka staged a second coup four months later, claiming the
interim administration had not settled the issue of Fijian
political dominance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
