<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChainSawKilling     05-31 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chain Saw Killing,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Will Focus On Death And Degradation Of Male Homosexual
Prostitute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Contents of the following, especially of 7th graf, may be
objectionable to some readers</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The degradation and death of a teen-age
homosexual prostitute will be the focus in the murder trial of a
former university professor who is accused of chopping up his
victim with a chain saw.
   Tracy Leroy Nute, a homeless 18-year-old from Kansas City, Mo.,
died on Aug. 20. He was shot to death in a West Hollywood apartment
six months after leaving home saying he was going to California to
be a movie star.
   After his death, police say, someone took a chain saw to Nute's
body and hacked it into several pieces, later scattering the parts
around California.
   The prosecution in the trial scheduled to begin today seeks to
prove that the gun that killed Nute and the chain saw with which he
was dismembered were wielded by Max Bernard Franc.
   Franc, 58, a former political science professor at Fresno State
University, denies being the killer and blames a man named Terry
Adams.
   But the prosecutor, Deputy District Attorney Sterling Norris,
says a lengthy investigation of men named Terry Adams only
convinced him that Franc invented the person.
   Franc, who has no criminal record, was arrested Aug. 29 after he
returned a chain saw to a rental company with bits of flesh and
blood in its inner workings.
   Franc, who lived in Fresno, also maintained an apartment in West
Hollywood.
   Pieces of Nute's body were found near freeways in Fresno and
Valencia, 200 miles apart.
   Superior Court Judge John H. Reid has ruled that jurors in the
trial can be shown some photos of the severed body parts. But he
said other pictures are too gory to show jurors, who might be so
inflamed by them they would convict the defendant without weighing
other evidence.
   Norris, scheduled to deliver his opening statement today, said
he will try to prove through analysis of decomposition time that
Franc refrigerated portions of the body before discarding them.
   He contends Franc killed Nute in a homosexual rage and
dismembered the body to avoid detection.
   According to counselors in the homosexual community, Nute
quickly abandoned his dreams of stardom and wound up working the
streets of West Hollywood as a homosexual prostitute. He dyed his
dark hair blond and wore it in spikes.
   Franc, a native of DePere, Wis., has acknowledged knowing Nute
and said he once loaned him money. But he denies killing the youth.
   Franc resigned his teaching post after his arrest.
</TEXT>
