<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KayakRefugees     05-31 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kayak Refugees,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Flees Cuba in Kayak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who sailed a canvas-covered kayak from
Cuba survived stormy seas and a water spout that broke their
15-foot vessel's frame before being rescued by a fishing boat,
officials said.
   ``I don't know how in the world they made it across the ocean,''
said Don Gurgiolo, captain of a charter fishing boat that rescued
the couple off Upper Matecumbe Key, near Islamorada. ``It was
awfully rough.''
   The fishermen called the Coast Guard to pick up Juan Ramirez
Gomez and his wife, Regina Gilda Sabina Mendez, who were bobbing in
6-foot seas when they were found Sunday morning, 38 hours after
they set sail east of Havana.
   Coast Guard Petty Officer Glenn Gerber said he was surprised the
couple had survived the more than 100-mile voyage.
   ``It was not a real seaworthy vessel,'' Gerber said.
   The couple said they left Cuba on Friday night in a kayak loaded
with drinking water, a searchlight, jackets, a compass and other
supplies.
   After they were taken aboard the Gonfishin 5 passengers on the
charter gave them food and clothing, Gurgiolo said.
   ``She got on the boat, dried off her Bible and praised God,''
the captain said.
   The two were being held today at the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service's Krome Avenue detention center in Miami.
</TEXT>
