<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   05-31 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0494 ,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Stocks Climb</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout with final closing, comments, no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar lost ground after opening higher
against the Japanese yen in Tokyo today, while stocks gained for
the second consecutive day.
   After opening at 125.21 yen, up 0.23 yen, the dollar lost
strength and closed the day at 124.80 yen, down 0.18 yen.
   ``The dollar ranged between 124.77 and 125.28 yen, sandwiched
between buy and sell orders,'' said an exchange dealer with a major
Tokyo commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``The dollar comes under selling pressure when it goes above the
125-yen level, and buy orders start coming in when it falls below
that level,'' he said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained a strong 260.60 points Monday, added
another 193.60 points, or 0.71 percent, to finish the day's trading
at 27,416.70.
   ``Share prices rose substantially just before the end of the
afternoon session, led by large-capital issues, such as steels and
shipbuildings,'' said Hitoshi Otani of Wako Securities.
   Investors are now less worried about the U.S. econony, Otani
said. ``Fears about inflation and a rise in the U.S. official
discount rate have lessened among investors,'' he said.
   With its rallies on Monday and today, the market erased the big
loss suffered on Saturday, when the Nikkei index tumbled 327.99
points in a half-day session.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 1.7 billion shares,
up from 1 billion shares on Monday.
   Advancing issues included automobiles and precision machineries.
Textiles, drugs and financials also were higher, while some
electricals and constructions lost ground.
</TEXT>
