<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 0459EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Decaturs     05-31 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Decaturs,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Hero, Wife, Buried Side-By-Side After 168 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A duel took Susan Wheeler Decatur's heroic
husband from her 168 years ago and fate kept their remains apart
until now.
   Mrs. Decatur's resting place was dedicated Monday in a church
yard next to her husband's grave. Three students from an elementary
school named for Stephen Decatur participated in a wreath-laying
ceremony attended by about 100 people.
   Decatur was one of the young American Navy's heroes, lionized
for his feats of daring against North African pirates and for a
victory over a British warship during the War of 1812.
   After he was killed by a duelist's bullet on March 22, 1820,
Mrs. Decatur lived 40 years without him. She then lay buried for
128 years in Washington, D.C., while he rested beside his parents
at St. Peter's Episcopal Church here.
   Through the efforts of Georgetown University, the remains of
Mrs. Decatur were removed from a university-owned cemetery, placed
in a mahogany coffin and on May 19 reburied beside her husband, who
had been buried under a 30-foot-tall granite column.
   Monday's ceremony coincided with the opening of a small Decatur
exhibit at the Philadelphia Maritime Museum. Decatur was a native
of Philadelphia, the son of a Revolutionary War naval officer who
was reared among the ships and shipbuilders of the city's late
18th-century waterfront.
   His most intrepid act was his Feb. 7, 1804, burning of the
captured American frigate Philadelphia in the harbor of Tripoli, in
modern-day Libya.
   Then 25 and disguised as a Maltese sailor, Decatur headed a
raiding party that sailed into the heavily guarded harbor. They
boarded, set fires and destroyed the frigate, which had been seized
six months earlier by Tripoli warships.
   Two years later, Decatur married Susan Wheeler, the daughter of
the mayor of Norfolk, Va., and a noted belle of that town and
Baltimore. She was said to be well educated, charming and pretty,
but little else is known about her.
   They were childless and had been married for 14 years when
Decatur died in the duel at age 41.
   Decatur was challenged by Capt. James Barron, whom Decatur had
criticized after a ship Barron commanded was severely damaged by a
British warship in 1807.
   The men stood about 8 yards apart in Bladensburg, Md., outside
Washington and fired a pair of ornate, long-barreled silver
pistols. Barron was wounded in the hip but recovered.
   Decatur also was shot in the hip but the bullet traveled into
his abdomen, and he died in his home that evening.
   Mrs. Decatur eventually settled near the campus of what is now
Georgetown University and in 1837 gave the struggling Catholic
college $7,000.
   She died July 21, 1860, and was buried in a college graveyard
that was forgotten until the ground was prepared for a new building
in 1954, according to Charles F. Meng, Georgetown's vice president
for administration. Her remains were moved to another college
cemetery, where they stayed until she was reburied alonside her
husband.
   ``All of the family, and there are quite a number of us, feel
very good about this,'' said Maria Decatur Garnett, 67, of Kittery
Point, Maine, a great-great-great-niece of Decatur. ``It was a
romantic marriage. They were extremely romantic and very handsome.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
