<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 0509EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CollegeChemicals     05-31 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-College Chemicals,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tons of Toxic and Explosive Chemicals Found At College</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tons of old chemicals that have turned toxic and
potentially explosive were being removed from two buildings at
Hunter College, where they were like ``a time bomb'' in science
laboratories, officials said.
   The discovery of the chemicals, some up to 30 years old, forced
the college to close Thomas Hunter Hall and the North Building on
May 20, city Department of Environmental Protection and school
officials said Monday.
   Among the chemicals found were 25 canisters of explosive and
highly reactive chemicals, including ether and picric acid, and 90
canisters of gases, some of which may be poisonous, said department
spokeswoman Joan Paylo.
   ``Picric acid, when it crystallizes, can be as explosive as
dynamite in small quantities. It is feared throughout labs when it
is old,'' Ms. Paylo said, calling the chemicals ``a time bomb.''
   College officials learned about the chemicals' presence when the
Fire Department discovered ether during an inspection May 11,
college spokesman Robin Elliott said.
   Subsequent investigations revealed tons of expired chemicals in
the buildings' science laboratories and storage rooms, Ms. Paylo
said.
   So far, the spokeswoman said, 135 to 140 rooms have been
searched for dangerous chemicals. A hazardous waste removal
contractor planned to search all 500 rooms in both buildings today,
she said.
   The police bomb squad and individual contractors have removed
some of the dangerous substances, Elliott and Ms. Paylo said.
   ``Some of the gas is still on the premises because it is
difficult to find a contractor who will take it,'' she said.
   The college's policy had been ``to leave the regulation of
materials to individual researchers in the labs,'' Elliott said.
The discovery of the chemicals ``shows that you can't leave this
important safety-related area to individual people.''
   Classes at the college ended for the summer two weeks ago.
</TEXT>
