<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 0523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-31 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>May Goes Out Like A Lion As Snow Falls in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Spring snow fell in parts of Montana today as rain showers and
thunderstorms dampened much of the nation after spawning floods and
tornadoes in New Mexico.
   Rain over western Montana turned into snow in higher elevations,
and as much as 3 inches of snow was expected to fall above the
6,000-foot level. A snow advisory was posted for the mountains of
southwest Montana.
   Rain showers and thunderstorms fell from the Nebraska Panhandle
to the Texas Panhandle and from eastern Wyoming to eastern New
Mexico. Showers and thunderstorms also extended from northeast New
York state to central New England, and over southern Florida.
   Heavy thunderstorms Monday triggered flooding near Clovis and
Portales, N.M. Advisories warning of local flooding were posted for
southeast Colorado.
   Near Hartman and Holly, Colo., it was estimated that up to 3{
inches of rain fell in two hours. More than 3 inches fell in Clovis
in six hours overnight.
   Tornadoes touched down south of Clovis and southeast of Portales
on Monday evening, but there were no reports of injuries or major
damage.
   In addition, Clovis was hit by hail the size of golf balls.
Hail, often accompanied by gusty winds, also was reported in
Haxtun, Colo.; Bowman, N.D.; near Edgemont, S.D.; at Hill City,
S.D.; near Alliance, Neb.; and at Syracuse, Kan.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
Rockies to the upper Missouri Valley and the Great Plains from
North Dakota into western Texas; rain over the northern Pacific
Coast; showers from northeast New York state to northern New
England; and scattered thunderstorms over central and southern
Florida.
   Temperatures were expected to reach 90 to 95 degrees from
southern New England to the Carolinas, from Georgia to the lower
Mississippi Valley, and in the Tennessee Valley, the lower Ohio
Valley, southern Texas and the desert Southwest; the 50s and 60s
from the Rockies to Nevada, the Pacific Northwest and along the
central Pacific Coast; the 70s and 80s in the rest of the country.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 33
degrees at Butte, Mont., and Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 80
degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 fair; Boston 59 foggy; Buffalo 64 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 65 fair; Cincinnati 62 fair; Cleveland 64
fair; Detroit 67 fair; Miami 76 cloudy; New York 67 cloudy;
Philadelphia 72 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 68 fair; Portland, Maine
51 foggy; Washington 71 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 74 windy; Chicago 69 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
75 partly cloudy; Denver 57 partly cloudy; Des Moines 68 fair;
Indianapolis 72 fair; Kansas City 71 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 74
partly cloudy; Nashville 65 fair; New Orleans 70 fair; St. Louis 73
fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 48 fair; Anchorage 52 cloudy; Las Vegas 59
fair; Los Angeles 57 fair; Phoenix 70 fair; Salt Lake City 43
cloudy; San Diego 59 fair; San Francisco 54 fair; Seattle 51 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 63 foggy; Toronto 64 fair.
