<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Bishop     05-31 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Bishop,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elderly Catholic Bishop Released From Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 80-year-old Roman Catholic bishop jailed since
1982 for ordaining priests outside of the official
Communist-controlled church has been released, an official said
today.
   Bishop Fan Xueyan, also known as Joseph Fan, was released two or
three months ago from the Shijiazhuang Jail in Hebei province, just
south of Beijing, a Hebei Justice Department official said in
response to a question.
   The official gave his name only as Li. He said he did not know
why Fan was released, his present whereabouts or the state of his
health.
   The Vatican ordained Fan bishop of Baoding in Hebei province in
1951, shortly before China's new Communist government ordered the
Chinese Catholic church to break with the Vatican in the name of
anti-imperialism.
   The officially sanctioned Catholic Patriotic Association that
was then formed rejects the authority of the pope and ordains its
own bishops. Hundreds of Catholic clerics and laypeople who refused
to support the association were arrested in the 1950s and many have
been released only in the past 10 years.
   Fan, among them, was arrested in 1958 and spent 15 years in jail.
   He was arrested again in 1982 and sentenced to 10 years in jail
for allegedly maintaining ties with the Vatican and ordaining
priests.
   The government, which under senior leader Deng Xiaoping has
alternated between relaxation and severity in its policy toward
religious dissidents, has shown leniency this year to several
elderly Catholic clerics.
   China's most famous Catholic dissident, Shanghai Bishop Gong
Pingmei, also known as Ignatius Kung, was allowed to fly to the
United States this month for medical treatment. He had been jailed
from 1955-85 and parole restrictions were lifted only this year.
   The Rev. Zhu Hongshen, also known as Vincent Chu, was paroled
from jail in February so he could receive medical care. Zhu, who is
believed to be about 72, had been imprisoned from 1955 to 1979 and
was arrested again in 1981 for alleged subversive activities.
   China's official Catholic church claims more than 3 million
members. An unknown number of Catholics remain loyal to the Vatican
and worship is illegal ``house churches.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
