<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Profit-taking pushed the U.S. dollar lower against
most foreign currencies in European trading early today. Gold
bullion rose.
   The dollar fell in moderately active dealings as market players
took profits on the currency's gains Monday, traders said.
   A Rome trader said there was no fundamental reason for Monday's
rise other than the closure of the London and New York markets for
national holidays.
   Mid-morning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday,
were:
   _1.7264 West German marks, down from 1.7270
   _1.4398 Swiss francs, down from 1.4415
   _5.8005 French francs, down from 5.8025
   _1.9317 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9335
   _1,278.50 Italian lire, down from 1,280.00
   _1.2366 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2378
   Against the trend, the dollar rose compared to the British
pound, which slipped to $1.8443 from $1.8478. The pound has been
declining steadily over the past few days.
   The dollar closed in Tokyo at 124.80 Japanese yen, down from
Monday's close of 124.98 yen. A trader said the dollar came under
selling pressure above the 125-yen level.
   In London trading later today, the dollar was holding steady at
125 yen.
   London's major bullion dealers fixed a recommended gold price at
mid-morning of $454 a troy ounce, up from $452 on Friday. London
bullion markets were closed Monday for a public holiday.
   Gold also traded at a bid of $454 in Zurich, up from late
Monday's rate of $452.50.
   Earlier, gold closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $455.80, up from
$454.31.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid of $6.58 a troy
ounce, down 1 cent from late Friday. Silver cost $6.57 in Zurich on
Monday.
