<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 0742EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cuba-Rights     05-31 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Rights,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Cross Visits Prisoners in Cuba, U.N. Team to Study Human
Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Red Cross officials have arrived in Cuba to
visit political prisoners and investigate prison conditions for the
first time since Fidel Castro came to power 29 years ago, an
organization spokesman said today.
   Carlos Bauverd, spokesman for the Geneva-based International
Committee of the Red Cross, said the team arrived in Havana on
Monday and hoped to begin visiting prisoners today.
   Cuba is believed to be the third Soviet ally to permit the Red
Cross to visit prisoners. Poland and Afghanistan have already done
so.
   The officials, including one doctor, hoped to visit every
political prisoner in the Communist country during their stay,
expected to last about one month, Bauverd told The Associated Press.
   The delegation planned to visit all of Cuba's prisons, Bauverd
said. Cuban authorities say there are 15.
   Bauverd said Cuban officials had agreed to the standard Red
Cross procedures of visiting prisoners without witnesses and
reserving the right to repeat visits in the future.
   He said the Red Cross would not have an exact number of
political prisoners in Cuba until after the visit.
   However, according to published reports, the Cuban government
has said the Red Cross would be allowed to visit 323 prisoners,
described as ``counter-revolutionaries,'' or state-security
prisoners.
   Bauverd said the Red Cross team would give a confidential report
to the Cuban government after the visit and that its contents would
not be made public under Red Cross policy.
   In a related development, the United Nations announced today the
composition of a team of delegates from its Human Rights Commission
who are to visit Cuba later this year.
   The six-member team will be headed by the commission chairman,
Alioune Sene of Senegal. It includes delegates from Bulgaria,
Colombia, Ireland, Nigeria and the Philippines, U.N. spokeswoman
Therese Gastaut told a weekly briefing.
   Ms. Gastaut said a date for their visit had not been set. Sene
said in March that the visit would probably take place in July or
August.
   The Human Rights Commission decided at its annual meeting
earlier this year to accept an invitation from Castro's government
to send a delegation to Cuba to investigate the human rights
situation there and report back to next year's commission, which
begins in February.
   The decision followed allegations by the United States and some
international organizations, including Amnesty International, of
human rights violations in Cuba, such as torture and mistreatment
of political prisoners.
   Cuba, which was an observer to the commission last year, was
elected last week to sit on the 1989 commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
