<2ND_LINE>PM-Money Found,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$90,000 Found in Mini-Storage Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOODLETTSVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a storage company
discovered a suitcase crammed with $90,000 in cash in a rental
compartment after the renter stopped paying the monthly fees,
police said.
   ``It's difficult to understand why somebody would not pay a $45
monthly fee and leave $90,000 lying around unless something
suspicious was involved,'' Lt. Leon Kimble of the Nashville Police
Department's armed robbery division said Sunday.
   In December, a man rented the garage-like storage unit
apparently under a fake name and address, police said. Company
log-in sheets show no one has visited the unit since Dec. 18, two
days after it was rented.
   When the renter became three months late on his rent, the
company sent him a letter, but it was returned as undeliverable.
   ``When your 90 days late on your rent, they send you a
registered letter advising you that if you don't pay, they will
inventory the stored items and auction them off at public sale,''
Kimble said.
   On Sunday, the owner of the storage business unlocked the unit.
   ``He found a suitcase with a little over $90,000 in wrapped $10
and $20 bills,'' Kimble said. ``It was really filled up.''
   The unit also contained a police radio scanner, an empty plastic
cooler and three or four hampers full of adult and children's
clothing, Kimble said.
   Police say the money will be held in the department's property
room until the rightful owner is found.
</TEXT>
