<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon     05-31 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike Protests Car Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks, schools, restaurants, gas stations
and other businesses closed today in Christian east Beirut's Rmaeil
district to protest a car bombing that killed 20 people and wounded
78.
   Christian militia leaders blamed Monday's bombing on Syria.
Police estimated the car that blew up in a crowded street in Rmaeil
was packed with more than 200 pounds of TNT.
   Charred corpses wrapped in nylon bags were turned over to the
victims' relatives at the St. Georges' Greek Orthodox hospital for
burial, police said.
   ``The victims will be buried separately because they come from
different villages and areas,'' said a police spokesman, who cannot
be identified under standing regulations.
   He said the Lebanese Forces, the main Christian militia, had
banned a mass funeral, adding: ``They don't want a large crowd
gathered at one place. It will be too tempting a target for another
terrorist attack.''
   The bomb exploded about 500 yards from an office of Christian
President Amin Gemayel's Phalange Party. It shattered facades of
eight apartment buildings, badly damaged 20 others and wrecked at
least 30 cars.
   The bombing came four days after Syrian troops moved into the
slums of south Beirut, ending three weeks of bloody clashes between
Shiite Moslem militias in which nearly 300 people were killed and
1,000 wounded.
   The Lebanese Forces blamed Syria for the bombing.
   Karim Pakradouni, the militia's second in command, told a news
conference: ``The day before yesterday (Saturday), we received the
propaganda message. Today (Monday) we received the bloody message.''
   He referred to a statement Saturday by Information Minister
Mohammed Salman of Syria, who said presidential elections in
Lebanon would only be possible this summer if the Lebanese Forces
withdrew from east Beirut.
   Syria deployed about 2,400 troops in the slums of south Beirut
on Friday and Saturday to end street battles between the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah and the Syrian-supported Amal militias.
   The police spokesman said about 40 percent of south Beirut's
estimated 250,000 population who fled the fighting had returned to
the devastated area since the Syrians moved in to enforce a
cease-fire.
   Government buses resumed services in the area today after
bulldozers removed earth barricades used by the feuding factions
for combat positions.
   In December 1985, Gemayel torpedoed a Syrian-brokered peace
treaty intended to end Lebanon's civil war. Pakradouni maintained
Syria wants the Lebanese Forces out of east Beirut to facilitate
the election of a pro-Syrian president and to extend Syria's
control over the whole country.
   Syrian forces now control Moslem west Beirut, most of the
capital's southern slums and Lebanon's eastern and northern
provinces. Most of Lebanon's Moslems, who have been at war with the
Christians since 1975, are backed by Syria.
</TEXT>
