<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Scouts-Statue     05-31 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scouts-Statue,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scouts Want To Turn George Washington Around</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a group of Cub Scouts set out to lay a
wreath at the foot of George Washington's statue, they didn't
expect him to return their salute. But at least he could have
looked their way.
   Members of Pack 469 headed out to the statue in a plaza at the
Brooklyn entrance of the Williamsburg Bridge, where Washington sits
atop his horse, and prepared to salute the nation's first president.
   They found themselves saluting the tail end of the horse.
   It seems the horse and rider face the bridge and Manhattan,
rather than Brooklyn.
   Assistant Cubmaster Thomas Youngfleisch of Pack 469
characterized the situation as embarrassing and said the 800
members of Brooklyn's Dawn Star District of the Boy Scouts of
America will attempt to get the president and his steed turned
around.
   Next year marks the 200th anniversary of Washington taking the
presidential oath in Manhattan, and District Commissioner Reggie
Regula said the Founding Father should be allowed to take a good
look at Brooklyn for the occasion.
   Regula said the Scouts would keep the area surrounding the
35-foot statue clean if the city turned it around. City officials
are contemplating the offer.
</TEXT>
