<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Party     05-31 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Party,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegates Demand ``General Overhaul'' Of The Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates at a national Communist
Party conference today demanded ``a general overhaul'' of the party
and replacement of those leaders who have led the country into its
worst economic and social crisis in postwar history.
   ``The party needs a general overhaul, and that process has to
start with the presidium (Politburo) of the Central Committee,''
Boro Avramovic, a delegate from the largest republic of Serbia,
said during the third day of the conference.
   Other delegates blamed their leaders for failing to implement
changes to ease the nation's crisis.
   ``It is unlikely that those people who have led us into this
crisis will be able to bring us out of it,'' said Rade Milicevic,
another Serbian delegate.
   Yugoslavia has been wrestling with a $21 billion foreign debt
and unsuccessful attempts to lower its 170 percent inflation and 15
percent unemployment.
   The government Saturday announced austerity measures _ including
an almost 24 percent devaluation of the national currency and
lifting of price controls _ to combat the economic crisis. But
growing labor unrest in protest of the new program is threatening
the current Communist government.
   Luka Miletic, a delegate from Zagreb, said the Yugoslav people
``increasingly insist'' that the entire Communist leadership should
be replaced for failing to implement the necessary reforms.
   Several delegates today called for a special party congress to
be held by the end of this year in order to replace the current
leadership.
   ``We don't need a special congress,'' Zvonimir Hrabar, head of
the state-run trade unions, said today. ``What we need is action,''
he added.
   Party conferences are largely advisory in nature and are
intended to help the ruling party deal with problems arising
between two party congresses. Party congresses, held every four
years in Yugoslavia, have broad powers to make changes in personnel
and party organization.
   Vilma Mancek, from Yugoslavia's economically most advanced
republic of Slovenia, opposed calls for a special congress, saying
it would be ``a waste of time and money.''
   ``Those who demand a special congress should have the courage to
propose the replacement of the party presidium,'' she said, ``since
the Central Committee has the power to recall members of the
presidium'' without holding a special congress.
   ``Young people are reluctant to join the Communist party because
they have no confidence in our organization,'' said Metka Tekavcic,
a Slovenian delegate.
   Party members account for less than 10 percent of the country's
population of 23 million, and their number is rapidly dropping.
   The official Communist publication Komunist said recently that
50 percent of Yugoslavia's young generation shows repulsion toward
party membership, compared with 10 percent seven years ago.
   Komunist attributed this to the general disillusionment with the
party after nearly 10 years of economic decline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
