<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     05-31 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Moving Up On Bush In Utah</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis has has virtually
erased the lead held by Republican George Bush in the predominantly
GOP state, a poll indicates.
   The poll, published in Monday's Salt Lake Tribune shows Bush
with a 3-point lead over Dukakis, well within the poll's 4.4
percent margin of potential sampling error. Two months ago,
pollster J. Roy Bardsley said, Bush held a 21-point lead over
Dukakis.
   The Bardsley research organization asked 490 people by telephone
whether they supported Dukakis or Bush. In all, 42 percent favored
Bush, 39 percent favored Dukakis and 19 percent were undecided.
   In late March, the survey showed that 55 percent favored Bush,
34 percent liked Dukakis and 11 percent were undecided.
   Bardsley said the main difference between the two polls is the
switch of independent voters to Dukakis. Independents favored Bush
by a 5-to-4 margin in March, but the latest poll shows independents
support Dukakis by a 5-to-3 ratio.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Alabama Delegation To Dukakis: Pick a Southerner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic members of Alabama's congressional
delegation, still lukewarm in their support for Michael Dukakis,
say the Masachusetts governor's chances at the White House would be
greatly enhanced by picking a Southern running mate.
   Rep. Tom Bevill, D-Ala., said he told Dukakis last week that to
win the South in November he would need a Southerner on the ticket,
preferably Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia or Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of
Tennessee.
   ``I gave him some good advice, and I hope he takes it,'' Bevill
said.
   All seven Democratic members of Alabama's congressional
delegation expressed similar sentiments when asked how Dukakis, who
is closing in on the Democratic nomination, can capture Southern
electoral votes.
   ``I would hope he would seriously consider Sam Nunn,'' said Sen.
Richard Shelby, D-Ala. Shelby, a member of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, said Nunn's experience on defense issues would
neutralize Dukakis' perceived weaknesses in the area.
   ``That's an area in which Dukakis is lacking experience,
knowledge and maybe a vision,'' Shelby said. ``It would be a vacuum
that the senior senator from Georgia could fill.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Libertarian Candidate Applauds Tax Defeat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ron Paul, the Libertarian candidate
for president, says the local activity that helped defeat a
proposed school tax increase in Fort Collins is the kind that will
help turn Libertarian philosophy into public policy.
   Paul appeared in Fort Collins the past weekend for the Colorado,
Wyoming and Alaska Libertarian Convention.
   ``I run to win, but not with any naive belief that that's an
absolute certainty,'' said the former Republican congressman from
Texas. ``A lot of good comes from it _ more attention, more
publicity. It's a grass-roots movement, actually.''
   Mary Margaret Glennie, a Fort Collins Libertarian leader, helped
lead the opposition to a school mill levy increase earlier this
month, and Paul said this is the type of activity the party needs.
   ``She took a Libertarian position and was successful,'' Paul
said.
   In his speech before the convention, which was attended by about
75 people, Paul condemned compulsory public school attendance and
encouraged parents to educate their children privately to obtain
tax credit.
   ``The disintegration of public school systems shows that
government monopolies are bad,'' he told the audience.
   The Libertarian party, which claims it has more than 200,000
registered members, has run presidential candidates since 1972.
</TEXT>
