<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Armenia 1stLd-Writethru a0538 05-31 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0538,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike Closes City In Disputed Area Of Southern Soviet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with resident giving details of strike
in Stepanakert, two more regional party members fired. ADDS byline.
No pickup.
^By ANDREW KATELL</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A general strike today shut down a city at the
center of a territorial and ethnic dispute between Armenians and
Azeris in the southern Soviet Union, sources said.
   A Moscow dissident, Sergei Grigoryants, said the strike has been
under way for a week in Stepanakert in the disputed region of
Nagorno-Karabakh.
   The strike closed factories and mass transit in the city today,
with thousands of Armenians staying away from work, said a resident
in a telephone interview with The Associated Press. The resident
declined to give his name.
   Also today, the official Soviet news agency Tass announced two
officials in the region were dismissed from the Communist Party for
organizational and political mistakes that led to violence between
Armenians and Azeris.
   Word of the strike in Stepanakert came after a new demonstration
was held Monday in Yerevan, the capital of Armenia, said
Grigoryants.
   In the Yerevan protest, 300,000 Armenians took to the streets to
demand that Nagorno-Karabakh, in the neighboring republic of
Azerbaijan, be put under Armenian jurisdiction, Grigoryants said.
   The majority of Nagorno-Karabakh's residents are Armenian.
   Grigoryants, a half-Russian, half-Armenian journalist, said the
protest in Yerevan occurred outside the Opera Theater on a square
where huge demonstrations took place earlier this year.
   Armenians began agitating in February for the right to annex
Nagorno-Karabakh. At the end of that month, ethnic rioting broke
out in the Azeri city of Sumgait in which 32 people _ six Azeris
and 26 Armenians _ were killed.
   Communist authorities rejected the demand to change jurisdiction
over Nagorno-Karabakh, instead chosing a program of social and
economic development. The ruling Politburo also replaced this month
its party leaders in both republics.
   New party shakeups were announced today. Tass said the former
first secretary of the Nagorno-Karabakh regional party committee,
Boris Kevorkov, was dismissed from the party because of his
``serious political mistakes.''
   ``His errors resulted in the loss of the party organization's
vanguard role and in the heightening of inter-ethnic relations,''
Tass said in announcing the action taken by a plenary meeting of
the Azerbaijani party organization. ``He was found to be personally
responsible for the disorders tht took place in the autonomous
region.''
   Tass said the plenum also dismissed from the party D.M.
Muslim-Zade, the former first secretary of the Sumgait city
committee, for ``serious shortcomings in organizational and
political work that brought about the tragic developments in
Sumgait.''
   In another development, Grigoryants said police in Yerevan had
detained two friends of Paruyr Ayrikyan, an Armenian nationalist
arrested in March.
   The two, Mofses Gorgisyan and Nehak Gabrilyan, were accused of
organizing a protest on Thursday, were held for 10 hours and fined
the equivalent of $80, he said. The two are members of Ayrikyan's
nationalist group called the Alliance for National
Self-Determination.
   On Saturday, about 50,000 Armenians in Yerevan were said to have
gathered to demand that authorities free Ayrikyan.
   Ayrikyan, 38, emerged as a primary spokesman for activists
shortly after Armenians began demonstrating Feb. 13 for annexation
of Nagorno-Karabakh. He remains jailed, charged with spreading
false information discrediting the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
