<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0444 05-31 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Strategy Talks Focus Today On Economics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush comments on money problem, subbing 5 grafs
for 4th graf pvs, Also to</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, seeking to develop a
platform for the general election contest, was consulting economic
advisers today at his oceanside retreat here.
   Among those expected to meet with Bush was Martin Feldstein, a
former chairman of President Reagan's Council of Economic Advisers.
The outspoken Feldstein, now a Harvard economist, quit his post in
Reagan's first term after clashes with other White House aides over
his advocacy of a tax increase to help balance the federal budget.
   Bush, like Reagan, has vowed opposition to any tax increases.
   Money for Bush's campaign is another issue under close scrutiny
during his week in Maine.
   Though he has been able to raise money quickly through the
primary season, he has now nearly reached the primary spending
limit of about $29 million _ including money for accounting costs.
   Bush told reporters on Tuesday that he might have to cut back on
his travel plans the rest of the summer. That is one of the items
his strategists are discussing this week.
   ``It's expensive to take this show on the road,'' Bush said to
reporters Tuesday.
   The economists he was meeting with today also included Michael
J. Boskin, a professor of economics at Stanford University who is
among Bush's top economic advisers.
   Bush has sought to closely identify himself with the record
65-month peacetime economic expansion, and one of his closest
economic advisers is Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III.
   A Baker protege, former deputy Treasury secretary Richard
Darman, now a consultant with Shearson Lehman Brothers., a Wall
Street brokerage firm, will be among those visiting with the vice
president today.
   Also invited to Bush's summer home were Richard Rahn, chief
economist for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, and Kathleen Eickhoff,
a private economist who was formerly the chief economist for the
Office of Management and Budget.
   Reps. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., and Bill Frenzel, R-Minn.; and Sen.
James McClure were also expected to participate in today's session.
   On Monday, Bush confirmed that he had met recently with
embattled Attorney General Edwin Meese III and that the two
discussed the impact of Meese's current predicament on Bush's
campaign.
   Bush campaign aides have said that Meese is a political
liability, making it difficult for Bush to pursue his theme of
returning high ethical standards to public office.
   Bush told reporters on Monday that he had met recently with
Meese, and that the attorney general had promised to do nothing to
endanger Bush's presidential campaign.
   Bush has said in the past, and he reiterated on Monday, that he
would withhold judgment on Meese pending the report by the
independent counsel, due out shortly.
   Meese said in a broadcast interview Monday night that if he were
to quit before the report is out, it could reflect badly on Bush.
   ``If I were to quit now, for example, it would be a real
liability because people would say there was something wrong,''
Meese said on CNN's ``Larry King Live.''
   However, he said he would not rule out a departure before the
end of the summer.
   Meese added that his Justice Department has ``a remarkable
record that will be an asset to any Republican running for office
this fall.''
   Bush gave the keynote address on Monday at a Memorial Day parade
here in the town square of Kennebunkport, his vacation home.
   In that speech, in the rain, Bush praised the efforts of
President Reagan in reaching an arms limitation agreement with the
Soviet Union, and said that if elected he would seek to reach
additional agreements, including ones to eliminate chemical and
biological warfare.
</TEXT>
