<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-RedSquare     05-31 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Red Square,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gorbachev and Reagan Mix with Public in Red Square</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev played tour
guide to President Reagan today, showing him the sights on
cobblestoned Red Square near historic St. Basil's church with its
famous onion domes.
   The superpower leaders strolled on the square, where hundreds of
people were lined up to see Lenin's tomb, after they extended their
meeting at the Kremlin by more than an hour.
   They chatted with groups of clapping tourists gathered in the
square amid heavy security. When Reagan mentioned peace and
friendship, people said ``thank you, good'' in Russian.
   ``It was wonderful, I had never actually seen Red Square,'' the
77-year-old president said later.
   Like an American politician, Gorbachev picked up a toddler in a
multicolored suit, and said to the little boy, ``Do you recognize
the president?'' The child did not respond.
   Gorbachev pointed out various features of Red Square which dates
from the 15th century, joking there should be ``no perestroika ..
no rebuilding here.''
   When one woman mentioned peace, Gorbachev said ``women are more
active, but men want peace too.'' Reagan also commented on the
female sex.
   ``I was just saying to the general secretary how much I have
great admiration for the women of Russia. They are courageous,'' he
said.
   The two men seemed in a good humor. ``What we have decided to do
is talk to each other rather than about each other and it's working
just fine,'' Reagan said.
   Gorbachev said he and Reagan sometimes criticized each other's
country, ``But I see that some of this is a misconception about
each other.''
</TEXT>
