<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Firefighters     05-31 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Firefighters,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Reinstate Affirmative Action Plan for DC Fire
Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to reinstate
an affirmative action plan designed to increase the number of
blacks in the District of Columbia Fire Department.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the plan _
calling for hiring at least six blacks for every 10 job openings _
unlawfully discriminates against whites.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here ruled last year that the
hiring quota violates federal law and the Constitution.
   Relying on recent Supreme Court rulings, the appeals court said
the plan is not narrowly tailored to remedy past discrimination.
   The appeals court noted, for example, that since 1981 about 75
percent of those hired as city firefighters are black.
   The appeals court said, ``We are entirely at a loss to discern
any act of hiring discrimination, much less any pattern or practice
of discrimination'' that the quota seeks to remedy. ``There were no
present-day impediments to black hiring. There were no relics from
yesteryear to overcome.''
   The appeals court added: ``To be valid, race-conscious remedies
must in fact be remedial in nature. They are not to promote the
Utopian goal, as some might see it, of a society in strict
proportional racial balance in every employment setting, from brain
surgery to basketball.''
   The appeals court overturned a federal judge's decree approving
the plan.
   The plan had been challenged by white firefighters and the
Reagan administration.
   City officials, in asking the Supreme Court to reinstate the
plan, said the appeals court ruling ``has crippled voluntary
efforts by government employers to eliminate discriminatory
barriers to employment and to cure the lingering effects of past
unlawful discrimination.''
   City officials said past discrimination was caused in part by a
written test for firefighters used from 1969 to 1980 that was not
related to the job and resulted in the hiring of whites for most
openings.
   The city also said that the appeals court ruling has put the
fire department in a bind, with some 100 firefighter vacancies now.
   City officials note that Congress, in an appropriations bill for
the District of Columbia, effectively has barred the fire
department from hiring at random from among applicants.
   The city has hired a testing firm to develop an examination for
hiring firefighters that would pass legal muster. But the exam is
not expected to be completed until 1989.
   Also at stake in the case could be back pay and seniority for
whites allegedly discriminated against by the affirmative action
plan.
   The Reagan administration, urging the justices to reject the
city's appeal, said the hiring quota is improper because there is
no continuing segregation that must be addressed.
   Justice Department lawyers, noting that some 38 percent of the
District of Columbia firefighters are black, said that ``compares
very favorably to the 29 percent black population in the greater
Washington metropolitan area'' that includes parts of Maryland and
Virginia.
   City officials said the relevant figure is the 64 percent
working-age black population within the borders of the nation's
capital. Approximately 70 percent of the city government's
workforce is black.
   The city's appeal was supported by state officials in
California, Illinois, Maryland, Ohio, South Carolina and Wyoming.
   Civil rights groups also urged the high court to reinstate the
plan. They said the appeals court ruling, if adopted elsewhere,
could have a devastating impact on voluntary efforts to fight
racial discrimination.
   The case is Barry vs. U.S., 87-1150.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-CableAccess     05-31 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Cable Access,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justices Say Cable Systems Need Not Carry All Local Signals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to resurrect
federal rules that would force cable television operators to carry
all local TV signals on their systems.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that struck down
as unconstitutional interim ``must-carry'' rules adopted by the
Federal Communications Commission's in 1986.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here ruled last December that
the rules, which were to be imposed for five years, violated
free-speech rights.
   The National Association of Broadcasters, the Association of
Independent Television Stations and other broadcast organizations
urged the justices to reinstate the rules, saying they fear cable
operators may drop their over-the-air signals.
   The appeals court said the need for such rules ``is more
speculative than real.''
   Lawyers for the FCC agreed, and urged the justices to reject the
broadcasters' appeals.
   The appeals court in 1985 said the commission's original set of
rules unlawfully ``coerce speech'' because they required cable
operators to carry local broadcasters' signals irrespective of
whether the operator considered them appropriate programming.
   After the Supreme Court refused in 1986 to disturb that ruling,
the commission issued the interim rules _ forcing cable system
operators to carry local signals for five years.
   The rules entitled a television station to insist that its
signal be retransmitted on any cable system serving the station's
local service area.
   Cable systems, especially those with fewer channels, have
opposed the rules because they often were forced to run the same
programming on a number of stations if stations they are required
to carry broadcast programs from the same television network.
   For example, a cable system in Maryland might be forced to carry
the signal of the NBC affiliates in Baltimore and Washington, even
though the programming is identical much of the time.
   In its December ruling, the appeals court said, ``The FCC's
reimposition of must-carry rules on a five-year basis neither
clearly furthers a substantial governmental interest nor is of
brief enough duration to be considered narrowly tailored (in
imposing) restrictions on speech.''
   In one of the appeals acted on today, lawyers for the National
Association of Broadcasters contended that the appeals court ruling
could affect what television programming is available to tens of
millions of American families.
   ``The lower court has made the television choices that are
available to these homes largely dependent on the economic and
political predilections of the only cable operator to provide cable
service in any given neighborhood,'' the appeal argued.
   But Justice Department lawyers representing the FCC told the
court that during the 16 months between the appeals court's
invalidation of the original must-carry rules and imposition of the
interim rules ``cable operators generally did not stop carrying
local broadcast signals.''
   They said the appeals court's ruling ``gives the commission an
opportunity to observe how broadcasters and the cable industry will
operate without must-carry rules.''
   ``If experience, as opposed to prediction, proves that
must-carry rules are needed to advance public interests, the
commission may build a record supporting new must-carry rules and
defend those rules in the courts,'' the government lawyers said.
   The cases are Office of Communications of the United Church of
Christ vs. FCC, 87-1487; Corporation for Public Broadcasting vs.
Century Communications, 87-1506; National Association of
Broadcasters vs. Century Communications, 87-1510; and Association
of Independent Television Stations vs. Century Communications,
87-1551.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Kiting     05-31 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Kiting,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Leaves $25 Million Fine Intact for Check-Kiting Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today left intact a $25
million fine against a businessman for what prosecutors called the
biggest check-kiting fraud in the history of American banking.
   The court, citing the lack of a ``substantial federal
question,'' rejected a challenge to a New York law that says those
convicted in such schemes may be forced to pay fines equal to twice
the amount gained through their criminal conduct.
   Edward J. Halloran was convicted of defrauding Marine Midland, a
New York City bank, of $23 million through a complex, synchronized
drawing and depositing of some 15,000 checks.
   The evidence showed that Halloran had accounts at Marine Midland
and Citibank, and that he kept shifting funds from one to the other
for a one-year period that began April 1, 1983.
   His admitted aim was to save his financial empire, including the
Taft Hotel in New York, a Holiday Inn in Fort Washington, Pa., and
several concrete companies.
   Halloran was sentenced to six months in jail and fined $25
million. Harold F. Madden, a co-defendant who was not involved in
the appeal acted on today, was ordered to perform 120 hours of
community service and was fined $100,000.
   Halloran said his fine is excessive and violates his
constitutional rights. He denied that he made anything like a $25
million profit from the check-kiting scheme.
   But state Judge Carol Berkman, in upholding the fine, said
prosecutors demonstrated that the fraud enabled Halloran not only
to save his empire without paying interest but also that his
holdings substantially increased in value.
   Halloran's ``gain'' from the fraud was said to be more than $22
million.
   Moreover, the judge said, ``At trial, to avoid a grand larceny
conviction, the defendants were eager to show the health of
Halloran's financial empire.''
   Afterward, the judge said, ``The empire became moribund: its
gains limited to the amount pumped in from the kite; its losses
oppressive and all but wiping out any capital gains.''
   ``These self-serving arguments and conclusions at sentence did
not rebut the people's evidence that defendants' gains went well
beyond the monies taken in the course of the kite and returned to
Marine Midland Bank upon discovery of the fraud,'' the judge said.
   Halloran argued that he ``borrowed'' the money from the bank and
intended to repay it.
   He repaid Marine Midland some $23 million after a shortfall in
that amount was discovered in his account at the bank.
   In urging the Supreme Court to hear Halloran's appeal, his
lawyers said the case could have a bearing on government seizures
of property and profits from illegal drug operations and other
criminal enterprises covered by the federal Racketeer Influenced
and Corrupt Organizations Act.
   ``Constitutional questions concerning the applicable standard of
proof and the permissible limits of the term `gain' are both
important and recurring,'' they said.
   The lawyers said it is unconstitutional for a defendant to be
ordered to pay a fine up to twice the amount of the alleged gain
when proof of that gain is based only on ``a preponderance of the
evidence'' _ the standard used in the New York law. Most often used
in criminal cases is the more stringent ``beyond a reasonable
doubt'' standard of proof.
   The case is Halloran vs. New York, 87-1595.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-PunitiveDamages     05-31 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Punitive Damages,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Award Won by California Firm Against Ohio Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a $5 million
punitive-damages award won by a California savings and loan
association against an Ohio-based insurance company.
   The justices, over two dissenting votes, refused to hear
arguments that the award, believed to be the largest of its kind
ever upheld in California courts, is unconstitutionally excessive.
   Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and Anthony M. Kennedy voted to
hear arguments in the case, but four votes are needed to grant such
review.
   Justice John Paul Stevens did not participate in the case, for
uannounced reasons.
   The high court earlier this month passed up deciding in a
Mississippi case whether the ban on ``excessive fines'' imposed by
the Constitution's Eighth Amendment applies to non-criminal cases.
   No court ever has applied the constitutional principle to
non-criminal cases.
   A California jury awarded the Downey Savings and Loan
Association $123,769 in compensatory damages and $5 million in
punitive damages after ruling that the Ohio Casualty Insurance Co.,
a wholly owned subsidiary of Ohio Casualty Corp., had denied
insurance benefits in bad faith.
   Downey had been insured by Ohio Casualty Insurance against any
dishonest or fraudulent act by the savings and loan's employees.
Downey sought to collect on that insurance bond after one of its
branch managers allegedly took part in a conspiracy to bilk Downey
for hundreds of thousands of dollars.
   Downey claimed the scheme was partially successful, and resulted
in a lawsuit against the savings and loan by the American Funding
Corp.
   In defending against that suit, Downey paid over $68,000 in
legal fees and $55,000 in settlement costs. Downey in 1977 sought
reimbursement of those expenses from Ohio Casualty Insurance.
   The jury in 1984 found that Ohio Casualty acted in bad faith in
denying Downey's claim.
   The challenged $5 million award was upheld by a state appeals
court, and the California Supreme Court refused to hear Ohio
Casualty's appeal last May 29.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for Ohio Casualty argued
that the punitive damages award, and the way it was awarded, ``are
the inevitable, yet unpredictible, products of a system
fundamentally out of control in which fines are becoming larger and
are imposed more frequently.''
   Some state legislatures, reacting to soaring insurance rated, in
recent years have imposed ceilings on how much money can be
recovered in personal-injury lawsuits.
   New Hampshire has abolished the awarding of punitive damages _
those aimed at punishing wrongful conduct that harms others and
deterring such conduct in the future.
   Some commentators have decried soaring damages awards, charging
that such a trend spurs more lawsuits, some of them frivolous, and
that it overcompensates injured people.
   But other commentators contend that awarding punitive damages in
addition to compensatory damages serves a vital public interest in
deterring wrongful conduct.
   The case is Ohio Casualty Insurance Co. vs. Downey Savings and
Loan Association, 87-159.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hostages     05-31 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostages,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Times Says Four Hostages In Lebanon May be Freed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Times of London said today that four hostages
in Lebanon, three Americans and an Indian, may soon be freed
following the Syrian army's takeover of the Beirut district where
they are believed held.
   The paper identified the four as Americans Robert Polhill, Jesse
Turner and Alann Steen, and Indian Mithileshwar Singh, all
educators at Beirut University College. They were abducted Jan. 24,
1987.
   ``The Syrians appear set to produce four Western hostages from
the suburbs of Beirut within a week of their military deployment
there,'' the Times reported from Beirut.
   It said the four ``are now believed to be in the hands of the
Shiite Amal movement, Syria's proxy militia in west Beirut, and to
be in the Bourj el-Barajneh district of the suburbs which is now
under Syrian military control.''
   The Times said Amal leader Nabih Berri, Lebanon's justice
minister, has scheduled a news conference this week, ``and there is
understandable speculation that this may be to announce the
hostages' release.''
   The Beirut newspaper As-Safir reported Monday that the four
educators might be freed soon. The newspaper, which cited
unidentified sources close to President Amin Gemayel, linked the
possible release to the deployment of Syrian troops in Beirut's
southern slums.
   Eighteen foreigners _ including nine Americans _ are believed
held in Lebanon. The longest held is Terry A. Anderson, 40, chief
Middle East Correspondent of The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
