<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Summit-Reagan-Students 1stLd-Writethru a0551 05-31 1234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Reagan-Students, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0551,1,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan: U.S. Will Help Locate Missing Soviet Soldiers in
Afghanistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 13 grafs new to update with question-and-answer session;
picks up 4th graf pvs, ``The appearance xxx.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, in an extraordinary
question-and-answer session with Soviet students, said today that
the United States ``would like nothing better'' than to help in the
search for Soviet soldiers missing in Afghanistan.
   The session, covering topics as diverse as the plight of
American Indians to the two-term restriction on American presidents
and arms control, followed the president's speech at Moscow
University. He took questions from a stage beneath a towering bust
of Lenin and a banner emblazoned with a hammer and sickle.
   Reagan noted that there once had been hopes that he and Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev could mark the Moscow summit by signing
a sweeping treaty to cut strategic nuclear weapons by half.
   ``There are many things still to be settled,'' Reagan said, all
but confirming the treaty will not be signed this week.
   ``It is not completed, there are still points that are being
debated,'' said Reagan, who has only one more scheduled meeting
with Gorbachev before departing Thursday.
   ``We are both hopeful that it can be finished before I leave
office'' in January, he said. ``If it isn't, I assure you that I
will have impressed on my successor that we must carry on until it
is signed.''
   One student told Reagan th!t there are 310 Soviet soldiers
missing in Afghanistan after eight years of fighting. The student
asked if Reagan would assist in the search and return of the forces.
   ``Very much so,'' Reagan replied. ``We would like nothing better
than that.'' The United States has vowed to continuing supporting
the Afghan rebels as long as the Kremlin supportsthe Kremlin-backed
regime in Kabul.
   Another student told Reagan that a delegation of American
Indians had traveled here because they found it impossible to meet
with him in Washington. Reagan said he did not know they had sought
an audience, and that ``I'd be very happy to see them.''
   He said the United States had given the Indians millions of
acres of land and established reservations where they could live if
they chose. ``We've done everything we can to meet their demands as
to how they want to live. Maybe we made a mistake. Maybe we should
not have humored them'' and insisted that they become integrated in
American life.
   As for the delegation here, he said, ``I don`t know what their
complaint might be.
   The question-and-answer session followed a speech in which
Reagan preached free markets, freedom of speech and the American
way of life.
   The appearance, at the university where Mikhail S. Gorbachev
earned a degree in 1954, was one in a string of events undertaken
by Reagan to promote the concept of freedom and human rights. White
House planners said the appearance gave Reagan an opportunity to
pass along some thoughts to a generation that one day will govern
the Soviet Union.
   ``Progress is not fore-ordained,'' he said. ``The key is freedom
_ freedom of thought, freedom of information, freedom of
communication.'' He praised the economic progress of such
free-market citadels as Singapore, South Korea and Taiwan. And he
added:
   ``Perhaps most exciting are the winds of change blowing over the
People's Republic of China, where one-quarter of the world's
population is now getting its first taste of economic freedom.''
   As if that was not challenge enough to the world's other major
communist state, Reagan said he hoped that Soviet families will
soon be free to visit their relatives overseas.
   ``Recently, a few individuals and families have been allowed to
visit relatives in the West. We can only hope that it won't be long
before all are allowed to do so, and Ukrainian-Americans,
Baltic-Americans, Armenian-Americans can freely visit their
homelands just as this Irish-American visits his.''
   Extolling the importance of a free enterprise system in which
entrepreneurs may try and sometimes fail, Reagan said, ``it's so
hard for government planners, no matter how sophisticated, to ever
substitute for millions of individuals working night and day to
make their dreams come true.
   ``The fact is, bureaucracies are a problem around the world.''
   Reagan said ``Americans make no secret of our belief in
freedom,'' and exercise it by choosing a new president every four
years and enjoying freedom of religion, speech and assembly and a
judicial system where the accused is presumed innocent until proven
guilty.
   ``Freedom is the right to question and change the established
way of doing things,'' the president said.
   He said that in his talks with Gorbachev, ``I have spoken of how
important it is to institutionalize change _ to put guarantees on
reform.
   ``And we have been talking together about one sad reminder of a
divided world, the Berlin Wall,'' Reagan said. ``It is time to
remove the barriers that keep people apart.''
   He told the students they are living ``in one of the most
exciting, hopeful times in Soviet history. It is a time when the
first breath of freedom stirs the air and the heart beats to the
accelerated rhythm of hope, when the accumulated spiritual energies
of a long silence yearn to break free.''
   He said, ``We do not know what will be the conclusion of this
journey, but we are hopeful that the promise of reform will be
fulfilled.
   ``In this Moscow spring, this May 1988, we may be allowed that
this hope _ that freedom, like the fresh green sapling planted over
Tolstoy's grave, will blossom forth at last in the rich fertile
soil of your people and culture.''
   At a meeting earlier today with writers, artists, film makers
and others, Reagan said freedom for the arts has been expanded in
the Soviet Union in recent years. ``We hope to see it go further.
We hope to see the works of Alexander Solzhenitsyn published in the
land he loves and we hope to see a permanent end to creative
restrictions on all writers and artists.
   ``We want this not just for your sake but for our own,'' Reagan
said. ``We believe the greater freeoms in other countries, the more
secure our own freedoms and peace.''
   He said both artists and political leaders had to be able to
grasp a vision and to put it into life.
   ``By the way, I`ve found that Mr. Gorbachev has the ability to
grasp and hold a vision and I respect him for that,'' Reagan told
the 38 intellectuals assembled in the House of Writer's elegant
wood paneled restaurant.
   Praising what he called the recent thaw in the Soviet arts,
Reagan said he hoped all constrictions on the arts would finally
fall, and that artists like ballet dancer Mikhail Baryshnikov and
cellist and conductor Mstislav Rostropovich would once again
perform in their homeland.
   The president's speech drew a warm standing ovation. Afterwards,
writer Fyodor Burlatsky called it ``one of the best speeches of his
life.
   ``He spoke very sincerely, he spoke about his private life, he
mentioned all the names which are very dear to Russian
intelligentisa,'' Burlatsky said.
   Sergei Zalygin, editor of Novy Mir, a literary journal which has
published several previously banned works recently, was asked
whether he thought Solzhenitsyn's works would appear. ``Yes,'' he
said, declining to forecast when and saying this depended on
negotiations with Solzhenitsyn himself.
</TEXT>
