<2ND_LINE>PM-Chemical Fire,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Hospitalized After Fire In Shed Containing Chemicals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIGONIER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire broke out in a high school shed
containing hazardous chemicals, exposing firefighters and residents
to fumes and leaving four people hospitalized today, authorities
said.
   Eighty-three people, firefighters and residents were examined at
Latrobe Area Hospital as a precaution Monday night, shortly after
the fire broke out, said nursing supervisor Lisa Sciullo.
   Those examined complained of throat irritation, burning eyes and
coughing, Ms. Sciullo said, adding that four people were admitted.
   The cause of the fire in the shed about 30 yards from Ligonier
Valley Senior High School was not immediately determined.
   Classes began on schedule this morning, said school secretary
Lois Goodman.
   Gerry Tripoli of the state Department of Environmental
Resources' Bureau of Waste Management said the spillage posed no
danger as long as the area near the shed was kept off limits.
   The shed was used to store chemicals collected from chemistry
labs and photography clubs prior to disposal, said Ligonier Valley
School Superintendent Milroy ``Bud'' Carnahan.
   County Emergency Management Deputy Director Jack Simon said
phosphorous and sulfuric acid posed the greatest danger among the
leaking chemicals.
