<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Judges     05-31 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Judges,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says New York Can Force Some Judges to Retire at Age 70</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York's policy of forcing elected judges to
retire at age 70 even though no such mandatory retirement is
imposed on appointed judges was left intact by the Supreme Court
today.
   The justices, four of whom are over 70, threw out an appeal by
eight current or former New York judges who say the retirement
policy violates the Constitution's equal-protection guarantees.
   The court cited the lack of a ``substantial federal question''
in dismissing the appeal.
   The New York policy, reflected in the state's constitution and a
state law, was upheld by the New York Court of Appeals last Sept. 3.
   The state's highest court ruled that the differing treatment of
elected and appointed judges is valid.
   The state policy previously had applied to state and local
judges in New York, whether elected or appointed. A challenge to it
was rejected by the Supreme Court in 1985.
   But the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act, which
originally protected only people between 45 and 70 and does not
apply to elected officials, was amended in 1987 to bar employment
discrimination against people over 70.
   New York's policy subsequently was changed to exempt appointed
judges, sparking the equal-protection challenge.
   ``That the state policy requiring retirement of judges is
partially frustrated because the federal statute preempts it with
respect to appointed judges does not render the policy irrational,
and the state is free to pursue that policy to the extent doing so
is consistent with federal law,'' the state court ruled.
   The state court used the least stringent standard of review for
equal-protection challenges, in which courts decide whether a law
or governmental policy that allows differing treatment is rational.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the five state judges
argued that differing treatment based on age should spark the same
stringent standard of review in courts as does differing treatment
based on race.
   The state Court of Appeals rejected that argument.
   The eight judges who challenged the state policy are: Benjamin
Glass, an elected state trial judge in New York City forced to
retire in 1981; Benjamin Nolan and Louis Grossman, elected New York
City Civil Court judges; Barbara Kaiser and Ralph Diamond, elected
state Family Court judges in Westchester and Nassau Counties,
respectively, who turned 70 last year; Samuel Greenstein, an
elected New York City Civil Court judge who is 65; and James P.
Griffin and H. Buswell Roberts, whose judicial positions were not
listed in submitted court documents.
   Federal judges, including Supreme Court justices, are appointed
for life. The four justices over 70 are William J. Brennan,
Thurgood Marshall, Harry A. Blackmun and Byron R. White.
   The case is Diamond vs. Cuomo, 87-1361.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
