<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--PlaneCrash     05-31 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Plane Crash,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ultra-light Plane Crashes, Killing One Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Witnesses watched from the windows of a
popular restaurant as an ultra-light plane crashed and burned,
killing its pilot, a sheriff's investigator said today.
   The pilot had waved to restaurant patrons and was attempting to
regain altitude ``when his left wing folded, the plane started
spiraling and crashed'' several feet from the restaurant's parking
lot Monday night, said Sheriff's Department investigator Tom
Erickson.
   Jeffrey A. Blankestyn, a 34-year-old auto mechanic from
Kankakee, was the pilot, Erickson said.
   ``At this time we don't know if it was pilot error or structural
failure,'' Erickson said.
   No one else was injured in the accident, the investigator said.
   The Federal Aviation Administration and the Kankakee County
Sheriff's department were investigating, Erickson said.
   According to witnesses, the plane had taken off from the
Kankakee Airport and was headed southwest when it crashed and
caught fire, Erickson said.
</TEXT>
