<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Amadeo     05-31 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Amadeo,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Overturns Murder Conviction and Death Sentence of Georgia
Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today unanimously overturned
the murder conviction and death sentence of a Georgia man accused
of a 1977 killing in Putnam County.
   The justices ruled that Tony B. Amadeo should have been allowed
to raise the issue of discriminatory jury selection in a federal
court appeal.
   The Atlanta-based 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals had ruled
that Amadeo was not entitled to raise that issue because his
lawyers failed to comply with a state procedural rule requiring
such objections to be raised before trial.
   The appeals court rejected a federal judge's finding that
Amadeo's lawyers could not be expected to have learned about the
discrimination against women and blacks in the selection of Putnam
County grand juries and juries before Amadeo's trial began.
   In a separate case, Putnam County officials were found to have
structured the jury-selection process in a way in which blacks and
women were under-represented.
   Writing for the high court today, Justice Thurgood Marshall said
the appeals court should not have rejected the judge's finding
unless convinced it was ``clearly erroneous.''
   ``Because there is sufficient evidence in the record considered
in its entirety to support the district court's factual findings,
the court of appeals should not have set them aside,'' Marshall
said.
   ``The district court's conclusion that (Amadeo's) lawyers did
not deliberately bypass the jury challenge was supported by events
contemporaneous with the jury-selection process,'' Marshall added.
   Amadeo had been convicted in the Sept. 29, 1977, killing of
James Turk Sr. Prosecutors said Amadeo was one of three men
involved in the crime, each of whom was a Marine absent without
leave from Camp LeJeune.
   Today's decision means Georgia officials must give Amadeo a new
trial or set him free.
   The case is Amadeo vs. Kemp, 87-5277.
</TEXT>
