<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Securities     05-31 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Securities,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Settle Case Between Delaware and New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to settle a
multi-million dollar dispute between Delaware and New York over
unclaimed dividend and interest payments on securities.
   The justices granted Delaware's request that it be allowed to
sue New York in the Supreme Court without the case first having
been heard in some lower court.
   The court has such ``original'' authority in disputes between
states.
   The conflict stems from the fact that 15 of the nation's largest
stock brokerage firms are incorporated in Delaware but based in New
York.
   Each year, the firms recover substantial amounts of money in
dividend and interest payments for people who cannot be located.
   All states have so-called ``escheat'' laws providing that such
abandoned money goes into the state treasury after remaining
unclaimed for a certain time.
   In Delaware, the waiting period is seven years. In New York, it
is three years.
   Delaware's escheat law is binding on all corporations chartered
in the state, but New York considers brokerage firms with New York
trading addresses subject to its escheat law and has pursued
unclaimed payments.
   Delaware Attorney General Charles M. Oberly III said New York
has been collecting such payments from Delaware-chartered brokerage
firms since 1971. He said more than $50 million could be involved.
   Oberly told the justices, ``New York should be directed to pay
Delaware amounts already paid to it to which Delaware is or will be
entitled under the Delaware escheat law and to cease interfering
with Delaware's right to escheat the property of unknowns held by
the Delaware brokerage corporations.''
   But New York Attorney General Robert Abrams urged the high court
to reject Delaware's lawsuit.
   He said Delaware has not yet exhausted all administrative
remedies, and added that New York is entitled to the dividend and
interest overpayments held by brokerage firms with New York trading
addresses.
   ``Delaware's failure for 17 years to employ New York's claim
procedure, in contrast to other states, or to attempt to negotiate
with New York before bringing this original action demonstrates
that the case is not ripe for decision by this court,'' Abrams
argued.
   The case is Delaware vs. New York, 111 Original.
</TEXT>
