<2ND_LINE>PM-Murder Contract, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0506,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Face Trial In Plot To Commit Murder</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs, jury selection begins; picks up 6th graf
pvs, ``The parents xxxx</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began today in the
case of a Jordanian-American couple who allegedly hired a hit man
to kill their daughter's husband, his mother and his sister, and
cut off pieces of their bodies as souvenirs.
   The murder plot, which the prosecution says was hatched because
the daughter had been promised to someone else in a marriage
arranged by the parents, never was carried out.
   The case of Dr. Saud Tarawneh, 46, and his 44-year-old wife,
Ghada, involves a clash between the American ways of love and the
family's culture, where murder to avenge one's honor is acceptable,
their lawyer says.
   ``Keeping body parts as souvenirs _ I don't think is normal,''
said Assistant State Attorney William Dimitrouleas, adding that he
expects unusual testimony in the Broward Circuit Court trial.
   After several routine motions, jury selection began late this
morning.
   The parents left Jordan 18 years ago and lived in Toledo, Ohio.
When their daughter married her Syrian cousin in 1986 and moved to
Tamarac, Fla., tradition required that insult to be avenged, the
prosecution says.
   The parents, arrested February in Toledo, are accused of
conspiracy and solicitation to commit murder for allegedly hiring
an assassin and attempting to have the victims' body parts
preserved and shipped to Toledo.
   A private investigator that prosecutors say the couple hired to
find a hit man cooperated with authorities in their criminal
investigation. The assassin was supposed to receive an initial $500
and $2,000 after the killings, according to authorities.
   Agents taped phone conversations between the investigator and
the family, said Mike Breece, an investigator with the Florida
Department of Law Enforcement.
   Defense attorney Barry Roderman said threats about killing and
cutting off body parts are common in the Middle East, but are
seldom carried out.
   ``There's a definite clash of cultures here between the Arab
mind and the American mind,'' he said. ``The Tarawnehs are from a
tribe where they handle their problems their own way, inside the
family.''
   The parents declined to comment.
   Tarawneh, a gynecologist who became a U.S. citizen in 1980, and
his wife, a nurse, already had arranged a marriage for their then
17-year-old daughter, Raniah, and refused to allow her to marry
Mouataz Abdulsalam, now 28.
   ``My father said, `Don't mention this again,''' the daughter
said in a sworn statement. ``I think he was against the whole idea
of me marrying someone I wanted to.''
   The alleged targets were their unwanted son-in-law, his younger
sister Azza and his mother Najwa, 45.
</TEXT>
