<DOCNO> AP880531-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmScene     05-31 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Scene,0764</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Fish Farm Can Be Large- or Small-Scale Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharpened consumer appetite for fish and
seafood offers an opportunity for American farmers to reel in a
share of a growing worldwide aquaculture industry, says a report by
the Agriculture Department.
   Expanding world population and growing consumer demands have
already forced some nations to harvest ``previously underutilized
species'' of fish and seafood, and to develop alternative sources,
the report said.
   ``Many commercial fisheries, which harvest from the wild, are
approaching their maximum sustainable yield,'' it added. ``Thus
aquaculture _ growing fish or other aquatic life in a controlled
environment _ is expanding.''
   Americans are also honing their appetites, last year consuming
more fish and seafood per person than veal, lamb and mutton,
roasting chicken or turkey. Beef, pork and broiler chicken,
however, remain far in the lead as American favorites.
   In 1980, aquaculture accounted for 13 percent of the global
production of aquatic foods and goods, up from 7 percent in 1970.
Industry sources indicate that by the year 2010 aquaculture will
provide 25 percent of the worldwide aquatic harvest.
   The report was included in the June issue of Agricultural
Outlook magazine issued by the department's Economic Research
Service. The article was written by economists Mike Dicks and Dave
Harvey.
   By 1981, total U.S. fish consumption had grown 30 percent from
1970. About 47 percent was imported.
   ``Population growth accounts for only half the increase,'' the
report added. ``Per capita U.S. consumption of fish and shellfish
has grown, reaching a record 15.4 pounds (edible weight) in 1987.
It is expected to expand another 50 percent by 2010.''
   Dicks said in a telephone interview that the 1987 per capita
consumption figure included only 0.5 pound of the estimated 3 to 5
pounds per capita of U.S. aquaculture production. The half pound,
he said, only included catfish and none of the other species,
ranging from trout and salmon to oysters and shrimp.
   Despite the recent increases, U.S. per capita fish and seafood
consumption is well behind Europe, which averages 40 to 45 pounds
per person, and Japan, which averages 130 to 140 pounds annually.
   Per capita consumption of veal last year by Americans averaged
1.5 pounds; lamb and mutton, 1.3; mature chicken, 2.5; and turkey,
15.2. Beef consumption was 75.5 pounds; pork, 58.8; and broiler
chicken, 60.1. Those are retail weights as sold by grocery stores.
   The U.S. aquaculture industry _ fish farming _ has expanded
greatly in recent years but still is led by catfish, produced
primarily in the South. In 1986, for example, the U.S. aquaculture
harvest was nearly 620 million pounds valued at more than $496
million.
   Of those amounts, catfish comprised 327 million pounds worth
$229 million to growers, the report showed.
   Comparatively, in 1980 the total harvest was 203 million pounds
valued at $192 million, with catfish comprising less than 77
million pounds at a value of $54 million.
   Catfish, crawfish, salmon and trout make up about 90 percent of
the total U.S. aquaculture production.
   By 2010, according to industry estimates, U.S. aquaculture
production is expected to exceed 2 billion pounds, and that doesn't
count production from ``catch-out'' ponds and direct sales to
consumers, the report said.
   A study in Mississippi showed that for every 10 million
additional pounds of catfish produced, 220 new jobs are created in
the industry, and 1,100 jobs are created in related industries.
   Most catfish are grown in Mississippi, Alabama and Arkansas,
while salmon output is mainly in Washington and Oregon, crawfish in
Louisiana and Texas, and trout in Idaho.
   Channel catfish east mostly soybean products and corn. To get a
pound of catfish requires one pound of soybean meal, a half pound
of corn meal, and a half pound of other nutrients.
   Nearly 55 percent of the usual diet of farm-grown salmon are
also from the farm _ 17 percent whey, 16.5 percent wheat germ, 15
percent cottonseed meal, and 6 percent soybean oil.
   The report said aquaculture is suited to small as well as
commercial farms and that a modest operation can provide
significant income.
   ``Many agricultural institutions still regard aquaculture as a
sideline,'' the report said. ``Even so, aquaculture has become a
technical and highly capitalized commercial enterprise.''
   One problem has been the ``limited information'' available to
potential lenders, the report said. As a result, it added, many
federal agencies have been reluctant to aid aquaculture producers
financially.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-TVNews     05-31 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-TV News,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Television News Broadcast In Central Moscow, Not Enough Music</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Muscovites responding to their first peek at U.S.
television news say they wish it had more music and less talk, but
they still are wide-eyed over glimpses into the personal lives of
government leaders and average Americans _ even when they don't
understand the language.
   Cables News Network is being broadcast into central Moscow
during the summit under an agreement with the state broadcast
agency Gostelradio. Those Muscovites lucky enough to own recent
model television sets can pick it up on Channel 6.
   It also is available in the Rossiya Hotel overlooking Red
Square, where many foreign journalists are staying. Maids and
plainclothes KGB agents are often seen sitting together before
television sets in halls, watching attentively and sometimes with
the volumn off.
   For most, it marks the first time they have seen fast-paced,
round-the-clock, up-close-and-personal American television.
   Television news imported from the United States is a far cry
from the Soviet evening news show Vremya. The show has been jazzed
up in recent months with new graphics and backdrops, but it is
still dry and focuses on agricultural reports and Politburo
announcements.
   A 46-year-old clerk who would only give her first name,
Svetlana, said she was watching American news this week as often as
she could.
   ``I enjoyed learning something about the private life of former
President Carter,'' she said, smiling shyly. ``I saw him on a
fishing trip. For us, this is very unusual.''
   ``I would like to see such things about General Secretary
(Mikhail S.) Gorbachev on Vremya. But for the moment, we have only
rumors about his personal life,'' she said.
   Svetlana said she understood some English. But a lack of
language comprehension has not stopped Soviets from tuning in to
CNN, sometimes for hours.
   ``We've watched at least two hours a night all this week, even
though I don't know any English,'' said Lyubov Ivanova, 50. ``I
wish it had more music, but I'm still very interested. It is nice
to see President Reagan in Moscow and now I would like to see one
of his movies.''
   Both Svetlana and Mrs. Ivanova said they were disappointed that
the stories on American television, which last an average of two or
three minutes, were so short. On Soviet television, an item like a
Gorbachev speech can take up the entire newscast, which is
sometimes extended to two hours.
   CNN producer Ruth Oxenberg said the network was broadcasting its
program only in central Moscow and had received comments and
telephone calls from Soviets which indicated it was widely watched.
   ``We know sometimes official Soviets are not happy about the way
we do our reporting, but we think it is good for Moscow that we
were allowed to do this,'' she said.
   Moscow-born Andrei, 25, agreed.
   ``I think it is important to see even these small pieces of the
lives of Americans,'' Andrei said.
   ``We Soviets may be able to learn things that could help us,''
he said. ``For example, the Americans seem so relaxed and social
compared with us. Maybe we can learn how to take it easy by
watching them.''
   Andrei said he was disappointed to learn CNN would go off the
air here once President Reagan leaves Moscow on Thursday. ``It's
too bad,'' he said. ``I wish American TV could stay here and our
show Vremya could go to the United States. Television should have
no borders.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
