<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Punjab     05-31 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explosion in Punjab Market Kills 6, Wounds 32</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb hidden in a plastic bag exploded
in the crowded vegetable market of a Hindu town in Punjab state
Tuesday, killing six people and wounding at least 32, police
reported.
   They blamed Sikh extremists for planting the bomb in the market
at Dinanagar, 50 miles northeast of Amritsar, the Sikh holy city.
   It went off at about 6:30 a.m. as people were beginning their
morning shopping, said D.S. Khala, deputy police commissioner of
Punjab. He said most of the victims were Hindus.
   Dinanagar is in the Gurdaspur district, where seven bombs have
killed at least 13 people this year. The bombings are blamed on
extremists who have been fighting since 1982 for an independent
Sikh nation in Punjab, the only Indian state where the sect has a
majority.
   On Monday, an explosion in a crowded market in Amritsar killed
23 people and wounded 44.
   Police initially said the cause appeared to be the accidental
ignition of a propane gas cylinder. But the United News of India
quoted Suresh Arora, the Amritsar district police chief, on Tuesday
as saying it was a bomb, probably set off by remote control.
   Authorities blamed Sikh extremists for the Amritsar explosion.
   Two Hindu-dominated political parties sponsored a general
protest strike Tuesday in Amritsar that closed many stores and
offices.
   The bombing deaths and the killing of a Sikh man Tuesday in the
Amritsar district raised to at least 1,230 the number of deaths
blamed on Sikh radicals in Punjab so far this year, 200 more than
the 1,030 in all of 1987. Most of the gunmen's targets are Hindus,
but they also kill Sikh moderates.
   Police defused two bombs in a New Delhi residential neighborhood
Tuesday, and a bomb scare delayed the departure of a Paris-bound
Air India jet for more than 16 hours, Indian news agencies reported.
   Press Trust of India said the two bombs were found in a plastic
bag in the Kailash Nagar neighborhood and defused by the police
bomb disposal squad.
   Air India's Flight 123 to Paris was delayed because an anonymous
telephone caller said a bomb was aboard, but a search revealed no
explosives, United News of India said. There was no claim of
responsibility for either incident in the capital.
   Thousands of people have been killed since Sikh militants began
their violent campaign for a homeland in Punjab, a rich
northwestern state that is India's main agricultural region.
   Sikhism was founded 500 years ago as an alternative to Hinduism
and Islam. Members of the sect, who make up only 2 percent of
India's 800 million people, claim discrimination by the predominant
Hindus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
