<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Teachers     05-31 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Teachers,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Begin Indefinite Strike; Classes Put off for 2Oth Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schoolteachers began a strike for more pay
Tuesday. It was the 20th time in the past three months that public
schools have been closed because of teacher work stoppages.
   Unlike past strikes, this one was called for an indefinite
period. It was the first indefinite work stoppage by civil servants
in the public administration since Spain returned to democracy in
1977.
   The strike meant no classes for the nearly 6 million students in
Spain's public elementary, secondary and technical schools. There
is just one month left in the regular school year.
   The six unions representing Spain's 272,000 public
schoolteachers approved the indefinite strike Thursday. The
government of Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez broke off negotiations
after the strike was approved.
   Teachers are demanding pay parity with civil servants of similar
qualifications and monthly pay increases of $223 by September 1990.
   Teachers at elementary schools earn an average of $929 a month.
Teachers at secondary and technical schools earn about $1,090 a
month.
   On May 4, five of the six teachers unions reached a tentative
agreement with the Education Ministry for a monthly pay increase of
$178 by September 1990.
   The teachers branch of the Communist-oriented Workers
Commissions union opposed the pact, and a referendum was held May
16. Of the teachers who voted, 75 percent rejected the pact.
   A government decree published last week forces teachers to
guarantee students their required tests and final exams by June 30
or face suspension from their jobs for three to six years. The
unions said teachers would comply.
   In announcing the breaking off of talks last week, government
spokesman Santiago Varela, said ``this kind of strike is
unjustified.''
   ``It threatens the constitutionally guaranteed right of
education for students and impedes further talks in search of a
reasonable and just solution,'' Varela added.
   The National Confederation of Student Associations has
criticized the teachers' indefinite strike, as has the National
Confederation of Parents of Students.
</TEXT>
