<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Graham-VP     05-31 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Graham-VP,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Democrats Promote Graham for Vice President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Michael Dukakis moves closer to the
Democratic presidential nomination, some Florida Democrats are
pressing him to choose Sen. Bob Graham as his running mate.
   Rep. Bill Grant, for one, is heading a group of Floridians
writing Graham-promoting letters to Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis, as
well as to uncommitted Democratic delegates and other party leaders.
   The group has distributed 500 ``Graham for V.P.'' buttons, and
Grant said a formal committee will be put together as the
Graham-backers expand.
   ``We're trying to create a national awareness that he is a
viable possibility,'' said Grant, adding that the committee hopes
to flood the national convention in July with Graham banners, signs
and stickers.
   Another active Graham supporter is state AFL-CIO President Dan
Miller.
   ``Bob Graham is not only a favorite son, he's a very strong
candidate,'' Miller said. ``He was a very popular Southern
governor, and he would bring a Southern flavor to the ticket.''
   Other Florida Democrats have mixed feelings about the effort by
Graham supporters, one of the better organized efforts across the
country to promote possible vice presidential candidates.
   Though many Democrats want Dukakis, a Northeasterner, to pick a
Southerner, Graham isn't the most frequently mentioned possibility
from that region.
   ``Not to take anything away from Bob Graham because Graham is
very qualified, but my strong recommendation would be Sam Nunn,''
the Georgia senator, said William Boyd, a Tallahassee attorney and
Dukakis supporter.
   Graham's press secretary, Ken Klein, said in Washington,
``Senator Graham is not seeking a spot on the ticket. He is not
active in trying to make the phone ring. He has been flattered by
the suggestion that it might ring.''
   Meanwhile, state Party Chairman Charles Whitehead feels pulled
in two directions.
   ``The greatest thing for me as party chairman would be Bob
Graham on the ticket, because I believe that would ensure us of
carrying Florida,'' Whitehead said. ``But the worst thing for me
would be to have Gov. Bob Martinez get to appoint a senator.''
   If Graham were elected vice president, the Republican governor
would appoint someone to serve as senator until a special election
in 1990.
</TEXT>
