<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Austria-Waldheim     05-31 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Austria-Waldheim,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Waldheim to Visit Saudi Arabia; Other Middle East Trips Postponed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Kurt Waldheim will make an
official visit to Saudi Arabia this month, his chancellory
announced Tuesday.
   The visit is scheduled for June 4-6.
   The statement said planned visits to the United Arab Emirates
and Kuwait have been postponed because of an upcoming Arab summit
in Algiers.
   Waldheim, who was elected in June 1986, has not been invited or
received by any Western heads of state because of allegations about
his World War II past.
   He visited Pope John Paul II in June 1987 and visited Jordan a
month later at the invitation of King Hussein, whom Waldheim
welcomed in Vienna earlier this year.
   An international commission of historians in February questioned
Waldheim's moral integrity as a second lieutenant serving in the
German army in the Balkans during World War II.
   It said Waldheim knew of Nazi war crimes but did nothing to
prevent them. It left open the question of whether he was guilty of
atrocities.
   Waldheim has denied any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
