<1ST_LINE>u a PM-NearCollision 1stLd-Writethru a0502 05-31 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Near Collision, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0502,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jetliner Narrowly Misses Light Plane Near Cleveland Airport</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout without FAA confirmation, quotes from flight
attendant</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Continental Airlines DC-9 with 84 people
aboard narrowly misseda small plane when the
jetliner's pilot took evasive action while preparing to land, a
Federal Aviation Administration official said today.
   The encounter occurred in restricted air space at about 7,000
feet Monday afternoon about 5  colliding with miles southeast of Cleveland-Hopkins
International Airport.
   ``The small plane did not show up on radar. We don't know if he
had a transponder or, if he had one, if it was on,'' said spokesman
Mort Edelstein from his Chicago office. A transponder makes an
aircraft more visible on radar.
   Flight attendant Milotka Liebelt was injured as Continental
Flight 283 made a sharp climbing turn to the left. She was treated
at Southwest General Hospital for bruises to her batain explained the incident
to passengers after they landed in
Cleveland.
   ``Thank God that our first officer responded instantly,'' said
Mrs. Liebelt, who has been a flight attendant for a year.
   She said the passengers remained calm and none were injured
because they were all in their seats in preparation for landing.
   The Continental pilot reported the incident to the FAA as a near
collision, estimating the distance between the planes as 100 feet
vertically and the span of the DC-9's wing horizontally.
   Small planes entering restricted airspace near airports are
required to get tower permission and to carry transponders.
   There was no immediate indication whether the private plane also
took evasive action, or whether its pilot even saw the airliner.
The Continental pilot told the FAA that he gained 800 feet of
altitude in making his maneuver. The airliner landed safely in
Cleveland.
</TEXT>
