<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-MineBlast     05-31 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Mine Blast,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fishing Boat Hits Mine, One Fisherman Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small fishing boat hit a mine in the
Gulf of Oman today and exploded, killing one fisherman and injuring
the two others on board, United Arab Emirates officials said.
   The official Emirates News Agency quoted an Interior Ministry
statement as saying the blast occurred off Dednah, about 20 miles
south of the entrance to the Strait of Hormuz and the Persian Gulf.
   The Interior Ministry said all the victims were Indians. The two
survivors were rescued by another fishing boat and taken to
Fujairah for treatment.
   The area where the explosion occurred is just north of an
anchorage off Khor Fakkan used by tankers and other commercial
vessels. The anchorage is the staging area for U.S. Navy-escorted
convoys of American-flagged Kuwaiti tankers.
   At least two vessels hit mines in the area last autumn. One, a
small offshore supply boat, sank with the loss of six crewmen.
   The previous mine explosions, which U.S. and other officials
blamed on Iran, prompted United Arab Emirate authorities to close
the anchorage temporarily. No mines had been reported in the Gulf
of Oman for several months.
   The United States reflagged the Kuwaiti vessels to protect them
from attacks that are an offshoot of the 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
</TEXT>
