<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TropicalWeather     05-31 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tropical Weather,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Year's First Tropical Depression Forms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The year's first tropical depression has formed 150
miles southwest of Havana just in time to inaugurate the 1988
Atlantic hurricane season, forecasters announced today.
   ``We don't expect significant strengthening,'' said
meteorologist Randy Lascody of the National Hurricane Center.
``Generally the winds at this time of the year are not favorable
for that.''
   Even if the weather system's 30 mph winds did strengthen, its
current 5 mph north-northwest course would take it across Cuba,
probably breaking up the depression, he said.
   The Caribbean system is expected to continue its path through
Wednesday, when a reconnaisance plane will investigate.
   For a depression to be upgraded to a named storm, winds must
reach 39 mph, and the system becomes a hurricane only when it
breaks the 74 mph barrier.
   The 1988 Atlantic hurricane season officially begins Wednesday.
</TEXT>
