<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GroceryMergers     05-31 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grocery Mergers,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Approves Major Grocery Takeovers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of acquisitions involving four major
Western grocery chains won tentative approval Tuesday from the
Federal Trade Commission.
   In one case, American Stores Co. will be allowed to acquire
Lucky Stores Inc., provided that American sells off between 31 and
37 stores in California plus its interest in a Midwestern chain.
   In the second instance, Vons Companies Inc. will be allowed to
acquire three Safeway divisions with stores in Southern California
and Nevada, provided a dozen California stores are sold to other
companies.
   Both acquisitions were approved by 3-1 votes, with Commissioner
Mary L. Azcuenaga dissenting. The vote opens both mergers to public
comment, after which the commission will make the decision final.
   Under terms of the FTC approval, American stores promised to
sell at least 31 and possibly as many as 37 stores in California
within six months after the merger. In addition, it will sell its
half interest in Eagle Food Centers, a Midwestern chain.
   In their agreement with the commission, Vons and Safeway agreed
to sell 12 stores to other companies before completing Vons
takeover of the three Safeway divisions.
   American Stores, based in Salt Lake City, Utah, operates
supermarkets across the nation under the names American, Acme,
Alpha Beta and Jewell. Lucky is based in Dublin, Calif.
   Vons is based in El Monte, Calif., while Safeway has its
headquarters in Oakland, Calif.
</TEXT>
