<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1442EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Yeltsin     05-31 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commentators Take Issue With Fallen Leader's Claims Of Soviet Rift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two prominent Soviet political commentators on
Tuesday disputed former Moscow Communist Party boss Boris N.
Yeltsin's claim that the Kremlin's No. 2 official is blocking
economic and social reforms.
   Yeltsin, in an unprecedented public airing of high-level Kremlin
disagreement, told the British Broadcasting Corp. in a television
interview Monday that Yegor K. Ligachev should resign.
   Feodor Burlatsky, a former member of the party's policy-making
Central Committee who writes for the weekly Literaturnaya Gazeta,
said Ligachev would face severe punishment if he were a true
opponent of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms.
   ``If Ligachev has his own views, it is only natural. It is
another thing to lead some conservatives, and I think this is not a
fact. ... I don't think that anybody leads some opposition. It is
just impossible in our political system. If such a person appears
on the political scene, he would be out of the leadership,''
Burlatsky told reporters.
   Alexei Arbatov, deputy director of the Institute for
International Economy and International Relations, said he
disagreed with Yeltsin that Ligachev is blocking reform. ``I also
can express my opinion and I do not agree with Mr. Yeltsin. Those
opinions are those of Mr. Yeltsin,'' Arbatov said in an interview.
   The 67-year-old Ligachev, who oversees Communist Party ideology,
has indicated in speeches he feels Gorbachev's policy of
``glasnost,'' or open discussion of the country's problems, has
gone too far in denouncing most of the economic and social policies
of the past.
   Yeltsin said in the interview that Ligachev should go ``because
the party is still lagging behind, because the process of
democratization in the party is not developing...and Comrade
Ligachev is the main person responsible for this.''
   Arbatov's father, Georgy, a Central Committee member who heads
the Institute for the Study of the U.S.A. and Canada, took issue
with Yeltsin on another point _ his decision to give the interview
to the BBC, as well as one to CBS News.
   ``In our point of view I don't think it was too correct for him
to do it, but that is my personal opinion,'' he told a news
conference.
   Yeltsin, 57, was removed Feb. 18 as a candidate, or non-voting,
member of the ruling Politburo. His problems began when he made a
speech to the Central Committee on Oct. 21, 1987 in which he said
Gorbachev's reforms were going to slowly and attacked Ligachev.
   On Nov. 11, the Moscow Communist Party Committee had fired
Yeltsin.
   At the time, Gorbachev accused Yeltsin of using immature words
and of radical actions and said he ``placed his personal ambitions
above the interests of the party.''
   Removed from the Politburo, he was named to the Cabinet-level
position of deputy head of the State Construction Committee. He
lost his job on the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the country's
nominal legislature, on May 4.
   As Moscow party boss, Yeltsin stood out for his brusque,
aggressive manner and populist style. He was popular among
Muscovites for criticizing consumer shortages and sometimes
striding into stores to take his complaints straight to shopkeepers.
   Rumors circulated in Moscow in mid-April that Ligachev and
Gorbachev had a bitter face-off, with Ligachev reportedly backing a
newspaper article defending the late dictator Josef V. Stalin and
Gorbachev supposedly counterattacking through another article
pushing radical reforms.
   The two have made several public appearances together since
then, with no obvious sign of disagreements.
</TEXT>
