<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1452EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StateSymbolsRdp     05-31 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Symbols Rdp,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Butterflies Take Wing, Others Don't</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia enshrined the tiger swallowtail and Utah embraced the
allosaurus, but no such warm welcome awaited the banana slug in
California or the monarch butterfly in West Virginia.
   The fate of these and other creatures was debated in
legislatures across the nation this year, part of the time-honored
custom of naming official state symbols for everything from fish to
fossils, from mollusks to muffins.
   Critics say the practice wastes time and holds lawmakers up to
ridicule, but defenders say it can help get young people involved
in the political process, boost tourism, and provide some
beneficial comic relief.
   ``It gets so tense in there sometimes. It's just too much,''
said Rep. Mary Vanderlinde in South Dakota, where this year's
Legislature designated the triceratops, a plant-eating dinosaur, as
the state fossil and Black Hills gold as the state jewelry.
   ``This livens it up, and then people will relax and get back to
work,'' she said.
   After the gold measure was passed by the House in January,
lawmakers adopted a second resolution naming Vanderlinde the
state's official jewel because she takes gold shots for arthritis.
   Idaho adopted a fossil this year, the Hagerman Horse Fossil, a
3{-million-year-old relic found in southern Idaho's Magic Valley.
State and local officials are trying to turn the fossil beds south
of Interstate 84 into a tourist attraction to boost the economy.
   The Florida House voted in April to name the Key lime pie the
official state pie, inspired by a legislative report that
recommended the honor as ``an excellent way to promote a genuine
Florida product, since the pie can only be properly made with Key
limes from Florida.''
   However, the measure ran into trouble in the Senate, where Rules
Chairman Dempsey Barron favors sweet potato pie more common to the
Panhandle.
   On Thursday, the California Senate nearly squashed a measure to
name the banana slug the official mollusk, but narrowly decided to
allow the proposal to be reconsidered in the future.
   ``These things are replusive, I mean look at them.... The joke
has to stop here,'' said Sen. John Doolittle, as banana slugs oozed
around inside a glass terrarium on a cart parked on the floor of
the upper house.
   In some other actions so far this year, Georgia designated the
tiger swallowtail the state butterfly, but the West Virginia House
refused to act on a Senate measure naming the monarch butterfly the
state insect. Utah made the allosaurus the state fossil, and
Hawaii's Legislature approved making the nene, a native goose, the
state bird, and the Hibiscus the state flower.
   Last month in Pennsylvania, a House committee named a
long-extinct aquatic creature _ phacops rana _ the state fossil
after 100 Bucks County schoolchildren trooped into the committee
room and performed skits and gave speeches supporting the
appellation.
   At one point, the committee chairman, Rep. Camille George,
donned a scarf and sunglasses and held an umbrella to show the
children how fossils are formed over millions of years.
   ``There's certainly some time consumed in this, but if you're
involving a bunch of youngsters in the process ... maybe there's
nothing wrong with it,'' said Stephen MacNett, chief counsel for
Senate Republicans. ``I guess it depends on how long it takes and
when on the legislative agenda it occurs.''
   That attitude was not encouraged this year in Indiana, where
House Speaker Paul S. Mannweiler and Senate President Pro Tem
Robert D. Garton warned lawmakers not to introduce frivolous bills
for the biennial short session.
   ``It creates the wrong image for the Legislature,'' said Garton.
``It's a frivolous image. It creates the image that that's all we
do, and it detracts from the serious business.''
   Elaine Knapp, editor with the Council of State Governments in
Lexington, Ky., defended the practice of naming symbols.
   ``It's not something that takes up a great deal of attention or
time,'' she said. ``I don't think anybody expects every minute to
be taken up with something serious. Maybe it's more harmless than
raising taxes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
