<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HomeSales     05-31 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Sales,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales of New Homes at Year-High Level</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New-home sales climbed 4 percent in April to
the highest level in a year, the government said Tuesday, but
analysts said rising interest rates would likely dampen sales this
summer.
   New single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 679,000 last month, the fastest pace since new homes sold
at a rate of 728,000 in April 1987, the Commerce and Housing and
Urban Development departments said in a joint report.
   It was the third consecutive increase, coming atop a 1.2 percent
rise in March and an 11.4 percent jump in February.
   ``Overall, it's a very nice report. No question about it,'' said
David Seiders, chief economist of the National Association of Home
Builders. A survey of home builders showed sales remained strong in
early May, he said.
   ``But clearly our concern is what's been going on with interest
rates,'' Seiders said. ``... If rates move much higher, certainly
sales are going to be coming down. Our forecast is for sales
activity to peak in the second quarter.''
   Rates on 30-year, fixed-rate conventional mortgages have been
climbing steadily since late March, averaging 10.58 percent last
week, up from the low this year of 9.84 percent, according to the
Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   Warren Lasko, executive vice president of the Mortgage Bankers
Association of America, said sales could be helped in May by
purchasers hoping to beat out further increases.
   ``But by June, the bloom will be off the rose and we're going
see sales trailing off,'' he said.
   However, James Christian, chief economist of the U.S. League of
Savings Institutions, said higher rates, rather than chasing buyers
from the market, may simply cause them to switch to adjustable rate
mortgages.
   ``We've proved over and over again that adjustable rate
mortgages provide a reasonable alternative to fixed rates. Even
though both rates are moving up, you still have adjustables in what
has to be considered very affordable ranges,'' he said.
   More worrisome, Christian said, is the increase in new home
prices. The median, or midpoint, price of a new home was $110,500
in April, up 3.3 percent from March and 14.5 percent from a year
ago.
   The average price of a new home was $137,000, up 4.2 percent
from March and 16 percent over the past year.
   The recent increases in sales followed declines in the three
previous months: 1.2 percent in January, 6.2 percent in December
and 4.3 percent in November. Economists attributed them to buyers'
uncertainty following the October stock market crash.
   Sales for the first four months of this year are 9.3 percent
below the same period of 1987, when mortgage interest rates hit
nine-year lows.
   There were 671,000 new homes sold in 1987 and 750,000 sold in
1986, a record. Analysts are predicting sales in the
620,000-650,000 range this year.
   Sales increased in all regions of the country in April. They
were up 5.9 percent in the Midwest, 5.5 percent in the West, 2.9
percent in the South and 2.8 percent in the Northeast.
   In a report last week, the National Association of Realtors said
sales of existing homes increased 4.5 percent in April after
increases of 2.5 percent in both March and February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
