<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-HeatWave     05-31 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Heat Wave,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll at 280 in Record Heat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 280 people have died of
sunstroke and other heat-related illnesses in a heat wave in
northern India, news agencies reported Tuesday.
   Rajasthan state was the area hit hardest. United News of India
said 205 deaths were reported there in the past four days.
Temperatures in some parts of the state hit a record 120 degrees
Tuesday, UNI said.
   In New Delhi, at least 25 people have died, according to reports
from two major hospitals, the Press Trust of India said. The
temperature in New Delhi was 113 degrees on Tuesday.
   Water shortages and intermittent power cuts were reported in
many areas.
   The death tolls reported by the news agencies included 18 in
Maharashtra state, five in Punjab, 11 in Haryana and 18 in Uttar
Pradesh.
   Dust storms were forecast for Punjab, Haryana and neighboring
areas.
   High temperatures often precede the nation's annual monsoon
rains, critical for its agricultural economy. The rains are
expected to begin in southern states early in June. They usually do
not reach northern areas until July.
</TEXT>
