<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1502EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Poll-Questions     05-31 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poll-Questions,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Poll-Primaries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is
based on telephone interviews April 29-May 8 with 1,204 adults in
the continental United States. The phone numbers were selected
randomly by computer, and interviews were conducted with the adult
in the household who had the most recent birthday.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the
sample. The poll has a three-point margin of error, meaning the
results theoretically would be within three points of the same 19
times out of 20 if every adult American were asked the same
questions. The error margin is larger for subgroups _ six points
for the 18-29 age group, for example, and seven points for those
over 64.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions and
responses in this poll:
   1. The Republicans and Democrats use state primaries and
caucuses and nominating conventions to select their presidential
candidates. Do you think the system works well enough as it is, or
does it need major changes?
   Well enough, 38 percent. Major changes, 52 percent. Don't know
or no answer, 10 percent.
   2. Please tell me which of these statements most closely
represents your view:
   a. Presidential candidates should be selected through primaries
and caucuses followed by conventions.
   b. Presidential candidates should be selected by the voters
without any delegates or conventions.
   c. Presidential candidates should be selected by party leaders
at the conventions without any primaries and caucuses.
   Primaries, caucuses and conventions, 31 percent. Voters only, 59
percent. Party leaders only, 3 percent. Don't know or no answer, 7
percent.
   3. This year for the first time, 14 Southern or border states
voted on the same day, Tuesday, March 8. Do you think the regional
primary called Super Tuesday was a good idea?
   Yes, 48 percent. No, 27 percent. Don't know or no answer, 25
percent.
   4. Do you think regional primaries should be held in the future?
   Yes, 54 percent. No, 25 percent. Don't know or no answer, 21
percent.
   5. Generally, do you think the second-place finisher in the
nomination campaign should be the vice-presidential nominee, or
should the presidential nominee select whomever he or she wants?
   Second-place, 24 percent. Whomever, 69 percent. Don't know or no
answer, 7 percent.
   6. From among those who run for the Democratic nomination for
president, do you think the Democrats generally nominate their best
candidate?
   Yes, 46 percent. No, 40 percent. Don't know or no answer, 14
percent.
   7. From among those who run for the Republican nomination for
president, do you think the Republicans generally nominate their
best candidate?
   Yes, 52 percent. No, 36 percent. Don't know or no answer, 13
percent.
   8. Do you think the nomination campaigns usually provide a good
discussion of the issues?
   Yes, 51 percent. No, 40 percent. Don't know or no answer, 9
percent.
   9. Have you been following the presidential primary campaigns
regularly, occasionally, hardly at all or not at all this year?
   Regularly, 41 percent. Occasionally, 50 percent. Hardly, 7
percent. Not, 2 percent.
</TEXT>
