<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--BraceletFound     05-31 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bracelet Found,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diver Finds Keepsake Missing In Lake 30 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A whole Sunday school class couldn't do it,
but Jerry Callison, using a metal detector, was a success when he
wasn't even trying.
   Callison found an identification bracelet lost in Fort Gibson
Lake in 1958.
   Callison, of Broken Arrow, dives with the Indian Territory
Historical Club, which focuses on the sport of metal detecting.
Callison found the silver bracelet May 17 in 8 feet of water,
buried 3 inches in the silty bottom.
   Callison cleaned the bracelet and found J. Ned Hansen's name, a
date and the message, ``I'll be loving you always, Joyce.''
   Callison looked up Hansen's name in the telephone directory.
   Joyce Hansen said she gave the bracelet to her husband for their
third wedding anniversary, Feb. 25, 1945. Hansen said his son, Ned,
lost it while swimming in 1958.
   ``The whole Sunday school class helped him look for it,'' Hansen
said. ``He told me it had really hurt him that he'd lost it.''
</TEXT>
