<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietHonor     05-31 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Honor,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texan Greeted By Soviet Friend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kemp Forest, a World War II bomber pilot,
was recently inducted into a prestigious veterans' group _ in the
Soviet Union.
   Forty-three years ago, Forest was befriended by a group of
Soviet soldiers. after his B-17 was forced down near the front in
Poland. He and his crew spent a week with the Soviets, who repaired
the plane and threw nightly banquets in their honor.
   As a sign of that friendship, a Soviet major and his wife,
Anatoly and Tamara Koshevnikov, presented Forest with a tablecloth
inscribed, ``May your journey back be as smooth as this
tablecloth.''
   Forest, now 66, recently traveled to Moscow to meet the
Koshevnikovs again. There were tears all around, he said.
   He took part in the annual May Day parade, chatted with a priest
in a Russian Orthodox monastery and rubbed elbows with Soviet
generals, publishers and schoolchildren.
   ``Friendship between our countries has to start with someone _
let it be me,'' said Forest, a Lake Travis resident and retired
representative of a clothing manufacturer.
   ``You have to understand your neighbor before you can know him.
The trip was utterly fantastic. It was hard to describe. I have
never felt so welcome anywhere. It came straight from the heart,''
he said.
   While in Moscow, Forest was named an honorary member of the
Soviet Veterans Association and responded by making now-Gen.
Koshevnikov and his wife honorary members of the Lake Travis Lions
Club.
</TEXT>
