<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1529EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JohnstownFlood     05-31 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Johnstown Flood,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elsie Frum Remembers 1889 Disaster as `A Roar'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elsie Frum remembers running uphill from
the Johnstown Flood of 1889, which swept everything in its path,
killing 2,200 people in one of the nation's worst natural disasters.
   ``It was just like a roar. There were millions of gallons of
water, you know,'' Mrs. Frum, 105, said Tuesday. ``It came just
like a tidal wave and then it was over. Everything was washed away.
We ran. If we didn't run, I wouldn't be here today.''
   Mrs. Frum was 6 when the South Fork Dam burst and a 40-foot wall
of water and debris slammed into this western Pennsylvania steel
and railroad city 12 miles downstream.
   She and Frank Shomo, 99, of Robinson, are the two remaining
survivors of the May 31, 1889, disaster. They were to be guests of
honor at the annual Flood Survivors' Banquet on Tuesday night.
   The dam held back Lake Conemaugh and was owned by the South Fork
Fishing and Hunting Club, a summer playground for wealthy
industrialists led by Andrew Carnegie and Henry Clay Frick.
   After several days of rain, the poorly maintained dam was
breached and finally burst, unleashing a torrent of water that
cleared the Conemaugh River valley of houses, bridges and trains
before it hit Johnstown.
   Pushing ahead uprooted trees, splintered beams, dead and dying
people and farm animals, and miles of wire from a destroyed steel
mill, the watery mass crashed into a Pennsylvania Railroad bridge
just below Johnstown, where it piled up to form a temporary second
dam that soon caught fire. Many bodies never were found.
   When she was a child, Mrs. Frum's family lived in nearby
Conemaugh. As the water approached, her father grabbed his wife and
three daughters and started them running up a hill. The floodwater
passed below.
   ``It happened and then it was over,'' Mrs. Frum recalled.
``After that, it was calm like nothing happened.''
   Shomo, only 100 days old when the dam burst, lived about 20
miles downriver from Johnstown at Lockport. He said the high water
did not reach his house.
   Mrs. Frum survived another flood in 1936, stranded on the second
floor of her Johnstown house. By the area's third flood disaster,
in 1977, Mrs. Frum was living high and dry on a mountain in nearby
Southmont.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TestBurn     05-31 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Test Burn,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pershing II Rocket Motor Test Burn Completed On High Plains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials fired a rocket motor from a Pershing 2
missile on the high plains east of Denver on Tuesday, hoping to
determine whether hundreds of the motors can be safely destroyed as
required by a new U.S.-Soviet treaty.
   The burn, following 11 days of delays because of bad weather,
came on the final day open for such test firings under the
U.S.-Sov-Range Nuclear Forces treaty.
   ``From our initial indication, the burn, the static firing, was
conducted just as we had planned. And the plume _ the exhaust cloud
_ traveled with the wind over the (50) monitoring sites,'' said
Pueblo Army Depot Actiiet Intermediatevity spokeswoman Mary Wilson.
   The Colorado Department of Health monitors will analyze the
exhaust to see whether such firings would pose any threat to the
environment.
   About 20 reporters and photographers witnessed the 58-second
test at 6:36 a.m. at the depot 15 miles east of Denver, officials
said.
   ``There was a steady, bright white light from the end of the
rocket nozzle extending approximately 75-80 feet,'' Wilson said.
   The weapons treaty was ratified last week by the Senate, and
copies were scheduled to be exchanged Wednesday at the summit
meeting in Moscow between Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and
President Reagan.
   The treaty requires that the Army's 420 Pershing missiles be
destroyednal Park Service superintendents were invited to
attend the four-day gathering in Grand Teton National Park.
   The meeting, the first of its kind in 12 years, was called by
Park Service Director William Penn Mott in early 1987, but he left
most of the planning and agenda to a committee of superintendents.
   ``The program was turned over entirely to the superintendents
and they chose subject matter which focuses on current issues, both
internal and external, facing the parks today,'' said George
Berklacy, chief of public affairs for the park service. ``This is
not a regional or headquarters agenda, this conference is by and
for the superintendents.''
   T. Destry Jarvis, vice president of the National Parks and
Conservation Association, a Washington, D.C.-based nonprofit
citizens group, praised the park service for holding the
superintendents' conclave.
   ``I think it is a very serious, professional thing that they
have done,'' said Jarvis, who planned to attend as an observer. ``I
think it's very important that the National Park Service enhance
the notion that this is a single service, with a single purpose.
I'm sure they will get a lot of business done that would not occur
if they weren't together.''
   Steve Whitney of the Wilderness Society said the meeting ``is in
the best interest of the country. They (the superintendents)
shouldn't wait another decade for another one.''
   Last week the Wilderness Society issued a report calling on the
federal government to move all hotels and other concessions out of
the national parks and describing some parks as endangered.
   The Wilderness Society's assessment was just the latest in a
continuing controversy over what's best for America's officially
preserved natural heritage.
   The National Parks and Conservation Association recently issued
a report recommending a $50 million annual increase in the park
service's budget just to fix a resource management backlog of
problems.
   In 1980, the National Park Service itself issued a report to
Congress on the ``State of the Parks.'' In that summary more than
4,000 individual threats were identified.
   A recent General Accounting Office survey concluded the Park
Service had an unmet need of $1.9 billion for maintenance and
capital improvements in the 1987 fiscal year.
   ``Because of advanced, continuing deterioration, some of these
assets may be lost permanently,'' said the GAO study.
   The National Park System includes 49 full-fledged national parks
and 292 other units, including national recreation areas and
national seashore areas, encompassing a total of 77 million acres.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
