<DOCNO> AP880531-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1531EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EndangeredTurtles     05-31 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Endangered Turtles,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Program Turns Out Too Many Male Sea Turtles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A program used in some areas to hatch
endangered sea turtles is turning out too many males and must be
changed, naturalists say.
   From May to November, loggerhead and green sea turtles lay eggs
on the beach and abandon them. Eggs buried in cooler sand hatch as
males and in warmer as females, said J. Alan Huff, who heads the
state Department of Natural Resources turtle protection program.
   But some of those nests are dug up by scientists and hatched in
incubators to gurarantee a higher survival rate.
   Until recently, eggs gathered up in the John U. Lloyd State
Recreation Area here and in some other locations around Florida
have been incubated in styrofoam chests. Young turtles do not show
their gender externally, however, and scientists were unsure how
many hatchlings were male.
   But a study of 1986 hatchlings which involved a painstaking
surgical procedure has confirmed what some had suspected _ most of
the turtles from the chests are male.
   To solve the problem, the naturalists are switching to burial of
the turtles in beach sand, but with a cage surrounding them to ward
off predators, as some other South Florida hatcheries do. The cages
are placed near the shore to make the hatchlings' run from their
nest to the sea as short as possible.
   ``We don't know all the implications, and are just being
conservative and encouraging people to use beach hatcheries
whenever possible,'' said Huff. Incubating the eggs in boxes will
now be the choice of last resort, he said.
   The unbalanced sex ratio is not considered serious yet because
only about 10 percent of the turtle nests are dug up and incubated
artificially, he said.
   ``We take so few compared to the worldwide population, it's
unlikely we'd ever affect the wild population,'' he said. But the
aim of the turtle program is to simulate nature as nearly as
possible, he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ZooArrest     05-31 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zoo Arrest,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Arrested After Climbing Into Tiger Enclosure at Zoo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police seized a shirtless man who climbed atop a
zoo exhibit where a worker was mauled to death last month, thumped
his chest and traded growls with two agitated Bengal tigers.
   The incident, which occurred before about 100 Memorial Day
spectators, came a day after two of the zoo's 15 tigers were
returned to view for the first time since the May 12 mauling of
keeper Ricardo Tovar.
   Robert Lavoie, 27, was charged with criminal trespass and jailed
in lieu of a $1,000 bond, police said Tuesday. He was not injured.
   ``He was making a Tarzan call down to the tigers. He was really
aggravating the animals,'' said witness Larry Spaetgens, who
videotaped the incident. ``I thought he was going to fall. I sent
my wife away.''
   The episode underscored recent employee complaints about lax
safety. Lavoie apparently gained access to a walkway over the tiger
display through a fallen, unmarked gate while a guard was at lunch.
   Zoo officials, who ordered an investigation of safety procedures
after Tovar's death, said Monday's incident is not indicative of
lax procedures.
   ``There is no way we can protect anyone from their own
irrational acts,'' said zoo curator Nelson Herwig.
   But zoo employees have complained that the zoo's design and
management put them and the public in jeopardy. Chief among their
concerns is working alone with dangerous animals because of
staffing shortages.
   Moments before Lavoie appeared atop the 12-inch-wide wall behind
the rocks, he was lingering outside the fallen gate. The gate was
erected as a temporary measure about two years ago, Herwig said.
   ``The walkway was intended as an overview for the cat
facility,'' he said. ``It was never opened because it would be
impossible to prevent an incident such as this.''
   He said he did not know how long the gate was broken, but Zoo
Director John Werler said Lavoie was the first unauthorized person
to have gone past the barrier and into the exhibit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
