<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nicaragua-Boat     05-31 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Boat,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Yacht Reportedly Rammed Near Nicaragua, American Detained</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Tuesday it has
received unconfirmed reports that a U.S. pleasure boat was rammed
by a Nicaraguan naval vessel and that the yacht and a U.S. citizen
have been detained.
   The U.S. Embassy in Managua was trying to learn from the facts
of the case and to seek consular access to the American citizen,
spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said.
   She was not authorized to disclose the name of the American
reportedly detained.
   Ham radio operators who picked up a distress call said the
skipper identified the yacht as the Satori, based in Miami. The
incident was alleged to have taken place Monday night 20 miles off
Nicaragua's Pacific Coast.
   The skipper, whose name sounds like ``Melbourne,'' radioed that
he had been rammed and that one large gunboat was a quarter-mile
off his bow and a smaller gunboat was 100 feet off his stern,
preventing his escape, said a Honolulu ham radio operator who spoke
only on condition he not be named.
   The distress call said the vessel was taking on water as a
result of being rammed, but was not in danger of sinking, the ham
operator said.
   The Satori reportedly was en route from Honolulu to Costa Rica.
</TEXT>
