<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Spoleto-Critics     05-31 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spoleto-Critics,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Critics Praise Adventurous Spirit Of Spoleto '88</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critics are praising the adventurous
spirit of this year's Spoleto Festival U.S.A. of the performing
arts, even if some productions haven't emerged unscathed from
reviewers' pens.
   The Washington Post said Spoleto ``has often been daring, but
this year seems to be more so than usual.''
   Everywhere at this year's festival ``there is something
beguiling and new _ or so ancient it's just as challenging,'' said
USA Today.
   The main opera at the festival which continues through Sunday is
Dvorak's ``Rusalka,'' a work which is rarely performed in this
country.
   Spoleto also features the seldom-performed ``Montezuma'' by Carl
Heinrich Graun and saw the premiere of a controversial
dancer-theater piece by New York choreographer Martha Clarke.
   The Post called the Spoleto production of ``Rusalka'' ``one of
the most effective in the festival's 12-year American history.''
   But The New York Times said the staging and special effects are
the real highlights of the opera based on a Czechoslovakian fairy
tale about a water sprite.
   ``Though the singers involved were mostly good second-and
third-level professionals, the principal strengths of this staging,
at least for two of the three acts, were visual,'' the Times
reviewer said. ``Striking stage pictures came and went,
compensating to an extent for a lack of vocal excitement.''
   The State said the production ``is not to be missed by
opera-lovers. Spoleto's staging may be the only opportunity to see
this sadly neglected opera in a lifetime,'' the Columbia newspaper
said.
   ``Montezuma,'' which tells of the Spanish destruction of the
Aztec civilization in the 1500s, is performed even less frequently
and hasn't fared well with the Spoleto critics.
   The News and Courier of Charleston called the cast ``spotty''
and suggested ``it is not an opera for all to enjoy.''
   ``It did manage to give a taste of `Montezuma' however, albeit
with a merely serviceable abstract decor and conducting and singing
that was mostly insensitive and inauthentic to the period, '' wrote
The Wall Street Journal.
   USA Today called Ms. Clarke's ``Miracolo D'Amore'' ``a delicious
little scandal'' for the festival.
   The work, which conjures sometimes violent images of love,
features some nudity and has caused a stir among Spoleto audiences.
A number of people have walked out of the historic Dock Street
Theater before the end of the performances.
   ``Viewed with a calm, receptive eye, `Miracolo d'Amore' is a
profoundly impressive, tight, lucid piece,'' said USA Today.
   ``The naked women evoke Botticelli, and the lyrics and minuscule
amount of text are all in Italian, making for a rather remote
experience if you don't get the references,'' The Wall Street
Journal said. ``It's either a dream or a bore, depending on whom
you ask.''
   One reviewer for The News and Courier called the work
``unsettling'' and described it as ``a hateful piece, bitter and
malevolent. As a theater work it's visually beautiful. But then, so
is a coral snake.''
   Another reviewer for the paper suggested ``this is clearly a
work of _ dare I say it? _ feminist revenge.''
   The reviewer added Ms. Clarke ``has wrought a theatrical
experience that will affect different people in radically, one
might say almost violently, different ways.''
   Composer Gian Carlo Menotti founded the Festival of the Two
Worlds in Spoleto, Italy, in 1958, and later founded the Spoleto
Festival U.S.A. in Charleston and the Spoleto Festival of the Three
Worlds in Melbourne, Australia. He still heads all of them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1922EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Elections     05-31 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Elections,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Says It Will Boycott June 19 Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Solidarity trade union federation
announced Tuesday it is boycotting nationwide elections June 19 for
local and provincial councils.
   ``The boycott will be an expression of our resistance to the
deprivation of our rights. It will be an expression on striving for
regaining of social sovereignty,'' Solidarity's national executive
commission said in a communique released by spokesman Janusz
Onyszkiewicz.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said earlier that the
government was prepared for opponents to mount a boycott.
   The vote will be the first held under a new election law that
requires at least two candidates for each seat, secret ballots and
allows various social groups to propose candidates.
   But the ballot continues to be structured in such a way that
Poland's Communist Party is guaranteed a majority of the seats on
the municipal and provincial councils.
   For most seats, only communist party candidates are nominated.
Allied political parties and independents are also allotted a
certain number of seats fixed beforehand by nominating commissions.
   Urban defended the arrangement at his weekly news conference
Tuesday, saying the public will be able to show its preference for
individuals although not for parties.
   But the statement by the outlawed Solidarity movement said any
hopes that Poles would be able to elect candidates ``freely and
democratically ... were in vain.''
   ``Instead of returning to us our rights, we were offered
participation in a show ... Disguising the old practice in which it
is decided for the citizens who can represent them,'' Solidarity
said.
   Solidarity initially had discussed trying to nominate candidates
for the council elections, the first to be held in Poland since
1984.
   But the electoral law passed March 10 said only legal groups
could propose candidates, and it left the final ballot composition
in the hands of the electoral commissions dominated by the party.
   ``This electoral procedure gives us no chances in practice,''
said Warsaw regional Solidarity leader Zbygniew Bujak.
   But Urban said ``many representatives of independent communities
were proposed to be candidates (and) most of them refused because,
as they stated, the electoral procedure wasn't democratic enough
for them.''
   He called it a ``vicious circle. ... They want more democracy
but don't want to take advantage of existing possibilities.''
   Urban also said the government does not fear a boycott and would
not, as in the past, interpret the eventual turnout figures as a
barometer of public support for the government.
   ``Experience shows that these boycotts have minimal effect on
electoral attendance,'' he said.
   In Poland's last nationwide election, the Nov. 29 referendum on
government plans for economic and political reform, 67.3 percent of
the 26.2 million eligible voters participated. It was the lowest
announced turnout of any election in Poland's postwar history.
   Both referendum questions were approved by a majority of votes
cast. But the low turnout prevented them from receiving approval by
more than half all eligible voters, as required by law for the
results to be legally binding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0160 </DOCNO>
