<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FireworksAccident     05-31 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fireworks Accident,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fireworks Producer Says He Can Account for Shells</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of a fireworks production at
which a shell exploded, injuring 27 people, said Tuesday he can
account for all the shells that were fired and the exploding one
may have come from somewhere else.
   ``We haven't been able to substantiate that,'' said Lt. Arnold
Meyers, who heads the arson abatement investigating the Sunday
evening accident during the annual Dayton River Festival.
   Thirteen people remained hospitalized, all but one in good or
fair condtion. Steven Stevens, 34, of Springfield, was in serious
condition.
   Rick W. Leibert, producer for National Fireworks Ensemble of Los
Angeles, believes the shell that exploded came from somewhere other
than the launch area, about 600 feet from the bank of the
Stillwater River where it hit.
   The shells, which normally travel 350 to 500 feet in the air
before exploding, are fired off electrically. All 1,500, ranging
from 3 to 13 inches in diameter, were sequenced and timed according
to a script, Leibert said.
   ``When we looked at the videotape, the bursts were all in the
sky where they should be when they were supposed to be,'' he said.
   Meyers, who said investigators had about 40 more witnesses to
interview, said an inspection of the site yielded little conclusive
information.
   ``We found a lot of debris along on the bank, and some of the
markings were not of the type that the show uses,'' he said. ``Yet
we didn't have any odor of gunpowder on it'' which would indicate a
recently fired shell, he said.
   He said it would be several days before anything conclusive can
be released.
   ``Most people were looking at the sky and weren't paying any
attention. We'll get lucky if we find two of three people that saw
something that don't have a claim in this,'' Meyers said.
   San Diego Fireworks of California, which supplied the shells and
the necessary state and federal licenses, carried the $1 million
umbrella insurance policy required by the city, Leibert said.
   Fire Chief Glenn Alexander said the shell appeared to explode
twice. Leibert said his show did not use any ``double-banger''
shells.
   Any drifting debris from the launching site also should have
been pushed away from the accident scene by the prevailing winds,
he said.
   Meyers said that if the shell had come from the launch site, it
must have come out of a launch tube, turned sharply right and
skimmed 15 or 20 feet above the ground until hitting the bank.
   Leibert said the ensemble's most recent show was for the
Kentucky Derby weekend in Louisville and its next show would be the
July 4 celebration in Columbus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HolidayTraffic     05-31 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holiday Traffic,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memorial Day Accidents Claim At Least 385 Lives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traffic accidents claimed the lives of at least
385 people on the nation's roads during the three-day Memorial Day
weekend, authorities said Tuesday.
   Based on ``the past trends of the Memorial Day holiday period,''
the National Safety Council had projected 380 to 480 people would
die in traffic accidents, said council spokeswoman Barbara Carraro.
   The preliminary total late Tuesday morning ``is right around the
normal'' for a non-holiday, three-day weekend, Ms. Carraro said.
   Generally, she said, more people die in accidents on holiday
weekends because automobiles carry more people. The three-day
holiday period began at 6 p.m. Friday, local time, and ended at
midnight Monday.
   During last year's Memorial Day weekend, 416 people died in
traffic accidents, the Chicago-based council said.
   The worst Memorial Day traffic toll in the last quarter-century
was recorded in 1968, when 629 people died. The lowest recorded
toll, in 1982, was 341.
   About 390 traffic deaths on U.S. roadways would be projected for
a non-holiday, three-day weekend this time of year, council
statistics clerk Mary Johnston said.
</TEXT>
