<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     05-31 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Hyundai Worker Stabs Himself In Dispute Over Wages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A striking Hyundai worker tried to
commit ritual suicide in Ulsan on Tuesday in a dispute over wage
increases, and police were asked to free 11 Hyundai executives
taken hostage by strikers in Changwon.
   Yoon Jung-han, 28, was in critical condition at a hospital after
plunging a knife into his abdomen before hundreds of colleagues at
a plant in Ulsan, an industrial city on the southeast coast. Yoon
fell to the ground with blood gushing out of a deep cut in his
abdomen, witnesses said.
   The worker took the action when he was asked by union leaders to
stop a speech to striking workers at the plant owned by Hyundai
Precision and Industry Co., a major manufacturer of train cars,
witnesses said. The company is a subsidiary of the Hyundai Motor
Co., the nation's leading automaker.
   Hyundai Motor's assembly line in Ulsan was shut down after more
than 80 percent of union members voted for a strike to press their
demand for wage increases, company officials said.
   About 20,000 Hyundai Motor Co. workers halted production Monday
and walked out in the salary dispute, the officials said.
   The Hyundai workers demanded wage increases of up to $177. The
company offered an increase of $54.
   Hyundai workers with five to six years of experience now earn
about $821 a month, including bonuses and other allowances, the
company said.
   On Friday, 2,000 workers at a Hyundai Precision plant in the
southern city of Changwon held 11 company executives hostage in
offices inside the plant, including chairman Chung Mong-ku and
president Yoo Ki-chul.
   After repeated efforts to free the executives, Hyundai officials
on Tuesday asked police to intervene. The striking workers refused
to back down and blocked all gates to the plant with containers and
trucks.
   Police officials said they would ``wait until the last moment''
to solve the situation without using force. But one police officer
said intervention was inevitable if the workers did not free the
executives ``in a day or two.''
   Police officials said they also needed to investigate an
incident on Friday in which two Hyundai officials were beaten
unconcious by striking workers as they tried to leave the plant in
Changwon. One official remained in criticial condition at a
hospital after brain surgery and the other was listed in serious
condition with head injuries.
   Cabinet ministers met Tuesday to discuss the situation and said
the government would deal sternly with those who broke the law.
   In another development, the U.S. government on Tuesday said it
supported the right of South Korean demonstrators to express their
opinions about the United States, as long as their protests remain
non-violent.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley was asked by
reporters in Washington to comment on recent anti-U.S.
demonstrations in South Korea.
   ``We support the right of free expression, of opinion. We
certainly understand people's wanting to express themselves, but we
strongly oppose the use of violence,'' she said.
   Radicals and students have held demonstrations in recent weeks
demanding the removal of 42,000 U.S. troops in South Korea.
   Thousands of students shouting ``Yankee go home!'' on Monday
joined a Seoul funeral procession for a dissident student who
committed suicide. Police fired tear gas when students burned a
U.S. flag, and a handful of students then threw firebombs at the
police.
