<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis Bjt   05-31 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Plans to Be a Frequent Flyer in Weeks Before Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis expects to clinch the Democratic
presidential nomination next week and then, skipping the
traditional break after the final primaries, immediately begin his
fall campaign with trips to more than a dozen states before the
July convention.
   Dukakis aides say the Massachusetts governor wants to broaden
his exposure throughout the country. His trips will include states
considered vital to his chances in the fall, including Florida and
Texas, Republican strongholds in recent presidential elections.
   ``We want to spend a good part of June out there in America,
traveling, telling people who Mike Dukakis is and why he would be a
good president,'' said Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach.
   California, New Jersey, New Mexico and Montana hold the final
primaries June 7. Five days later Dukakis will attend a National
Conference of Mayors convention in Salt Lake City. His schedule
then calls for a swing through Texas, Florida, Georgia, Kentucky
and North Carolina.
   At the end of June, Dukakis plans to visit several Midwest
states, including Wisconsin, Illinois, Minnesota and Michigan. He
also plans another trip to California and other Western states in
early July. The Democratic National Convention is July 18-21 in
Atlanta.
   Vice President George Bush, who has enough delegate votes for
the Republican nomination, plans campaigning in Texas and Colorado
June 9-11 but is scheduled to spend the rest of June and all of
July either in Washington or at his summer home in Maine, a
campaign spokeswoman said.
   During the six weeks between the final primaries and the
Democratic convention, Dukakis also will have to select a running
mate and plot convention strategy, in addition to his state duties.
But aides say he can take care of business while traveling.
   Democratic Party chairmen in Florida and Texas said Tuesday they
viewed early and frequent Dukakis appearances in their states as
vital to the Massachusetts governor's chances of winning them in
November.
   ``I certainly think it is imperative that he start early because
he is not really well known in Texas,'' said Texas Democratic Party
Chairman Bob Slagle. ``He has a reasonable chance in Texas. I
wholly agree with the strategy.''
   Dukakis will attend the Texas Democratic convention June 17-18,
when more than 10,000 state delegates and alternates will be on
hand.
   Bush represented Texas in Congress and claims the state as his
home. But recent polls have shown Dukakis close behind Bush _ and
leading the vice president in a hypothetical race with Texas Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen as his running mate.
   Slagle said Dukakis' fluent Spanish has made him popular among
Mexican-American voters, and he predicted Dukakis also would win
overwhelming black support in the fall. To beat Bush in Texas,
Dukakis will have to do well among working-class voters who are
traditionally Democrats but who supported President Reagan in 1980
and 1984, Slagle said.
   Charles Whitehead, the Florida party chairman, was equally
enthusiastic about Dukakis' fall chances in his state. Dukakis won
the Florida and Texas primaries in March.
   ``I think it can make the difference in whether or not we win
Florida.'' Whitehead said of the planned Dukakis visit. He said the
latest poll in Florida showed Bush with a slight lead over Dukakis.
As in Texas, the poll showed Dukakis winning if he picks a favorite
son running mate, in this instance Florida Sen. Bob Graham.
   In 1984, Reagan and former Vice President Walter Mondale relaxed
their campaign schedules between the final primaries and the
conventions. But Reagan was an incumbent president and Mondale also
was well known.
   As for Dukakis' plan, Bob Beckel, who managed the Mondale
campaign, said, ``I think it's a very smart move for Dukakis to do
that. It gives him a chance to work on his general election
message. Being out there and being seen will go a long way.''
</TEXT>
