<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoatCapsizes     05-31 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boat Capsizes,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coroner Rules Deaths of Seven Drowning Victims Accidental</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COFFEEVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A holiday joy ride in an overcrowded
aluminum boat turned to tragedy when six young women drowned about
30 yards from the short of a lake, along with a man who tried to
rescue them.
   Funeral home officials who met with the families of the seven
victims said they hoped to complete arrangements by Wednesday
morning.
   Yalobusha County Coroner Stanley True said Monday he had ruled
the deaths accidental. ``There were several people that witnessed
the accident,'' he said. ``It was one of those tragic things.''
   The bodies were recovered in eight to 10 feet of water near the
boat, True said.
   Robert Armstrong, 32, who was operating the 16-foot,
flat-bottomed aluminum boat, said the occupants were on a slow
``joy ride,'' splashing water on each other when the accident
occurred Monday afternoon.
   ``One girl leaned over when the boat was turning and some water
started coming in the boat and everybody panicked,'' said
Armstrong, who admitted that the boat was overloaded.
   ``Everybody stood up and started moving around in the boat,''
said Armstrong. ``Then it turned over. They was just hollering
`Help. Help. Help.' Couldn't none of them swim.''
   ``There were about 35 or 40 people on the shore and I was
saying, `Somebody help us.' People on the shore kind of panicked. A
couple people fainted,'' he said.
   True identified the victims as sisters Anna Martin, 21, and
Marlee Martin, 20; their cousin, Janice Martin, 20; Sherry Taylor,
21; Sandra Baker, 24, and Sherry Jenkins, 19.
   Eddie Lee Rounds, 41, died after swimming from the shore in an
attempt to rescue the women, True said.
   Another boat passenger, Melvin Pernell, who still clinging to
the boat when he was rescued by a fisherman was reported in stable
condition Tuesday at Grenada Lake Medical Center.
   Witnesses told the Yalobusha County Sheriff's Department that
the boat had traveled about 30 yards from the shore of 25-acre Lake
Tillatoba in rural, north-central Mississippi when the accident
occurred. The group went to the lake for a fish fry and barbecue.
   The boat, according to Deputy Sheriff Homer Melton, was powered
by a 25-horsepower outboard motor and was designed to hold four or
five people. True said no life jackets were on the boat, but
Armstrong said there were two, though neither was worn.
   Three of the girls, Armstrong said, held hands when the boat
overturned and were still holding hands when their bodies were
recovered.
</TEXT>
