<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Churches     05-31 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Churches,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clergymen Call For Non-Violence Resistance In South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid clergymen ended an
unprecedented emergency conference Tuesday with a church service at
which they called for intensified non-violent resistance to the
government.
   ``We are determined we are going to obey God whatever the
cost,'' said Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu. ``We are on the
march!'' he shouted as a mostly black audience of 1,200 people
shouted, cheered and whistled.
   The 1984 Nobel Peace Prize winner then removed symbolic gags
from the mouths of black and white youths on the podium, took up a
wooden cross and carried it back and forth down the center aisle of
the Regina Mundi Cathedral. The audience held hands and swayed
together, singing ``We Shall Overcome.''
   Participating church leaders said they would try to mobilize
support for a three-day national protest planned next week by black
trade unions.
   They also disclosed plans for a campaign seeking release of
political prisoners, to start June 12 and end July 18 _ the 70th
birthday of jailed African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela.
   The Rev. Frank Chikane, general secretary of the South African
Council of Churches, said: ``We are not trying to undermine
authority or advocate anarchy. We are distinguishing between two
different kinds of authority.''
   The Rev. Allan Boesak, mixed-race leader of the World Alliance
of Reformed Churches, said he wanted the convocation to adopt a
stronger statement calling for more protests and direct
confrontation with the government.
   ``I was hoping the convocation would ask for a personal
commitment that not all church leaders are ready to make either in
their personal capacities or on behalf of the churches,'' said
Boesak. ``It will take time. But we are moving away from a theology
of protest to a life of protest, and resistance.''
   Chikane said there was division among the church leaders, the
largest group in many years to gather to discuss action against
white domination.
   He said the decision to support the national protest next week
was significant but added that the church leaders had decided to
form a committee to work out details of specific actions.
   During the convocation, workshops were held to discuss a range
of anti-apartheid tactics, including ``non-cooperation and
non-collaboration'' with the government. The agenda suggested that
targets of civil disobedience could include tax payments, military
service and racially oriented laws such as those mandating
segregated residential areas.
   People attending the church service were asked to take these and
other proposals back to their congregations for consideration.
   The convocation was sponsored by the South African Council of
Churches, which includes major Protestant denominations active in
the fight for black rights. Also participating were the Roman
Catholic Church and a number of independent African churches.
   Organizers said political conditions in the country have
worsened since leading clergymen decided in early February to
organize the convocation.
   They cited the effective bannings of 17 anti-apartheid
organizations, the closure of two opposition newspapers, and
pending legislation to restrict labor unions and opposition
political groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
