<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Pakistan     05-31 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Pakistan,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Expresses Hope For Prompt Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed hope Tuesday
that Pakistani President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq will follow his
dismissal of the prime minister with prompt, free and fair
elections.
   Spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Zia's decision to fire Prime
Minister Mohammed Khan Junejo last weekend appeared to be within
rules set by the Pakistani constitution.
   ``We note President Zia's May 30th statement that there will be
no reversion to martial law, and that basic freedoms, including
speech, press and assembly, remain intact. We also note the
president's statement on holding national elections. We hope that
those elections will be held promptly, and that they will be free
and fair,'' she said.
   Zia, who came to power in a coup in 1977, granted power to a
civilian government three years ago, but the constitution permits
the president to dismiss the government if he feels there has been
a breakdown of law and order. The constitution provides for
elections to be held within 90 days.
   Asked if the United States would send officials to monitor the
elections, Mrs. Oakley said, ``all that is very premature. I'm sure
we'll be watching as the election process develops.''
   Pakistan's $645 million in U.S. aid for the current fiscal year
puts it third on the list of nations receiving American assistance,
behind only Israel and Egypt. Zia's country receives so much
because it acts as a funnel for aid to U.S.-backed resistance
forces in Afghan and provides a haven for more than two million
refugees from the Afghanistan war.
   Mrs. Oakley said the assistance would not be affected by the
political developments in Pakistan.
</TEXT>
