<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     05-31 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Appeals For Safety Of Kidnapped Editor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anonymous caller to a Bogota radio
station on Tuesday said a newspaper editor was kidnapped to force
the government to suspend the extradition of drug traffickers to
the United States.
   ``We are The Extraditables,'' the man told Radio Todelar in a
reference to a group that identifies itself with Colombian drug
traffickers that the United States has sought to extradite for
prosecution.
   The man said he and his associates abducted Alvaro Gomez Hurtado
on Sunday in Bogota. Gomez Hurtado, who is also a Conservative
Party leader, was kidnapped by four men carrying machine guns who
shot and killed his bodyguard.
   The caller also said the kidnappers want to exchange Gomez
Hurtado for Carlos Lehder Rivas, a reputed leader of Colombia's
so-called Medellin drug cartel who was convicted in the United
States on drug trafficking charges.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley was
asked about the possibility of an exchange of Gomez Hurtado for
Lehder.
   ``We don't deal. We don't make concessions,'' she said. ``We
deplore this act of violence, whether it emanates from the
traffickers, the violent left or right .... We offer his family and
friends our hope he will be released soon.''
   However, a statement signed by ``The Extraditables'' denied the
group was involved in the kidnapping. Reporters in Medellin, who
received the statement about five hours after the call to the radio
station, said it appeared to be authentic, based on previous
releases from the same group on other matters.
   The voice of the 69-year-old Gomez Hurtado was heard on the
radio station Monday saying: ``Oh, Oh, I'm dying.'' His wife and
daughter said the call should be taken seriously and they asked the
kidnappers for more details.
   The family said it had received an anonymous call and issued a
public appeal to the kidnappers for medical attention for Gomez
Hurtado, saying a team of doctors was standing by and that his
blood type is A positive.
   ``We demand that the government not extradite any more
Colombians to the United States. Furthermore, we don't accept that
our comrade Carlos Lehder is condemned to life imprisonment,'' the
anonymous caller told the radio station.
   Another caller to the radio station, who said he was among the
gunmen, said Monday that Gomez Hurtado had died from wounds
sustained during his abduction.
   But the man who called the radio station Tuesday said Gomez
Hurtado's injuries in an arm and a foot were not serious.
   ``We have Gomez Hurtado, injured,'' the man said, adding that he
had been taken Monday night by helicopter to Medellin, Colombia's
second-largest city, 250 miles northwest of Bogota.
   Lehder was convicted in May in federal court in Florida on
charges that he smuggled 3.3 tons of cocaine from Colombia to the
United States through the Bahamas. He was captured in a Colombian
jungle and flown to Florida for trial.
   Relatives of Gomez Hurtado, who also is a former presidential
candidate, say they were threatened earlier this year by the drug
traffickers because of his intense anti-drug campaign in his
newspaper El Siglo.
</TEXT>
