<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FarmPrices     05-31 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Prices,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Increase in Farm Prices Reported for May</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices farmers got for raw products in May
averaged 3.1 percent over April levels and were 4.7 percent over
their mark for the same month last year, the Agriculture Department
said Tuesday.
   ``Higher prices for hogs, oranges, soybeans and broilers were
partially offset by lower prices for tomatoes, onions, milk and
upland cotton,'' the department's Agricultural Statistics Board
said in its preliminary report.
   May farm commodity prices averaged 134 percent of a 1977 base
used for comparison, according to the preliminary figures. A year
ago the index was 128.
   Hog prices climbed to their highest levels since October on
average, while cattle rose to the top levels since May 1979.
Soybeans marked the largest month-to month increase in more than
four years, 58 cents a bushel, and broilers were 5.5 cents a pound
over their April mark.
   According to USDA economists, net cash income of farmers set a
record of about $57 billion in 1987. This year's net _ the
difference between cash receipts and cash expenses _ may be in the
$50 billion-$55 billion range.
   Consumer food prices are expected to rise 2 percent to 4 percent
this year, compared with a 4.2 percent average increase in 1987.
   Preliminary May figures, based mainly on mid-month averages,
showed livestock and poultry prices up 2.7 percent from both April
and May 1987.
   ``Higher prices for hogs, broilers and beef cattle more than
offset lower prices for milk, eggs and calves,'' USDA said.
   Crop prices overall were up 4.5 percent from April and 7.4
percent above the levels of a year ago.
   The price index for oil-bearing crops, which consist mainly of
soybeans, was up 7.4 percent from the previous month and 26 percent
above the May 1987 level.
   Prices paid to commercial vegetable growers decreased 12 percent
from April's levels and 11 percent from last year. USDA attributed
most of the change to lower prices for tomatoes, onions and sweet
corn.
   The report also said:
   Cattle averaged $70 per 100 pounds of live weight nationally, up
from $69 in April and the $63 reported for May 1987. Those are
averages for all types of cattle sold as beef.
   Hogs averaged $46.90 per 100 pounds, compared with $41.90 in
March and $54.40 a year earlier.
   Corn, at $1.89 a bushel, was up from $1.88 in April and well
over lastyear's mark of $1.66.
   Wheat prices at the farm, according to the preliminary figures,
averaged $2.83 a bushel, up from $2.79 last month and $2.66 a year
earlier.
   Rice averaged $8.27 per 100 pounds, down slightly from $8.33
last month but still far above the year-ago figure of $3.71.
   Soybeans were reported at $6.98 a bushel, compared with $6.40
last month and $5.20 in May 1987.
   Upland cotton averaged 56.4 cents a pounds, a decrease from 59.4
cents in April and 60 cents a year earlier.
   Eggs were 43.1 cents a dozen, down from 45.5 cents in April, and
49.3 cents in May 1987.
   Milk was reported at $11.75 per 100 pounds, an increase from
$11.72 last month but a decrease from $12.37 a year earlier.
   Broilers were 33.5 cents a pound, up from 28 cents last month
and 29.9 cents in May 1987.
</TEXT>
