<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Jagger     05-31 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Jagger,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Notice of Appeal Filed in Copyright Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick Alley, the reggae musician who
claimed Mick Jagger stole his music, has filed notice he will
appeal the verdict against him in his copyright lawsuit.
   Lawyer Jerome G. Lee Jr. said Tuesday he had filed a notice of
appeal in U.S. District Court because he had found new evidence
Jagger could have heard Alley's song. He would not elaborate.
   Alley, 36, of the Bronx, claimed the chorus of Jagger's 1985 hit
``Just Another Night'' had been stolen from his 1979 song of the
same title.
   The jury found that Jagger could not have heard Alley's song,
which was released both in New York and Britain and played on
several small radio stations in New York in 1983.
   Alley said he copyrighted his song in 1983 because drummer Sly
Dunbar, who played with Jagger on the album, told him his song was
``being ripped off,'' according to trial testimony. Alley said
Dunbar also played on his version.
   Alley claimed that Jagger had earned as much as $6 million from
the song.
   Jagger, whose song was copyrighted in 1985, testified he had
never heard Alley's song.
   Dunbar, who testified for Jagger, said he could not remember
playing on Alley's recording and denied ever telling Alley the tune
was being plagiarized.
   Jagger's attorney, Peter Parcher, said through his assistant
that he would comment if an appeal actually was filed.
   A notice of appeal, which must be filed within 30 days of a
verdict, does not mean an actual appeal would be filed. Appeal
papers must be filed with the 2nd Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals,
which would hear arguments.
</TEXT>
