<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says He's ``Earned Consideration'' As Vice President</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Tuesday he's ``earned
consideration'' to run as the Democrats' vice presidential
candidate, though he continued his presidential campaign one week
before the final primaries.
   Jackson, campaigning in New Jersey for the state's June 7
primary, also spoke of possibly going directly to the floor of the
Democratic National Convention in July to fight for platform planks
or other issues he considers important.
   On Tuesday, in what was billed as a ``major urban policy
speech,'' he also renewed his calls for equal rights and justice.
   ``Making America better is our challenge. Invest in the people.
Reinvest in America,'' he said.
   On the subject of the vice presidency, he was asked whether he
would accept if he should receive an offer from Democratic
front-runner Michael Dukakis to be the Massachusetts governor's
running mate.
   Jackson's reply: ``I've earned consideration.''
   Were he himself to win, he added, he would give the same
consideration to Dukakis.
   He declined to elaborate on his feelings about the No. 2 spot,
saying only, ``I'll discuss that in more detail after June 7.''
   Jackson said he and Dukakis must work together to defeat Vice
President George Bush, the Republican Party's all-but-certain
nominee.
   ``We need each other. We're keenly aware of that. Together, we
must use our combined strength to change the course,'' Jackson said.
   The Democrats' own course, Jackson said, is one that he _ not
Dukakis _ has set with what he called his progressive campaign
centered on a call for ``jobs, peace and justice.''
   Dukakis this week met with black Democrats, and later said
Jackson would have a major role at the convention and in the fall
campaign.
   ``If I put forth a vision, then reward me,'' Jackson said.
   ``I do not foresee confrontation,'' Jackson said. ``We can
effectively negotiate on mutually respectful terms.''
   Jackson said he expects the anchors of his campaign _ including
workers' pay, reduced military spending and the war on drugs _ to
become planks in the party's 1988 platform.
   He said he has been given six seats on the platform committee,
as has Dukakis by Democratic National Chairman Paul Kirk.
   As the likely nominee, Dukakis would wield great power over the
platform. But Jackson said he, too, will help set the Democrats'
agenda. ``We've set the tone for the country,'' he said.
   If disputes occur, Jackson said, he and his supporters might
bypass the platform writers and take their issues to the full
convention.
   ``There's room to take one's case to the floor,'' he said.
</TEXT>
