<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AmericansInMoscow 1stLd-Writethru a0635 05-31 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Americans In Moscow, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0635,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Looking for All Those Americans in Moscow? Try The Hotel Gift Shop</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 5th graf bgng: Another was ... to clarify that Brown was
not in gift shop.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taxicabs are scarce, subway signs are
indecipherable and police guards are everywhere. So when the going
gets tough in Moscow, tough American visitors go shopping.
   Many of the White House staffers and news reporters attending
the Reagan-Gorbachev summit are forced to spend most of their time
in the Hotel Mezhdunarodnaya press center.
   When they grab a few minutes of free time, they usually head for
the hotel's duty-free Beryozka gift shop, which accepts U.S.
dollars and other hard foreign currencies.
   Among the recent gift shop customers was Elaine Crispen, press
secretary to first lady Nancy Reagan, who was found inspecting oil
paintings ofreligious figures. ``You caught me,'' she laughingly
told a reporter.
   Another man who spent time the hotel was John Brown, a U.S.
Information Agency official who flew to the Soviet capital from
Poland to lend a hand at summit coverage.
   He discovered that only a few reporters are selected to
accompany President Reagan on his summit forays. Hundreds of other
media people stay close to the press center, watching outside
events on television monitors and attending press briefings by a
steady stream of U.S. and Soviet officials.
   ``I really haven`t had time to get out since Reagan arrived,''
Brown said.
   White House stenographer Pamela Gray has spent virtually all her
time in the ``Mezh,'' as the press hotel is nicknamed, or shuttling
across town by bus to the Hotel Rossiya, where the television
networks maintain headquarters. She slipped into the shop to buy
souvenirs for a 3-year-old boy back home.
   Some of the most popular items on display are painted wooden
Russian dolls, whose prices range from $3 to $48. Also favored are
lacquered boxes, lifelike children's dolls and coffee table picture
books.
   Determined shoppers who ventured out to the giant GUM department
store near Red Square and other local shops were disappointed by
the merchandise.
   ``I feel sorry for the Russians _ they don't have anything,''
said Diane Jones of Miami, a Pan American World Airways flight
attendant.
   At the ``Marathon,'' a neighborhood cooperative store, one
American shopper found 10 sweatshirts, a few headbands and a dozen
pair of blue jeans _ one of which cost the equivalent of $176 in
rubles. The biggest crowd stood around a display of European-made,
low-heeled leather shoes.
   Besides shopping, the American summiteers enjoy eating the
caviar, ham and cheese sandwiches at the press center or sampling
the borscht, chicken Kiev, mushroom soup and other Russian fare in
hotel restaurants.
   Far more popular, however, were the free hamburgers that a
Louisiana entrepreneur, Bill Spiers, was dispensing at a kitchen in
the Hotel Mezh.
   Spiers, president of a chain of fast-food restaurants called
Fast Track, shipped in 10,000 hamburger patties to serve in a
summit restaurant operated by Cajun cook John Folse.
   When the restaurant's $16 cover charge _ fixed by the Soviets _
turned away many prospective customers, Spiers decided to give his
hamburgers away. He says he figures his $25,000 loss is worth all
the publicity.
   ``Representatives of every major media have eaten my burgers,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
