<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-AfghanRefugees     05-31 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghan Refugees,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Relief Coordinator Returns From Tour</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of international experts returned Tuesday
from a four-day visit to Afghanistan, Pakistan and Iran to help
prepare an appeal for a huge aid program to the area.
   Paer Stenbaeck, secretary-general of the International League of
the Red Cross, was among the group headed by Prince Sadruddin Aga
Khan, the U.N. relief coordinator for Afghanistan.
   Stenbaeck said the group's talks confirmed the need for a
step-by-step approach in repatriating the more than 5 million
Afghan refugees who have fled to neighboring Pakistan and Iran.
   ``At this time, no one can say whether there will be a
spontaneous or orderly repatriation,'' Stenbaeck said in an
interview. ``We have to work with two different scenarios.''
   He said the new Afghan prime minister, Mohammed Hassan Sharq,
indicated that plans could be made to receive 1 million returnees a
year. Stenbaeck said the ``clear message'' from leaders of the
Moslem guerrillas, who also met with the group, was that under
present conditions the refugees should not return.
   Guerrilla leaders said the situation may change after Aug. 15,
the date by which half of the 100,000 Soviet troops are scheduled
to have left Afghanistan under a settlement signed in Geneva April
14.
   A Swedish-financed survey released Monday in Stockholm said it
would take years and billions of dollars before agricultural
production could be brought back to levels that could support the
returning refugees.
   Stenbaeck said another major barrier to repatriation was the
estimated 5 million anti-personnel mines strewn across Afghanistan.
``Who will take the responsibility for clearing them ?'' he asked.
</TEXT>
