<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-AllegedNazi 1stLd-Writethru a0737 05-31 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Alleged Nazi, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0737,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Charge U.S. Invitee War Criminal</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts one graf after 3rd graf bgng: The student ... and
adds 4 grafs with Pravda, Izvestia comments.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I.
Gerasimov charged Tuesday that one of the dissidents and refuseniks
invited to meet President Reagan was a Nazi war criminal.
   Gerasimov made the allegation at a news conference when asked to
comment on a question from a Moscow student to Reagan that he had
invited the ``Gestapo'' or German ``Polizei'' to his Monday meeting
with dissidents and refuseniks and their families.
   The student was repeating an allegation voiced Tuesday by the
Soviet news agency Tass, which said that Nikolai Rozhko, one of
those at the meeting with Reagan, ``voluntarily joined Nazi
police'' in 1942, one year after the Nazi invasion of the Soviet
Union in World War II.
   The Communist party newspaper Pravda and government daily
Izvestia also carried negative commentaries on the meeting,
attacking some of the participants by name.
   Tass said Rozhko was sentenced to death by military tribunal in
1944, but that his sentence was later commuted to 20 years'
imprisonment. In 1955, Rozhko was released on parole under a Soviet
government decree, Tass said. It did not say why.
   Gerasimov said Soviet journalists who attended Reagan's
reception for the dissidents, which was criticized by Soviet
officials, turned up the background on Rozhko by looking at Soviet
records.
   They ``were rather curious and looked into the dossier of the
invited,'' Gerasimov explained. ``They found out that one of them
in fact was a policeman sharing in the occupation of our country by
Germany ... so he was a former Nazi agent and a war criminal.''
   When asked about the allegation that a former Nazi was invited
to the meeting, Reagan told the Moscow student he did not know
anything about the man.
   A U.S. official who asked not to be identified said Rozhko is a
resident of the town of Grozdno in Byelorussia, a part of the
western Soviet Union ravaged during Nazi occupation.
   Rozhko was born in the United States and came to the Soviet
Union as a child with his parents, the official said. He has been
trying to emigrate for the past 20 years, but the Soviets have
denied him permission to leave.
   The source suggested that Soviet authorities have charged before
that Rozhko had a Nazi background, but ``never once gave us one
shred of evidence of his Nazi activities.'' The official said,
``This was not an issue (on Rozhko's emigration) until the Soviets
brought it up this week.''
   Memories of the struggle against the Nazis in World War II are
kept vividly alive in the Soviet Union, which estimates that 20
million citizens died in battles against Adolf Hitler's troops.
   The Soviet charges against Rozhko were likely therefore to lend
a highly negative connotation to Reagan's meeting with the
refuseniks, which unlike all other events in his program was
reported with negative comment by the state-run Soviet media.
   A senior Soviet journalist, speaking privately, said that
commentators at first were horrified when they learned of Reagan's
plans to meet with dissidents and refuseniks at his Moscow
residence. But he indicated they were then ordered to tone comment
down, and Communist Party leaders had made clear there would be no
other reaction to the meeting, he said.
   Pravda, quoting Reagan's reference to poet Alexander Pushkin
that ``it's time'' for more Kremlin reforms, said, ``Indeed, it's
time. Time to stop speculating on the problems of human rights
using this serious question as an easy reason for
self-advertisement and politicizing.''
   Izvestia criticized participants at the meeting, including
Alexander Ogorodnikov, a religious activist it accused of links
with ``anti-Soviet clerical centers abroad,'' Lev Timofeyev, a
campaigner for press freedom, and Abe Stolar, a 73-year-old
American citizen who has been trying to emigrate with his family
since 1975.
   Tass and Izvestia accused the people invited to meet Reagan at
the U.S. ambassador's residence of opposing official efforts at
reform and have nothing to do with efforts at changing the Soviet
Union because they want only to leave or to dismantle its Communist
system.
   ``Those invited to Spaso House are hampering (reforms) by their
noisy behavior, because far from being interested in them, they are
pursuing their selfish goals _ self-advertisement, gifts and praise
from the West,'' Izvestia said.
</TEXT>
