<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AlmondTrade     05-31 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Almond Trade,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>India Agrees To Loosen Restrictions on U.S. Almond Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States signed an agreement on
Tuesday with India to end a seven-year trade dispute over the sale
of American almonds.
   Under the six-year agreement, India agreed to allow annual
almond imports from all sources to increase to $20 million during
the first three years. In the second three-year period starting in
1991, India said it would remove all import licensing restrictions
on almonds if India's balance of payments position improves to an
agreed-upon level.
   In return, the California Almond Growers Exchange agreed to
withdraw a petition it had filed in January 1987 charging India
with unfair trade practices.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter and India's
ambassador, P.K. Kaul, attended a ceremony Tuesday to mark an end
to the dispute.
   U.S. almond sales to India have averaged around $4 million a
year in recent years.
   ``This agreement will create significant additional
opportunities for U.S. almond growers and demonstrate to the world
that we are serious about expanding our markets,'' Yeutter said.
</TEXT>
