<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-FirstCouple     05-31 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-First Couple,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nancy Reagan Says She's Had Little Time With Her Husband During
Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LENINGRAD, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan said Tuesday that she
and President Reagan have had such hectic schedules during the
U.S.-Soviet summit that they are ``like ships passing in the
night.''
   Mrs. Reagan, who met twice with reporters aboard the U.S. plane
that took her on a day-trip to Leningrad, said she's ``pretty well
adjusted'' to the jet lag and the eight-hour time difference
between Washington and Moscow.
   The first couple had a 3{-day stopover in Helsinki, Finland, in
order to adjust to the time change and to prepare for the five-day
superpower summit.
   ``I was awake at 6 a.m. this morning, and usually I wake up at 3
a.m., so that's progress,'' Mrs. Reagan said.
   Given the observation by some reporters that Reagan appeared
quite tired, Mrs. Reagan was asked how her husband was sleeping.
   ``He sleeps fine,'' she said.
   However, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said at a
briefing that while there was no problem with the president's
health, ``he did have a difficult night's sleep. And we're all a
little tired.''
   Gennady Gerasimov, the Soviet spokesman, took Mrs. Reagan's
side, saying he walked up a steep staircase with Reagan.
   ``I felt breathless, but the president felt OK,'' Gerasimov said.
   The first lady said she's had little chance to discuss summit
topics with her husband, due to her own heavy schedule of touring
Soviet monuments and museums, as well as the Leningrad tour.
   ``We're just like ships passing in the night,'' she said.
</TEXT>
