<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Students     05-31 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Students,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Fields Questions from Young Communist League, Wins Plaudits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Standing beneath a towering bust of Lenin,
President Reagan quoted from Boris Pasternak's once-banned ``Doctor
Zhivago'' Tuesday in a fervent plea that ``the first breath of
freedom'' be allowed to flourish in the Soviet state.
   He won a standing ovation from about 2,000 teachers and students
at Moscow State University, where his host, Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev, earned a degree in 1954.
   In a session that covered topics as diverse as the plight of
American Indians to the two-term restriction on American
presidents, Reagan took questions from a stage beneath Lenin's bust
and a banner emblazoned with a hammer and sickle.
   ``Let me cite one of the most eloquent contemporary passages on
human freedom,'' said Reagan, ``from one of the greatest writers of
the 20th century.''
   With that he quoted Pasternak's famous novel, banned for many
years in the land where its author lived:
   ``I think that if the beast who sleeps in man could be held down
by threats, any kind of threat, whether of jail or of retirbution
after death, then the highest emblem of humanity would be the lion
tamer in the circus with his whip, not the prophet who sacrificed
himself. But this is just the point: what has for centuries raised
man above the beast in not the cudgel, but an inward music, the
irresistible power of unarmed truth.''
   Soviet young people are living ``in one of the most exciting,
hopeful times in Soviet history'' Reagan said, when ``the first
breath of freedom stirs in the air.''
   The world is undergoing an economic revolution, but progress
``is not foreordained,'' he said. ``The key is freedom _ freedom of
thought, freedom of information, freedom of communication,'' he
said.
   One student told Reagan that a delegation of American Indians
had traveled here because they found it impossible to meet with him
in Washington. Reagan said he did not know they had sought an
audience, and that ``I'd be very happy to see them.''
   He said the United States had given the Indians millions of
acres of land and established reservations where they could live if
they chose. ``We've done everything we can to meet their demands as
to how they want to live. Maybe we made a mistake. Maybe we should
not have humored them'' and insisted that they become integrated in
American life.
   He also said that after he leaves the White House he would
deliver after-dinner speeches preaching his conservative political
agenda and campaigning for a constitutional amendment restoring a
president's ability to serve more than two full terms.
   In a luncheon meeting with writers, filmmakers and other artists
at the Writers Union, Reagan praised what he called a recent thaw
in the Soviet arts.
   Dancer Mikhail Baryshnikov and cellist Slava Rostropovich should
be able to perform again in Moscow and Nobel Prize winning author
Alexander Solzhenitsyn should be published ``in the land he dearly
loves,'' Reagan said.
   ``He spoke very sincerely, he spoke about his private life and
he mentioned all those names which are very dear to Russian
intelligentsia,'' Fyodor Burlatsky, an adviser to Gorbachev, said
after Reagan's speech at the Writers Union.
   But Dan Unguryanu, a history student from the Soviet republic of
Moldavia, said ``the leader of a great country should be more
intellectual.''
   ``But he is charismatic,'' said Unguryanu. He added that in
signing a treaty banning medium- and shorter-range nuclear
missiles, Reagan ``has shown us a good example of American
political pragmatism.''
   Mikhail Vasyanin, 20, a student in the linguistic department and
a member of the Young Communists League said, ``Really, the term
`Great Communicator' is good for him.'' He said that some of
Reagan's answers did not correspond to the questions, but he made a
good imression anyway.
   Physics graduate student Alexander Glazkov, 23, said, ``It's too
bad Ronald Reagan has to leave office. There are those who don't
agree with me, but I'd like to see him elected to a third term.''
   Students interviewed before and after the meeting said they were
members of the Young Communist League and had received their
tickets from the organization.
   Students from different university departments approached two
microphones in an orderly manner, suggesting their order and
questions were prearranged.
</TEXT>
