<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Honduran-Drugs,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduran Ambassador Pleads Innocent to Drug Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras' former ambassador to Panama pleaded
innocent Tuesday to charges he imported 26 pounds of cocaine into
the United States.
   Rigoberto Regalado Lara, 49, was stripped of his diplomatic
immunity and his post by the Honduran government after U.S. Customs
officials discovered the cocaine hidden inside coffee bags in his
luggage at Miami International Airport on May 15.
   He faces federal charges of importing cocaine and possession
with intent to distribute.
   On Tuesday he told U.S. Magistrate William Turnoff he was
innocent of the accusations. The case was assigned to U.S. District
Judge Edward Davis, but no trial date was set.
   Regalado was then returned to the federal Metropolitan
Correctional Center in southwest Dade County, where he has been
held without bond since his arrest.
   Prosecutors in the U.S. Attorney's office have described
Regalado as a relatively low-level ``mule'' who simply transported
the drugs.
