<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-Stamp     05-31 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Stamp,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Issue Stamp in Honor of Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has issued 2 million stamps
celebrating the Moscow summit between Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and President Reagan, a news report said Tuesday.
   Novosti, a government news agency that produces feature reports,
said the stamp first was issued on May 29, the day Reagan arrived
in Moscow, and shows a firm handshake with a background of the U.S.
and Soviet flags and the Kremlin's Spasky Tower.
   The stamp, which is worth 5 kopeks (8 cents), has an inscription
across the top saying, ``Soviet-American Summit.'' Below it is
written the dates May 29-June 2.
   Novosti said the sketch for the stamp was done by artist Yuri
Livinovsky.
   The news agency said several dozen stamps on the theme of
U.S.-Soviet relations have been produced in the Soviet Union since
1943, when the first was produced before the Tehran conference of
World War II allies.
   A stamp was produced in honor of the Washington summit meeting
in December 1987, and a month later the Soviets produced a stamp to
mark 30 years of a Soviet-American agreement on culture, technology
and education.
</TEXT>
