<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NearCollision     05-31 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Near Collision,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attendant Injured In Near-Collision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flight attendant who was injured when a pilot
abruptly turned a Continental Airlines DC9 to avoid a small plane
said Tuesday that passengers remained calm and she didn't know what
happened until after they landed.
   Milotka Liebelt said she was bent over her luggage near the rear
of the airplane when the small plane was spotted about 100 feet
away.
   ``It just happened in a split-second,'' Mrs. Liebelt said
Tuesday from her Akron home. ``Before I could realize what was
going on, I was on the floor with my bag in my lap.''
   Mrs. Liebelt was the only person reported injured when
Continental Flight 283 narrowly missed colliding with the small
plane while the jet prepared to land Monday at Cleveland Hopkins
International Airport. The flight from Boston to Cleveland carried
79 passengers and a crew of five.
   Mrs. Liebelt, 35, was treated at Southwest General Hospital for
bruises to her back and left knee.
   ``I don't see how that (small) plane could not have seen us,''
she said. ``Thank God that our first officer responded instantly.''
   ``The first officer (co-pilot) observed a light aircraft
approximately 100 feet below our aircraft and to the right. He
initiated a sharp climb to the left and gained an additional 800
feet of altitude,'' said Continental spokesman Ned Walker in
Houston. ``The Continential pilot did a professional job in
reacting the way he had been trained.''
   Walker said the airline does not release crew members' names.
   The Federal Aviation Administration and the National
Transportation Safety Board are investigating the incident,
officials said Tuesday. The encounter occurred in restricted air
space at about 7,000 feet and five miles southeast of the airport.
   However, FAA spokesman Mort Edelstein said from Chicago that air
traffic controllers were unable to track the small plane, which
didn't show up on radar.
   Small planes entering restricted airspace near airports are
required to get tower permission and to carry transponders, which
produce a signal to display airplane identification on radar
screens.
   Mrs. Liebelt said the flight had been uneventful and the
passengers, who were in their seats in preparation for landing at
the time of the sudden maneuver, remained calm.
   ``It's amazing when things happen, you don't have time to get
scared. You just assume your responsibilities,'' she said.
   Mrs. Liebelt said the plane's captain told the passengers what
had happened after the plane landed at Hopkins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
