<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2023EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AlienFine     05-31 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alien Fine,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Houston-Area Restaurant Owner Cited For Hiring Illegal Aliens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents slapped $10,000 worth of citations
on the owner of a Mexican restaurant chain Tuesday, claiming he is
Houston's most blatant employer of illegal aliens.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service agents delivered
citations and notices of intent to fine to lawyers for Ghulan
Bombaywala, president and chief executive officer of Marco's
Restaurants Inc. The chain operates 10 Mexican restaurants that
employ about 500 people, INS officials said.
   Bombaywala's lawyer said the government was overreacting.
   Under provisions of the 1986 Immigration Reform Act, Tuesday was
the last day federal officials had to serve citations before
issuing fines.
   Starting Wednesday, ``we can go directly to the fine. That's the
major difference beginning June 1,'' INS District Director Ronald
Parra said at a news conference.
   Parra said Bombaywala and his lawyer, Harry Gee, had 30 days to
respond to Tuesday's notices by either paying the fine or
requesting a hearing before a federal administrative law judge. Gee
said they likely would request the hearing.
   INS officials said they raided one Marco's Restaurant in January
and arrested 18 illegal aliens working there. In April, another
raid netted nine illegal workers.
   ``He didn't have any intention to clean up his act,'' said
Michael McMahon, INS deputy director in charge of employer
sanctions. ``The top rung of the ladder _ the corporate structure _
had some knowledge.''
   But Gee said the INS citations and fines were an overreaction by
the government and the result of a misunderstanding.
   ``Our client has made very strenuous efforts to comply,'' Gee
said. ``All of our people now are in compliance.''
   Gee, who described Bombaywala as a Pakistani who has become a
U.S. citizen, said his client has made good-faith efforts by
meeting with INS officials and by getting attorneys for
undocumented aliens who wished to apply for amnesty.
   ``We have a disagreement (with the INS) as to what constitutes a
good-faith effort,'' Gee said.
   He estimated more than 100 aliens had been aided by Bombaywala.
   Ronald Finch, the INS special agent who delivered the four-page
citation and intent to fine to Gee with about a dozen reporters and
photographers in tow, said the Houston INS office was working about
25 such cases, with around 15 nearing the stage at which fines will
be sought.
   Parra said most of the 66,000 Houston businesses have cooperated
with immigration officials to comply with the tough, new federal
laws regarding hiring of illegal aliens.
   ``We are not going to tolerate non-compliance with the law,'' he
said. ``The message to employers is: It's no longer good business
to hire illegal aliens.''
</TEXT>
