<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru a0642 05-31 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike Shuts Down City At Center Of Ethnic Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with demonstrations continue in
Yerevan; details, giving different figures on number of protesters.
PICKS up 11th pvs, Armenians began .... Edits to TRIM. Gives
LaserGraphic number.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY26</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Armenians stayed away from work on
Tuesday in a general strike that shut down factories and mass
transportation in a city at the center of an ethnic dispute, a
local resident said.
   Also Tuesday, the Tass news agency announced that two officials
were dismissed from the Communist Party for alleged negligence that
led to the violence between Armenians and Azerbaijanis.
   In the Armenian capital of Yerevan, round-the-clock
demonstrations were reported to be continuing for a fifth day.
   The resident of the city of Stepanakert, reached by telephone
from Moscow, said public transport was not running and that
factories and other businesses in the city were closed in a strike
that had been going on for days.
   ``People aren't working,'' the woman said. Asked how many, she
answered: ``Many thousands. Everyone.'' She hung up the telephone
before a reporter could ask her name or other questions.
   In Moscow, dissident journalist Sergei Grigoryants said the
general strike had been under way for about a week.
   Telephone calls to Stepanakert city offices and radio and
television stations did not go through.
   Stepanakert is the main city of Nagorno-Karabakh, a region in
the republic of Azerbaijan. Armenians want the Armenian-dominated
region to be made a part of their neighboring republic.
   Armenian literary critic Rafael Popoyan, 45, said by telephone
from his Yerevan home that since Friday about 5,000 people have
gathered during the day and 20,000 in the evening on the square
outside the city's Opera Theater. He said smaller groups of
protesters, mostly students, continued the vigil overnight,
``awaiting an official response to their demand.''
   The protesters want Armenia's Supreme Soviet, the republic's
parliament, to consider the annexation issue at a meeting next
week, he said.
   Popoyan, who spent four years in jail and six months in internal
exile for distributing underground literature, said Yerevan
authorities have not tried to stop the demonstrations.
   On Monday, Grigoryants, who is half-Armenian and half-Russian,
said the crowd in Yerevan swelled to about 300,000. It was unclear
why the figure he cited was so much higher than that given by
Popoyan.
   Armenians began agitating in mid-February for the right to annex
Nagorno-Karabakh. At the end of the month, ethnic rioting broke out
in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait. At least 32 people _ six
Azerbaijanis and 26 Armenians _ were killed.
   Most of the 160,000 residents of Nagorno-Karabakh are ethnic
Armenians, most of them Christians. Since 1923, the region has been
part of Azerbaijan, whose titular ethnic group is predominantly
Moslem.
   The Soviet government rejected the demand to change jurisdiction
over Nagoro-Karabakh, opting instead for a program of social and
economic development.
   On May 21, Communist Party officials fired the two leaders of
Armenia and Azerbaijan, apparently because they had not quelled the
unrest.
   New party shake-ups were announced Tuesday. Tass said the former
first secretary of the Nagorno-Karabakh regional party committee,
Boris Kevorkov, was dismissed from the party because of his
``serious political mistakes.''
   ``His errors resulted in the loss of the party organization's
vanguard role and in the heightening of inter-ethnic relations,''
Tass said in announcing the action taken by a plenary meeting of
the Azerbaijani party organization. ``He was found to be personally
responsible for the disorders that took place in the autonomous
region.''
   Kevorkov had been dismissed as head of the Nagorno-Karabakh
party committee on Feb. 24. He was replaced by Genrikh Pogosyan,
subsequently identified by Tass as an Armenian born in
Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Tass said the plenum also dismissed from the party D.M.
Muslim-Zade, the former first secretary of the Sumgait city
committee, for ``serious shortcomings in organizational and
political work that brought about the tragic developments in
Sumgait.''
</TEXT>
