<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GOPPlatform 1stLd-Writethru a0714 05-31 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP Platform, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0714,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Accuse Democrats Of Hiding Dukakis Views</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 6 grafs at end with further comments</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG HORST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans working Tuesday on their
party platform accused the Democrats of being less open than the
GOP and of trying to hide liberal views of likely nominee Michael
Dukakis.
   GOP Chairman Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr. said of the Democrats,
``They are simply not interested in writing an honest,
straightforward platform that expresses their true plan for
America. The Republican approach is one of openness.''
   Sen. Bob Kasten of Wisconsin said Republicans would force the
Democrats ``to take the field'' on critical issues and would
``flush the Dukakis Democrats'' out, exposing what he said were
their left-of-center views.
   The seven-member committee met to discuss social issues in one
of four hearings it will hold before the national convention in New
Orleans.
   Sen. Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas said in remarks to the committee
that the value of the platform should be restored by shortening it
and not ``making it a catch-all and promise-all.''
   Democratic Party Chairman Paul Kirk has made a similar request
concerning his party's platform.
   Kassebaum said, ``The one major difference between Republicans
and Democrats is that government must have a limited role.''
   Gov. Mike Hayden of Kansas urged the committee to include a
strong rural plank in the platform.
   ``Sometimes policies of the federal government have
discriminated against rural areas,'' Hayden said. ``We have heard
about urban renewal, but seldom have we heard about rural
revitalization.''
   The party's 1980 and 1984 platforms, the latter particularly
pleasing to conservatives, will serve as a basis for the 1988
platform, said Nebraska Gov. Kay Orr, chairman of the platform
committee.
   ``It's a good base,'' Mrs. Orr said of the 1984 platform. ``But
times have changed. There is a different emphasis that we will
place on things.''
   Fahrenkopf said the 1984 platform ``established a base, a soul''
for the party.
   ``But times have changed, problems have changed,'' Fahrenkopf
said at a news conference held by the seven committee members
during a lunch break. ``We want to take conservative approaches to
solve the problems we see coming down the road.''
   ``We have had no specific direction from Bush,'' Mrs. Orr said,
referring to likely GOP presidential nominee George Bush. ``We will
have a line of communication open. We're very interested in the
vice president's views.''
   As for the party's November opponents, Fahrenkopf said, ``The
Democrats face a level-with-America dilemma. Do they hide the
liberal agenda and record of their nominee Michael Dukakis, or do
they level with Americans and detail their liberal goals and
plans.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
