<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PandaExhibit     05-31 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panda Exhibit,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Gives Toledo Zoo OK To Continue Panda Exhibit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service gave the
Toledo Zoo the go-ahead Tuesday to continue exhibiting two giant
pandas on loan from China.
   David Klinger, spokesman for the service, said export documents
provided by the zoo late Friday have been reviewed and found to be
acceptable.
   ``The permit is acceptable to us,'' Klinger said. ``The
condition of the law has been met. That should settle it.''
   He said the zoo will be notified by letter Wednesday and that
the panda exhibit will be allowed to continue.
   However, a lawsuit is pending in which a wildlife group contends
the pandas _ an endangered species _ are being exploited for
commercial gain.
   In its federal suit against the Fish and Wildlife Service, the
World Wildlife Fund argues that the exhibit violates an
international convention that bars trafficking in endangered
species for commerical purposes.
   U.S. District Court Judge Norma Johnson has set a hearing on the
suit for June 13.
   The pandas entered the United States on May 13 accompanied by an
exemption form instead of a full Chinese export permit as required.
   The animals were allowed to begin their three-month exhibit last
Tuesday as part of Toledo's 150th anniversary celebration, but the
USFWS gave the zoo until May 29 to provide the proper documentation.
 
</TEXT>
