<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ArtTheft-List     05-31 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Art Theft-List,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Thefts in 1980s</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Art Theft Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Paintings by van Gogh, Cezanne and Jongkind recovered by Dutch
police Tuesday, 11 days after they were stolen from an Amsterdam
museum, were valued at up to $52 million. Here is a list of other
major art thefts in this decade:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FEB. 23, 1988 _ Thieves break into the Munch Museum in Oslo,
Norway, carrying away ``The Vampire,'' a painting by Norwegian
artist Edvard Munch insured for $2.3 million.
   FEB. 8, 1988 _ In New York's biggest art theft, burglars break
through a skylight into the Colnaghi Art Gallery and steal 27 Old
Master paintings and drawings, including two panels by Italian
Renaissance master Fra Angelico. The art is valued at $6 million.
   MARCH 24, 1987 _ Six paintings are stolen from the Castagnino
Museum in Rosario, Argentina. Among the paintings, worth an
estimated $12 million, are works by Goya, El Greco, Tiziano and
Veronese.
   FEB. 14-15, 1987 _ Nine paintings valued at $2.65 million,
including works by Renoir and Brueghel, are stolen from the
Noortman Art Gallery in Maastricht, Netherlands.
   MAY 21, 1986 _ Vermeer's ``Lady Writing a Letter with Her
Maid,'' is among 18 paintings worth $40 million stolen from
Russborough House in Blessington, Ireland. Others include works by
Goya, Rubens, and Gainsborough. Seven of the least valuable works
are dumped near a reservoir.
   OCT. 27, 1985 _ Five armed men steal nine Impressionist
paintings from Paris' Marmottan Museum in a bank-style holdup. Five
Monets, including ``Impression Sunrise,'' are among those stolen.
The curator estimates the paintings' value at $12.5 million.
``Impression Sunrise'' has been traced to Japan, but has not been
recovered to date.
   NOVEMBER 1983 _ Seven Italian Renaissance masterpieces,
including works by Raphael and Tintoretto, are stolen from the
Museum of Fine Arts in Budapest, Hungary. All of the paintings,
worth $7 million, are recovered within a year.
</TEXT>
