<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit Briefs,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At Moscow's House of Writers, President Reagan
talked to some of the Soviet Union's leading intellectuals about
how an actor could become a politician, explaining that both
artists and political leaders had to be able to grasp a vision and
to put it into life.
   ``By the way, I've found that Mr. Gorbachev has the ability to
grasp and hold a vision and I respect him for that,'' Reagan told
the 38 intellectuals assembled in the House of Writers' elegant
wood-paneled restaurant.
   Using references to two beloved and persecuted Soviet poets,
Nikolai Gumilyev and Anna Akhamatova, Reagan went on to explain
that artists _ and, in a democracy, politicians _ understood the
need to embrace all the strands of human existence.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It had the makings of a potential disaster for the
U.S. Information Agency's office at the international press center.
   Copying machines are rare in the Soviet Union, so USIA had a
large copier flown in to handle the job of reproducing the reams of
papers the government provides to reporters.
   But the machine literally blew up _ smoke poured from the top _
on Sunday when it was plugged in because it had not been converted
to the proper electrical current.
   John Harrod, a USIA spokesman, said the office needed another
machine ``real quick like,'' so officials had one brought in Monday
morning from Germany. That machine proved to be defective.
   Two technicians, taking instructions from someone in Washington
over the telephone, managed to repair the machine more than 24
hours after Reagan arrived.
   ``The whole idea of a summit is communications and if you can't
communicate, you're in trouble,'' Harrod said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Muscovites woke up to a new sound Tuesday _ a
radio talk show broadcast straight from WAVA, a station in
Arlington, Va., a suburb of the U.S. capital.
   Don Geronimo and Mike O'Meara, working in Virginia, were on the
air for about 30 minutes Tuesday morning, speaking English on Radio
Moscow.
   The two irreverent disc jockeys took calls from American
listeners, talked to a relative in Beloit, Wis., and cracked jokes
about pollution. ``That's something the Russians can relate to,''
one said.
   They closed the show, telling the Russians they were planning to
visit the Soviet Union. ``Buy our products, we're coming over,''
one said.
