<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Belgian     05-31 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Belgian,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Norwegian Relief Group May Suspend Activities in Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Norwegian relief group said Tuesday it
may suspend work in Lebanon if a member of its staff who has been
missing for 10 days does not turn up.
   Fears that Dr. Jan Cools, a 32-year-old Belgian physician, was
kidnapped have been expressed by the relief group NORWAC and others.
   ``Within one week we will stop working in Beirut if nothing
happens,'' said Kristin Ingebrigben, coordinator for the NORWAC
group. ``We are also thinking of stopping our activities in
Tripoli,'' a port in northern Lebanon.
   NORWAC evacuated its seven staff members from south Lebanon on
Saturday. It has 18 people in Lebanon.
   Cools has worked with NORWAC for three months. He vanished May
21 after leaving his apartment in the Rashidiyeh Palestinian
refugee camp near the ancient port of Tyre in south Lebanon.
   Ms. Ingebrigben said the group had no confirmation that Cools
left the camp. She said he was bound for a base of the U.N.
peacekeeping force in Tyre to pick up his mail.
   ``We cannot take the responsibility any longer for foreign
people as long as we don't know anything about what happened to Dr.
Cools,'' she told a news conference at her group's headquarters in
Moslem west Beirut.
   Police say they have no information about his disappearance.
NORWAC said it did not know what happened to Cools despite
contacting ``all the organizations and authorities concerned in the
area.''
   All Lebanese and Palestinian parties NORWAC approached denied
involvement in the physician's disappearance, Ms. Ingebrigben said,
and ``we didn't hear anything from anybody. We don't accuse anyone
of Jan's disappearance.''
   Rashidiyeh's ``popular committee,'' which runs the camp's
day-to-day affairs, said last Thursday that gunmen seized Cools at
a road junction near Tyre. It gave no details and did not identify
the alleged abductors.
   Ms. Ingebrigben said Cools' disappearance might affect
humanitarian work in Lebanon. She did not elaborate, but said
NORWAC had been in touch with other humanitarian agencies.
   Three other relief workers, two Scandinavians and a Briton, were
kidnapped in south Lebanon this year.
   Jan Stening, 44, and William Jorgenson, 58, of Norway were
seized Feb. 5 near Sidon, another southern port, and freed March 2.
They worked for the U.N. Relief and Works Agency, which cares for
Palestinian refugees.
   UNRWA blamed the abduction of Stening and Jorgenson on
Palestinians acting for personal motives. It evacuated foreign
staff members and reduced its services in the refugee camps until
the men were released.
   Palestinian guerrillas seized Peter Coleridge, Middle East
coordinator of the British relief agency Oxfam, and a Syrian aide
in Sidon's Ein el-Hilweh refugee camp March 4 after he took
photographs. Both were freed March 8.
   Eighteen missing foreigners are believed to be held hostage by
extremist Moslem groups in Lebanon, most of them in south Beirut by
pro-Iranian Shiite factions.
   Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, 40, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
