<1ST_LINE>r i AM-FetalTransplant     05-31 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fetal Transplant,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Doctors Perform Third Transplant Using Fetal Brain Cells</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British doctors have given a third sufferer of
Parkinson's disease brain cells transplanted from an aborted fetus,
a hospital announced Tuesday.
   A 58-year-old woman underwent the surgery May 17 at the Midland
Center of Neurosurgery and Neurology at Smethwick in central
England. She was reported to be back home and showing ``an
initially good response'' to the treatment.
   The hospital announced the development in a statement by
neurologist Edward Hitchcock, whose team carried out Britain's
first known fetal brain-cell transplants in March and April.
   Parkinson's disease is a potentially fatal condition that causes
gradual loss of muscle control. Fetal tissue is thought to
stimulate production of dopamine, a brain chemical lacking in
Parkinson's disease.
   Hitchcock's disclosure last month that he used the experimental
procedure provoked controversy. Critics complained it reduced the
aborted fetus to the status of a human spare part. Others welcomed
it as a possible medical breakthrough.
   The U.S. Department of Health and Human Services has banned
government scientists from carrying out surgery using tissue from
aborted fetuses, pending study of the ethical, legal and medical
questions involved.
   The first documented use of the experimental procedure was
reported in January, when surgeons in Mexico City said they
injected tissue from a miscarried fetus into the brains of two
Parkinson's sufferers last September. Swedish doctors subsequently
reported use of the technique, with disappointing results.
   Hitchcock said last month that his team transplanted fetal brain
cells into a 60-year-old woman and a 41-year-old man, both of whom
were said to have shown ``dramatic improvement.''
   Hitchcock said the latest operation was carried out under
guidelines issued by the British Medical Association last month.
</TEXT>
