<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DroughtAid     05-31 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Aid,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relief for Drought-Stricken Farmers Signaled by USDA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department signaled Tuesday it
is prepared to assist farmers in the nation's drought-stricken
heartland by easing curbs on the use of land idled under
conservation programs.
   Hay production and cattle grazing on such land will be allowed
in counties found to be suffering from a natural disaster that
harms pasture and forage crops, the department said.
   The statement came amid heightened concern over a drought
hammering broad stretches of the nation's heartland from south
Texas to the Canadian border and as far west as Idaho. Thus far,
however, no disaster counties have been declared.
   The statement from Milton Hertz, administrator of the
Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service, mainly
outlined possibilities already open to the department. It contained
no new programs.
   Under the 1985 Farm Act, farmers must devote a specified portion
of their land to conservation uses if they are to be eligible for
crop programs that produce federal payments. The amount of land
involved varies from one crop to another. For example, it is 27.5
percent for wheat.
   Producers also receive payments for placing endangered land in
the long-term Conservation Reserve Program.
   Under the law, haying and grazing are banned on acreage devoted
to conservation programs. The theory is that farmers already derive
economic benefit from the land in the form of government payments.
But USDA may make exceptions in the case of natural disasters.
   In counties found to be suffering from such a disaster, Hertz
said, ``haying and grazing will be allowed for any consecutive
five-month period between April 1 and October 1.''
   He said determination of counties eligible will be made on a
county-by-county basis.
   Hertz said no requests from state and county offices will be
approved if it appears that doing so will adversely effect haying
operations in the counties involved. No hay or forage harvested may
be sold, he added.
   A producer may charge a ``reasonable harvesting fee'' for
allowing other farmers to hay and graze on his acreage, however,
the department said. But it said he ``may not receive compensation
for the value of the vegetative matter that is harvested or
grazed.''
   Hertz noted that a number of steps already have been taken in
response to rising concern over the drought.
   He said producers enrolled in USDA's wheat and feed grains
programs may take part in the 0-92 disaster program, even though
the March 11 deadline for participation has passed. Under the 0-92
program, farmers produce no crop but still receive 92 percent of
the federal payments they otherwise would get.
   He also pointed to two programs under which the government
provides subsidies to farmers to purchase livestock feed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
