<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Disarmament     05-31 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Disarmament,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviets Clash Over Need for Nuclear Weapons Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's top arms control official, Lynn
M. Hansen, said Tuesday the United States will keep testing nuclear
weapons to preserve its nuclear deterrent. A senior Soviet official
called such tests ``immoral.''
   Speaking on the first day of a special four-week U.N. session on
disarmament, Hansen added that the United States will not try to
pass a U.N. resolution calling for arms cuts by Third World nations.
   Hansen, assistant director of the U.S. Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency, said: ``We are not going to come here and
insist that developing countries somehow change their defense
priorities for the acquisition of arms.
   ``Of course, we would like them to spend less money on arms and
put more money into development of their own countries.''
   The Reagan administration wants to increase arms sales to
foreign buyers this year to more than $15 billion, $3.3 billion
more than last year. The Soviet Union is also a major arms supplier.
   Hansen said if the United States refused to sell to a foreign
country seeking arms, ``they would go to another country that would
say `yes.'''
   When asked why America keeps testing nuclear weapons, he
replied: ``The security policy of the United States and its allies
is based upon the concept of deterrence.
   ``And as long as this is the policy which undergirds our
security and that of the Western alliance, we will continue to
test, because the requirement exists.''
   At a separate news conference, Deputy Soviet Foreign Minister
Vladimir F. Petrovsky said, ``We decline this strategy and policy
of nuclear deterrence, not only because of practical unusefulness
but because of the immoral nature of this kind of deterrence. ...
   ``We think the time is right to stop the nuclear tests.''
   Petrovsky said Moscow intends to ``reduce the number and might
of nuclear tests conducted during each year'' and to press for
adoption of a test ban treaty.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar opened the
session by noting it began ``at a most opportune time ... (when)
President Ronald Reagan and General Secretary (Mikhail) Gorbachev
are engaged in a dialogue in Moscow partly in the context of the
reduction of strategic nuclear weapons.''
   He expressed pleasure over the recent ratification of the
U.S.-Soviet intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty to scrap
medium and shorter-range nuclear missiles.
   Perez de Cuellar said it ``clearly shows that, with political
will, agreements to reverse the nuclear-arms race are possible and
compliance with them can be duly verified.''
   He called on the superpowers to take the next step and cut in
half their long-range nuclear arsenals under a strategic arms
reduction treaty, or START.
   Petrovsky told reporters the Soviets will seek to focus the
attention of the U.N. disarmament session on ``the whole range of
nuclear issues, on the nuclear weapons test ban, prevention of the
weapons' expansion into outer space, the soonest possible
conclusion of a convention on the ban on chemical weapons,'' as
well as reducing conventional forces.
   The United States wants the session to stress cuts in
conventional arms.
   Hansen said the United States does not seek to bring Britain and
France into superpower talks to reduce nuclear arsenals.
   Moscow would prefer a treaty that would include British and
French weapons.
   Hansen said the United States also seeks to balance European
arms control with progress on human rights issues.
   The U.N. General Assembly stated in 1979 that the United Nations
should play a central role in disarmament, and that complete
nuclear disarmament was the priority.
   No breakthroughs are expected to emerge at this U.N. session,
during which at least 25 presidents and prime ministers are
scheduled to address the General Assembly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
