<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0775 05-31 0802</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0775,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Sees No Confrontation at Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Tops with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Bush comment; picks up 7th
graf pvs, bgng: Dukakis stuck ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson offered Michael Dukakis hope for a harmonious
Democratic National Convention on Tuesday, and Republican George
Bush emerged from a seaside meeting with economists to renew his
no-tax-increase pledge.
   With his two front-running presidential rivals taking a break
from campaigning, Jackson stumped in New Jersey and spoke of the
convention in Atlanta this July.
   ``I do not foresee confrontation,'' Jackson said. ``We can
effectively negotiate on mutually respectful terms.''
   That kind of talk was bound to be welcomed by Dukakis, as he and
his supporters looked forward to gaining a mathematical lock on the
nomination in the primary-season finale next Tuesday.
   In a weekend interview with The Associated Press, Dukakis also
had said he looked for a convention without the divisiveness that
some feared.
   ``I think we're going to have a good convention,'' Dukakis said.
``I don't see any deep divisions. ... I don't see anything that
can't be resolved.''
   Bush, his Republican nomination long assured, met with
economists at his home at Kennebunkport on the Maine seacoast.
Afterward, he said he would reject a call for new taxes even if it
is recommended by a blue-ribbon bipartisan commission.
   But Bush, who often says he wants to become ``the education
president,'' said higher local school taxes might be needed.
   ``They may have to,'' Bush said. ``Ninety-three percent of the
money for education comes from sources other than the federal
government. If it's taxes, that's where it has to be. It isn't
going to be at the federal level, absolutely.''
   Bush urged the Federal Reserve not to tighten credit too much,
which he said risks shutting down economic growth.
   Dukakis stuck to his duties as governor of Massachusetts,
spending the day at the Statehouse in Boston. He had an evening
fund-raiser in Baltimore.
   The race for the presidency, at a quiet point in the campaign
season, drew a pleased comment from the Soviet side at the summit
in Moscow.
   Soviet government spokesman Gennady Gerasimov said: ``What we
like about your campaign is that the Soviet-American relations, at
least as I see it, are not an issue. Everybody agrees, both
candidates agree, that you must have normal relations with our
country. We like it.''
   While Jackson said he foresaw no major convention rifts, he
still left open the possibility of a convention floor fight. He
said he expects the issues of his campaign _ including workers'
pay, reduced military spending and the war on drugs _ to become
planks in the party's 1988 platform.
   Jackson also talked about the vice presidential spot on the
ticket, repeating his contention that ``I've earned consideration''
for the No. 2 spot with Dukakis, if Dukakis should win the
nomination.
   The presidential primary season ends Tuesday with the heftiest
delegate prize, California, and also contests in New Jersey,
Montana and New Mexico.
   Dukakis was to resume campaigning after flying to California on
Wednesday.
   He planned stops in Montana and New Jersey, and a brief visit
back where it all began _ in Des Moines, Iowa, where party caucuses
in the February cold were the initial delegate event of the season.
Dukakis planned a breakfast meeting with supporters pointing toward
the fall race against Bush in the farm state, as he crossed the
country.
   Dukakis and Jackson both said over the Memorial Day weekend that
Jackson would play a major part in Dukakis' expected fall campaign
against Bush. But both said the nature of that role hadn't yet been
worked out.
   There are 466 Democratic delegates at stake in next Tuesday's
primaries _ enough to put Dukakis over the 2,081 needed to
nominate. The Massachusetts governor can lay claim to more than
1,700 delegates now, compared with fewer than 1,000 for Jackson.
   Bush was weighing fall campaign strategies with advisers as his
campaign faced a series of polls showing him trailing Dukakis
nationally.
   The vice president acknowledged to reporters his campaign is
facing a money crunch of sorts that might require him to cut back
on summer campaign travel. The problem is he has nearly reached the
federal spending limit for the primary campaign.
   ``It's expensive to take this show on the road,'' Bush said.
   Bush recently met with embattled Attorney General Edwin Meese
III, whose problems some Republicans say are damaging to Bush's
campaign. Meese, in an interview on CNN on Monday night, said he
and Bush had ``talked frankly about the campaign.''
   Meese said if he were to resign now it would harm Bush ``because
people would say there was something wrong.'' He left open the
possibility, however, that he might leave office by the end of
summer.
</TEXT>
