<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1854EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     05-31 0853</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Wants No Tax Increase, No Strong Credit Tightening</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said
Tuesday he would reject any call for a federal tax increase, even
if one came from a blue-ribbon bipartisan commission now working on
ways to trim the huge federal deficit.
   However, he also said that higher local school taxes might be
needed to carry out his education policies.
   On another economic subject, Bush cautioned the Federal Reserve
Board against tightening credit too much, saying, ``I don't want to
see action taken that's going to shut down economic growth.''
   Bush, the all-but-certain Republican presidential nominee, met
with a group of private economic advisers, then spoke with
reporters in a meeting hall in this oceanside town where he has a
vacation home.
   He said that, while he had full confidence in Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan, he wanted to voice ``a word of caution.''
   The Federal Reserve in recent weeks has been slightly tightening
credit in hopes that by nudging up interest rates it can keep
inflation in check.
   Bush said ``there was some expression of concern'' about recent
Fed actions among the economists during the first day of a two-day
session.
   The group included Harvard economist Martin S. Feldstein, a
former chairman of President Reagan's Council of Economic Advisers,
and Stanford economist Michael J. Boskin. They are two of Bush's
most frequently consulted economic advisers.
   Feldstein quit his White House post after his advocacy of tax
increases to reduce the federal deficit ran afoul of Reagan
administration no-new-taxes policy.
   Bush said of Federal Reserve policymakers, ``I think they are
putting a great emphasis on inflation. Whether it's too much, I
don't know. ... It's a tough balancing thing.''
   In response to a reporter's question, he said he would reject
the notion of a tax increase even if it were part of the
recommendations of the bipartisan commission now at work.
   The panel, which includes administration appointees as well as
members appointed by Democratic and Republican congressional
leaders, was formed earlier this year to seek ways to trim the
nation's massive budget deficit.
   ``It seems to me that commission might well come up with a tax
increase,'' Bush said. ``And I'll be saying, wait a minute, I've
taken my case to the American people to hold the line on taxes.''
   The commission, which will also gain two new members appointed
by the president-elect after the November election, is scheduled to
present its findings in 1989.
   ``I wold be interested in their views, but not persuaded'' if a
tax increase is included, Bush said.
   However, the vice president, who has told audiences he wants to
be the ``education president'' and has stressed educational issues
in his campaign, was asked if local school taxing authorites might
have to increase taxes to carry out some of the still-unspecified
programs he envisions.
   ``They may have to,'' Bush said. ``Ninety-three percent of the
money for education comes from sources other than the federal
government. If it's taxes, that's where it has to be. It isn't
going to be at the federal level, absolutely.''
   Bush is spending a week at his family oceanside retreat in a
series of meetings with advisers and Republican consultants.
   The vice president said that there was wide support among the
economists for his propsal for a ``flexible freeze'' on spending to
reduce the budget deficit.
   Bush's plan would hold federal spending, except for Social
Security benefits, to the levels of the 1989 budget plus inflation.
Individual programs would not have to be frozen. However, for every
one that went up, another would have to go down by a corresponding
amount.
   Bush says such a plan could result in a balanced budget within
four years.
   He said there was some discussion of taxes at Tuesday's meeting,
but that he made his position clear from the outset that he opposed
any form of tax increase.
   On other subjects, Bush:
   _Said he was pleased with how things were going in the
superpower talks in Moscow and did not think that Reagan ``offended
the Soviets by talking too much about human rights. I don't believe
that for a minute.''
   _Said that his wait-and-see position on Attorney General Edwin
Meese III hasn't changed. ``We're so close to hearing from that
independent counsel we ought to get the report and let Ed sort all
that out.''
   _Said remarks like a recent comment by Democratic National
Chairman Paul Kirk that he was a ``country club Republican'' didn't
bother him. ``Listen, that's just part of the territory. That was
mild, they didn't even lay a glove on me.''
   Bush had said over the weekend that his campaign was running low
on cash and tht it might have to curtail some travel plans after
the June 7 California primary.
   Aide Bob Teeter said on Tuesday that, of the $29.5 million
raised so far by the campaign, including $7 million in federal
matching funds, less than $1.5 million is left in campaign coffers.
   Bush has raised the maximum allowed by law for pre-convention
spending.
</TEXT>
