<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Dinner 1stLd-Writethru a0690 05-31 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Dinner, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cream of Soviet Society Invited to Reagan Dinner at Spaso House</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New throughout with details of dinner, quotes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev pronounced the jazz ``good,''
and the rest of Moscow society tapped their feet to the distinctly
American rhythms at President Reagan's lavish dinner Tuesday for
the Soviet leader and his wife.
   The superpower leaders exchanged toasts touching on arms issues,
and Reagan said the two nations should work together ``that we
might forever keep our swords at our sides.''
   Gorbachev recalled the history of Soviet-U.S. relations, from
their World War II alliance to the tensions of the Cold War era,
when ``we all felt the breath of impending catastrophe.''
   ``Even today, we're sometimes chilled by cold winds,'' Gorbachev
said.
   He said the two countries ``may be standing at the threshold of
a uniquely interesting period in the history of our two nations''
and added: ``May the years to come bring a healthier international
environment.''
   Weightier issues aside, the evening was filled with the rhythms
of jazz great Dave Brubeck's quintet. The musician is one of the
Reagans' favorite performers. Jazz, which began in the United
States, is heard by thousands of Soviets though a daily Voice of
America shortwave radio program. And Brubeck has toured the country
in critically acclaimed concert series.
   ``I can't understand Russian, but I can understand body
language,'' said Brubeck, who added that Gorbachev appeared to be
``very into it.''
   Brubeck's 36-year-old son Chris, who plays bass guitar and
trombone in the group, said he learned from a woman sitting near
Gorbachev that Mrs. Reagan turned to Gorbachev at one point during
the music and asked if he liked jazz. According to the younger
Brubeck, the Kremlin chief responded, ``I like good jazz and this
is good jazz.''
   Reagan and the 120 guests seemed to enjoy the the lobster
bisque, supreme of chicken with truffle sauce and California wines.
   During the dinner party, Reagan was seated next to the wrong
man. The official seating chart called for Aleksandr Yakovlev,
secretary of the Communist Party's central committee, to be on
Reagan's left, while Mrs. Gorbachev was on the other side.
   In fact, Reagan's dinner partner was Yegor Yakovlev, editor of
the Moscow News, the English language weekly newspaper and a beacon
of glasnost.
   Elaine Crispen, Mrs. Reagan's spokeswoman, said she did not know
how the confusion occurred. Said Mrs. Crispen of the mix-up: ``I
hope somebody was able to tell the president.''
   Soviet dissident Andrei Sakharov came to the dinner, as did the
elite of Soviet political, cultural, scientific and sports circles.
The guest listed ranged from Yegor Ligachev, No. 2 in the Communist
Party, to Olympic gold medalist Katya Gordeyeva and Bolshoi
ballerinas Nina Ananiashvili and Natalya Bessmertnova, and Defense
Minister Gen. Dmitri Yazov.
   But Gorbachev's daughter, Irina Virganskiy, and her husband,
Anatoly, snubbed the dinner. ``They accepted, but they did not
arrive,'' Mrs. Crispen said. The couple did not give a reason for
their no-show.
   The Russian guests appeared to appreciate the entertainment, and
many tapped along with their feet as Brubeck's quintet played
``Take the A Train,'' ``Take Five,'' and ``Some Day My Prince will
Come.''
   Sakharov, a winner of the Nobel Peace Prize, told reporters he
believed the summit was ``very important as a continuation of
mutual understanding and achieving trust.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, in genial mood as he raised
a vodka toast in the direction of the press, made an extra point of
greeting Sakharov and his wife Yelena Bonner.
   Reagan, his wife, Nancy and the Gorbachevs posed for pictures
briefly before walking into the resplendent towering reception
rooms at Spaso House, a mansion built in czarist days and now the
residence of U.S. Ambassador Jack F. Matlock.
   The first lady wore a gray and white Galanos knee-length dress,
while Mrs. Gorbachev wore a shimmery fitted gold tunic top with a
ruffled collar and a straight black satin skirt.
   The crowd of Soviet and American guests arrived about 30 minutes
before the Reagans and the Gorbachevs, and mingled in an ornate
anteroom while they sipped drinks and listened to soft violin music.
   ``The atmosphere is terrific,'' said Ambassador Selwa Roosevelt,
the American chief of protocol who helped usher guests into Spaso
House.
</TEXT>
