<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-31 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storms Roar Across Texas Panhandle; Upper Midwest Cooks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms dumped heavy rains Tuesday in the
Texas Panhandle and across the Plains, while sunny skies produced
record high temperatures in the Midwest's northern reaches.
   The greatest concentration of thunderstorms in the southern and
central Plains region extended from eastern Nebraska south into
central and western Texas, prompting tornado watches and causing
heavy rain.
   More than 3 inches of rain fell at Amarillo, Texas, Tuesday
morning. Numerous accidents were reported and Interstate 40 in
western Amarillo was closed for a few hours because of submerged
underpasses, police said.
   Thunderstorm winds blew part of the roof off a house in Fremont,
Neb. The same thunderstorm produced marble-sized hail at Herman,
Neb.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued in parts of southern
Florida. There were also isolated areas of rain and rain showers in
Montana, light rain in western Washington and Oregon and a few
showers in northern Maine.
   Sunny skies Tuesday afternoon brought high temperatures in the
upper 80s and low 90s from much of the Mississippi Valley and the
Great Lakes region to the East Coast from the mid-Atlantic states
south to central Florida.
   Partly cloudy to cloudy skies across the central and northern
Rockies held afternoon temperatures down into the 50s and 60s.
   A high wind advisory was posted for the Guadalupe Pass area of
southwest Texas, where winds reached 54 mph in gusts early Tuesday
afternoon.
   Record high temperatures for the date included 91 degrees in
Cape Hatteras, N.C.; 85 in Duluth, Minn.; 93 at Flint, Mich.; 93 in
Fort Wayne, Ind.; and 94 in Toledo, Ohio.
   Record low temperatures for the date also occurred with 24
degrees in Alamosa, Colo.; 38 in Albuquerque, N.M.; 37 in Grand
Junction, Colo.; and 49 in Tucson, Ariz.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 39
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 95 degrees at Greenville,
S.C. and Meridian, Miss. The morning low was 21 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   Wednesday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms
scattered from the central and eastern Great Plains into the lower
Missouri Valley and also across southern Florida. Rain and rain
showers should be prevalent in the Pacific Northwest, scattered
rain showers in northern Maine, isolated afternoon showers from
northern Michigan to southern New York, and scattered thunderstorms
across parts of the mid-Atlantic region.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 50s and 60s across
northern and central New England, 60s in the northern and central
Rockies and the northern and central Pacific Coast region and 90s
through the middle and lower Mississippi Valley, western Ohio
Valley and much of the Southeast. Highs should rebound into the 90s
or near 100 in the Southwest deserts and interior valleys of
Southern California. The rest of the nation was forecast to have
high temperatures in the 70s and 80s.
</TEXT>
