<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoeingCoincidence     05-31 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing Coincidence,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Similarities Between Taiwan, Aloha Crash Only Coincidence, Boeing
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing 737 that disintegrated and crashed
over Taiwan in 1981 and another one that lost part of its fuselage
over Hawaii in April were built back-to-back, but Boeing officials
Tuesday attributed any similarities to coincidence.
   The 151st 737-200 model Boeing produced was the Far Eastern Air
Transport jet that broke up at 22,000 feet over central Taiwan Aug.
22, 1981, killing all 110 people on board.
   No. 152 was the Aloha Airlines aircraft on which a 20-foot
section of forward upper fuselage ripped away at 24,000 feet on
April 28. A flight attendant fell to her death and 61 passengers
were injured, but the flight crew landed the plane safely.
   The cause of the Aloha accident is still under investigation.
But the Federal Aviation Administration has ordered U.S. airlines
flying older 737s to re-inspect the aircraft, including mandatory
electronic testing of planes with more than 50,000 landings.
   Boeing believes the Far Eastern crash was caused by maintenance
problems, spokesman Jack Gamble of Boeing Commercial Airplanes said.
   Any connection between that crash and the Aloha accident are ``a
series of coincidences,'' Gamble said.
   ``We do not think that is a fair assessment'' to directly link
the two, he said.
   At the time of the planes' manufacture in 1969, Boeing was
turning out two or three 737s a month, Gamble said. He said he knew
of no other problems involving 737s made about that time.
   Benjamin Cosgrove, Boeing Commercial Airplanes vice president
and general manager for engineering, was quoted by The Wall Street
Journal Tuesday as saying the consecutive aircraft numbers were
coincidence.
   Although both accidents involved the same part of the fuselage,
nothing was inherently wrong with that portion of the aircraft,
Cosgrove said.
   He told the Journal that the Taiwanese 737 repeatedly was used
to ship fish in open containers, and corrosive salt water may have
gotten into the cargo hold. The newspaper said Far Eastern
officials denied that.
   National Transportation Safety Board spokesman Michael Benson in
Washington, D.C., said Tuesday the safety board's investigators
also believe leaking salt water from fish shipments caused the
Taiwan jet's corrosion.
   Gamble said Boeing had issued a series of service bulletins on
older 737s. Those included a March 1978 bulletin recommending
additional inspections of fuselage skins for possible corrosion. On
July 1, 1981, the FAA issued an airworthiness directive requiring
U.S. carriers to inspect older 737s.
   Boeing had supplied kits to airlines to allow them to replace
corroded skin on planes, Gamble said.
   A kit was delivered to Far Eastern in April 1980, which means it
was in the company's spare parts inventory considerably before that
crash, but it apparently was never used on the plane, he said.
   Cosgrove was in Washington, D.C., to attend a conference on
problems with aging aircraft and was unavailable for comment
Tuesday, Gamble said. The FAA called the three-day conference after
the Aloha incident to study safety issues involving older aircraft.
   One of the FAA directives issued after the Aloha accident
focuses on early models of 737s in which Boeing used a cold-bonding
process, in which structural parts of the fuselage were laminated
using an adhesive that cured at room temperature.
   T. Craig Martin, director of public relations for Boeing
Commercial Airplanes, said that about 1971, after the first 291
models of 737s were built, the company changed to a hot-bonding
process that used an adhesive that cured with heat. He said the new
method was a technological improvement over the previous process,
which was more prone to corrosion.
   About that time, Boeing also made a series of changes in
manufacturing processes and design, including strengthening parts
of the fuselage and making the skin thicker where sections
overlapped, Martin said.
   The twin-engine 737 is the world's most popular commercial
aircraft, with more than 2,000 on order.
   Martin said he found a number of differences between the two
accidents. The Taiwanese plane, for example, was 12 years old and
had approximately 33,000 landings, while the Aloha jet was 20 years
old and had about 90,000 landings.
   He said that ``as best we know,'' the Far Eastern accident was
caused by corrosion in the plane's cargo hold, while the Aloha
accident involved the top of the plane.
   ``But again, the appropriate thing is to see what the NTSB and
the FAA conclude before drawing all these analogies and
comparisons,'' Martin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
