<HEAD>High Court Grants Stay Of Execution To Georgia Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Tuesday granted a stay of
execution to Son H. Fleming, who had been scheduled to die in
Georgia's electric chair on Wednesday.
   The stay was granted at 6:53 p.m. EDT with Chief Justice William
Rehnquist and Justices Byron White and Sandra Day O'Connor
dissenting, said court spokeswoman Kathy Arberg.
   Fleming's family had also asked the state Board of Pardons and
Paroles to block his execution.
   Fleming, 58, was scheduled to die at 7 p.m. Wednesday for the
1976 slaying of Ray City Police Chief Ed Giddens.
   Georgia has executed 12 people since the U.S. Supreme Court
allowed states to restore the death penalty in 1976.
