<2ND_LINE>AM-Fleming Execution, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0721,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fleming Appeals To Parole Board On Eve Of Execution</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with Supreme Court granting
stay. Picks up 6th graf pvs ``Son Fleming's...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court granted a stay of
execution for condemned Georgia death row inmate Son H. Fleming on
Tuesday, a day before he was scheduled to die in the state's
electric chair.
   The high court granted the stay with no immediate comment,
except to note that Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices
Byron White and Sandra Day O'Connor dissented, said court
spokeswoman Kathy Arberg.
   Fleming, 58, was scheduled to die at 7 p.m. Wednesday for the
1976 slaying of Ray City Police Chief Ed Giddens. If the stay had
not been granted, he would have been the 99th person put to death
since the Supreme Court allowed states to restore the death penalty
in 1976. Georgia has killed 12 people.
   Giddens was abducted and killed after he stopped a car matching
the description of one used in a robbery. He had pleaded for his
life and told his captors he planned to retire the next day,
according to trial testimony.
   Henry Willis also received a death sentence for the slaying, but
no execution date has been set. A third defendant, Larry Fleming,
nephew of Son Fleming, was sentenced to life in prison.
   Earlier Tuesday, Fleming's family had asked the state Board of
Pardons and Paroles to block the execution.
   Son Fleming's attorney, Ken Shapiro, said Tuesday's appeal was
virtually the same as one filed two years ago, when Fleming came
within hours of execution. The latest petition has a supplement
containing a statement from Fleming's son, Shapiro said.
   The earlier appeal raised questions about Fleming's role in the
crime and cited three heart attacks Fleming has suffered during 12
years on death row. The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals stayed
the execution.
   Parole board Chairman Wayne Snow said after the 40-minute closed
hearing that the board would review the new appeal through the
afternoon. He said the board would consider Fleming's frail health
and his relatives' arguments.
   About 10 members of Flemings's family attended the hearing,
including four of his sisters and his younger brother, Handy
Fleming.
   ``I think he deserves another appeal,'' Handy Fleming said. ``I
really don't think he done it.''
   Shapiro said relatives described Fleming as a compassionate,
devoted family man who was a father figure for his younger brothers
and sisters after their father left home.
   ``There remains a question of Son's culpability,'' Shapiro said.
``Son has always maintained that he was not the triggerman.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
