<DOCNO> AP880531-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile 1stLd-Writethru a0748 05-31 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0748,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chile Extends State Of Emergency</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with junta member saying emergency will be
lifted before referendum, more exiles to be allowed to return. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government on Tuesday
decreed a 90-day extension of the state of emergency. Opposition
leaders say the extension will prevent a fair campaign in the
presidential referendum this year.
   In another development, Interior Ministry officials issued a
list Tuesday of 25 political exiles allowed to return home. It
included several prominent figures in the leftist government of
President Salvador Allende that was overthrown in September 1973.
   More than 4,000 exiles have been authorized to return since the
government began issuing periodic lists early in 1986, but only a
few hundred have done so. Human rights groups say 400 exiles still
are banned. The government claims the number is closer to 300.
   No date has been set for the presidential referendum, in which
Chileans will be allowed only to vote ``yes'' or ``no'' on a
single, military-appointed candidate for the 1989-97 term.
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet, who is 72 and has been president since
the 1973 military coup, is considered the most likely candidate.
   If voters reject the government's choice, a competitive election
is to occur a year later, with Pinochet remaining in office until
then.
   The state of emergency would have expired Tuesday.
   ``By renewing the state of emergency, the government is casting
doubt on the fairness of its own plebiscite,'' said Patricio
Aylwin, president of the centrist Christian Democratic Party, the
largest opposition group.
   Enrique Silva, president of the centrist Radical Party, said:
``Under the state of emergency, the most basic guarantees for a
clean electoral process cannot exist.''
   Government officials have hinted the election might be held
Sept. 11, which means the emergency would cover at least part of
the campaign.
   Adm. Jose Merino Castro, the navy chief and member of the ruling
military junta, told reporters after a junta meeting the emergency
would be lifted 30 days before the referendum.
   ``If the opposition doesn't like it, it means the state of
emergency is good,'' Merino said.
   Genaro Arriagada, a leading member of a 15-party coalition
organized to promote a ``no'' vote in the referendum called
extending the emergency ``a gross abuse'' by the government.
   Officials claim the emergency is necessary to deal with what the
government calls a growing terrorist threat from radical leftists.
   The Roman Catholic Church and several foreign governments,
including the Reagan administration, have urged Pinochet to lift
the restrictions before the referendum.
   Under the emergency, which was imposed when the military seized
power and has been enforced intermittently since, the government
can restrict freedom of the press and ban public gatherings.
   It allows authorities to censor mail and prevent citizens from
entering or leaving the country or traveling freely. The emergency
is enforced by regional military commanders.
   On December 17, 1987, President Reagan declared his support for
a European Economic Community statement urging Pinochet's
government to lift the restrictions several months before the
election. The EEC statement said that was essential for a fair
campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ObscenityLaw     05-31 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obscenity Law,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Videotape Retailers, Anti-Porn Group Head For Showdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-pornography group is planning to
picket videotape retailers, who plan to retaliate with boycott
threats against protesters' employers, as amendments to the state's
obscenity law take effect.
   A group called the Minnesota Cleanup Project plans to protest at
about 50 videotape stores throughout the state Saturday to draw
attention to provisions taking effect Wednesday and to urge local
officials to enforce it, said Robert P. Heinrich, director of the
anti-pornography organization.
   But video store owners are planning a countermove, said David
Ballstadt, president of Adventures in Video, which operates 10
videotape stores in the Minneapolis-St. Paul area.
   ``In retaliation for this picketing, video store operators are
going to hire private detectives, take down license plate numbers
of people picketing and find out where they are employed,''
Ballstadt said. Letters will be sent to the picketers' employers
telling them their products will be boycotted because of their
employees' activities, he said.
   ``If these people think they can walk around and express their
freedoms, which they have a right to do, they're going to have to
pay a price, just as we have to,'' Ballstadt said.
   The Legislature approved amendments this year to make the
state's obscenity law conform with U.S. Supreme Court rulings.
   ``The changes technically are not that great, but they do
provide some tools for prosecutors to use,'' Minnesota Solicitor
General Norm Coleman said.
   The previous law provided only for civil penalties and left
unclear what role prosecutors should play in enforcing it, Coleman
said.
   The new law provides for criminal penalties, which clearly are
in the purview of county prosecutors, he said. A first offense is
considered a gross misdemeanor and carries a penalty of up to one
year in prison, a $3,000 fine or both. Subsequent offenses are
considered felonies and carry a prison term of up to two years, a
fine of up to $10,000 or both.
   Among its provisions, the law prohibits distribution of obscene
materials and specifically includes videotapes in its definition of
materials that may be deemed obscene.
   ``Anything on film or video is more enticing than a still
picture, and this material is readily available to children of all
ages and people of all ages,'' Heinrich said.
   Heinrich said pickets will target ``major hard-core pornography
outlets throughout the state'' which previously were contacted by
the group and have refused to remove what the group considers
obscene materials from their shelves.
   Besides picketing stores in Minneapolis, St. Paul and some
suburbs, protests are planned at stores in Mankato, St. Cloud and
Rochester, he said.
   Though Ballstadt came up with the idea for the boycott to
counter the pickets, his own stores may no longer offer the
videotapes targeted by the group. A decision has yet to be made, he
said.
</TEXT>
