<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia     05-31 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Leader Calls For Better Relations With U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam of
Ethiopia called on Tuesday for better relations between his Marxist
government and the United States, reminding Americans, ``Once upon
a time we were good friends.''
   The leader of this East African nation also made an impassioned
defense of Ethiopia's war in its northern provinces, charging that
the rebels are fighting a proxy war to consolidate Arab control of
the Red Sea.
   In reply to a question, Mengistu denied that his government was
using food as a weapon in the north, where the war and a big
government counteroffensive have jeopardized a massive
Western-financed relief effort for 3.2 million Ethiopians facing
starvation in Eritrea and Tigre provinces.
   Instead, Mengistu insisted, rebels were using ``an issue as
sensitive as a food deficit situation and hunger to elicit
international sympathy and support for them to promote their
propaganda activities against us.''
   Mengistu spoke with unusual candor on a wide range of issues,
gesticulating with passion and occasionally smiling and laughing
during a six-hour news conference with foreign reporters, his first
since May 1986.
   For the first time, Mengistu accused Arab states of backing the
northern secessionist insurgency, where rebels have won major
victories this year by capturing several towns.
   Rebels of the Eritrean People's Liberation Front have been
fighting for 27 years in Africa's oldest civil war.
   Mengistu made no reference to the insurgency by rebels of the
Tigrean People's Liberation Front, who have been fighting for 14
years for a bigger say in the governing of their province.
   Mengistu said the U.S. government refused to impose sanctions on
South Africa but was ``imposing an undeclared embargo'' on
Ethiopia. He said Washington was ``at the verge of cutting the last
tethers which we have to the United States'' with congressional
discussions last week on stopping annual imports of 20,000 tons of
Ethiopian coffee.
   ``We are not really pleased with our relations with the United
States and it is our hope that better times will come in the
future. We want to assure them, and I am sincere, quite sincere,
about this, that we will do our best to improve relations,''
Mengistu said. ``We have always pushed for better relations with
the United States and I hope the United States will reciprocate ..
. Once upon a time we were good friends.''
   He said Ethiopians were fond of the American people and admired
their achivements, but relations could improve only if ``the United
States accepts us on a basis of equality and respect.''
   ``We are really not sure what mistakes we have committed against
the (U.S.) government,'' he said, adding perhaps it was Ethiopia's
choice of socialism that was repugnant to ``the defender of
capitalist values.''
   He said Ethiopia's Marxist revolution of September 1974 had
improved lives of the country's 42 million people. Contrary to
Western news reports, he said, and to U.S. government insistence on
categorizing it as communist, his government was not an ogre intent
on filling Ethiopia's prisons with political dissidents and
starving its people.
   Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, were
puzzled by Mengistu's conciliatory attitude. They said Ethiopia at
the last minute caused Chester Crocker, U.S. assistant secretary of
state for African affairs, to cancel a January visit when it
announced he would not be meeting Mengistu.
   In February, Crocker said he believed Ethiopia was not serious
about improving relations with the United States.
   Once-warm U.S. relations with Ethiopia deteriorated after the
revolution in which Mengistu and a clique of fellow army officers
overthrew Emperor Haile Selassie.
   The United States continued to arm the new military government
until Somalia invaded Ethiopia's southern Ogaden region in 1977.
   In a dramatic superpower reversal, the Soviets switched sides to
Ethiopia and the United States started backing the Somalis.
   Mengistu said Tuesday that rebels in Ethiopia also had won
support from progressive countries, which the diplomats identified
as Cuba and the Soviet Union, which in the past have helped trained
Eritrean rebels. About 2,500 Cuban troops in Ethiopia have refused
to fight in the north.
</TEXT>
