<1ST_LINE>u w AM-EMPSuit     05-31 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EMP Suit,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Tests Put Off By Court Order; Were Set To Start Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Tuesday temporarily enjoined
the Navy from starting tests of a high-powered electrical generator
designed to simulate one of the effects of a nuclear explosion.
   U.S. District Judge John Garrett Penn, after hearing arguments
from attorneys representing the Navy and the Foundation on Economic
Trends, issued a temporary restraining order against the tests,
which were set to begin Wednesday.
   The restraining order, which expires at noon Friday, was issued
to give the government time to file a motion striking a paragraph
from a consent decree the foundation contends prohibits the Navy
from beginning the tests.
   Navy officials had planned to begin the test Wednesday with
Empress II barge in international waters about 15 miles off the
Virginia-North Carolina coast.
   The Empress II barge is equipped with two diesel generators and
a huge antenna system, capable of sending ``pulses'' of electrical
power into the atmosphere at power levels up to 7 million volts to
test a phenomenon known as electro-magnetic pulse, or EMP.
   Each pulse lasts only a billionth of a second, and the Navy
maintains the testing will have no affect on human or marine life.
   Electro-magnetic pulse is a powerful wave, or surge, of
electrical energy that is released by a nuclear explosion and which
can travel long distances through the atmosphere or water.
   EMP became a matter of concern to the military in the early
1960's when the Pentagon discovered a nuclear bomb detonated at
high altitudes could generate a pulse so strong it could disable
the electronic components used in computers, communications and
guidance equipment.
   As a result of that discovery, military laboratories have
studied the phenomenon for 25 years in the course of developing
methods for ``hardening'' electronic weapon components to withstand
EMP. The Navy wants to use the Empress II barge to test its success
in hardening electronic equipment on warships.
   The Foundation on Economic Trends, an activist environmental
group that has long tried to curtail biological weapon research,
sued the Defense Department in March 1987 with the goal of stopping
all EMP testing until environmental impact studies had been
performed.
   The lawsuit asserted that EMP experiments could ``affect human
health directly, and through the disruption of electronic circuits
in nuclear power plants, automobiles, computers, airplanes, phone
lines and navigational systems, can cause potential catastrophies
under many possible circumstances.''
   Two weeks ago, the Pentagon agreed to settle that suit by
sharply curtailing or shutting down EMP research facilities across
the country until environmental assessments were performed. In the
case of Empress II, however, the Navy argues it already has
performed the necessary environmental study and thus can proceed
with testing.
   The foundation acknowledges the Navy has finished one
environmental study, but says the recent settlement clearly
envisioned the Navy performing a second study because the first
focused on the effect of EMP testing in the Chesapeake Bay, not the
Atlantic Ocean.
   Congress prohibited EMP testing in the Chesapeake.
   ``The U.S. Navy has violated the settlement,'' asserted Jeremy
Rifkin, the president of the foundation.
   ``Our attorneys questioned them on this before we finalized the
settlement. They can't claim now that the first impact study is
sufficient. And if Congress says it's too dangerous for the bay,
why should the waters off North Carolina be treated differently?''
   Penn's ruling gives the Navy time to file a motion to strike the
paragraph in the consent decree that Rifkin contends prohibits the
test.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
