<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ExecutionBan     05-31 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Execution Ban,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Urges Legislation To Outlaw Execution Of The Mentally
Retarded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for the mentally retarded said
Tuesday that executing the mentally retarded, even those convicted
of first degree murder, is cruel and unusual punishment and urged
lawmakers nationwide to outlaw the practice.
   ``It has been our experience that even the foremost proponents
of the dealth penalty draw the line at young children and people
with mental retardation,'' said James W. Ellis, president-elect of
the American Association on Mental Retardation.
   ``States which have the death penalty, in our view, must pass
laws that make it unlawful to execute someone who is mentally
retarded or to sentence to death someone who is mentally
retarded,'' said Ellis.
   Ellis announced the organization's resolution calling for a ban
on the death penalty for the retarded at a press conference during
the group's annual conference, citing a recently passed Georgia law
that allows for a plea of ``guilty but mentally retarded.''
   Ellis, a law professor at the University of New Mexico at
Albuquerque, said the Georgia law requires a psychological
examination for defendants who wished to enter the plea.
Individuals convicted under the law could be sentenced to life
imprisonment but not executed he said.
   Ellis also noted that most of the members of the Georgia
Assembly are strong supporters of capital punishment.
   The Georgia law, which becomes effective July 1, was prompted by
widespread criticism of the June 24, 1986 execution of mentally
retarded convicted murderer Jerome Bowden.
   ``This position, that the mentally retarded should never be
sentenced to death or executed, leaves the whole array of the
criminal justice system left to deal with in any way that seems
most appropriate,'' said Richard H. Burr of the NAACP Legal Defense
and Educational Fund, Inc. which has handled several capital
punishment cases involving the mentally retarded.
   According to figures compiled by Burr's group, at least 13
percent of the 66 persons executed since capital punishment was
reinstated in 1976 had been diagnosed as mentally retarded.
   Burr also noted that while blacks comprise 40 percent of the
general prison population, 80 percent of all mentally retarded
prisoners are black or Hispanic.
   Both men agreed that initial determination of a defendant's
mental capacity was vital to correcting the problem. They urged
states to follow the example of Texas, which routinely tests its
prison inmates for mental deficiencies.
   ``We need to address the needs of criminal offenders or criminal
defendants from the very begining when confessions are sought, when
waivers of rights are sought, '' Ellis said. He noted the need to
educate members of the criminal justice system about mental
retardation ``to make sure justice is done'' in cases involving the
mentally retarded.
   But Burr cautioned that even with these procedures in place a
number of mentally retarded defendants may be ``deemed competent to
stand trail or educated sufficiently to become compenent to stand
trial ... and (could be) convicted'' to face possible execution.
   Burr noted that there were several cases currently in the court
system in which a retarded individual sits on death row. He cited
the case of Limmie Arthur, 28, of South Carolina who was convicted
in the ax murder of a crippled neighbor in 1985.
   Burr said the courts should be to asked decide whether executing
Arthur, whom he said has the mind of a 10- or 12-year old, would
constitute a violation of the 8th Amendment's prohibition of cruel
and unusual punishment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
