<2ND_LINE>AM-School Violence, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0771,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Who Assault Teachers Will Be Expelled, Koch Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts two grafs after 6th ``Koch said'' to UPDATE with Koch
not sure of legislative approval is needed, and with later teacher
shooting. Picks up 7th graf pvs ``The recent...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Any student who assaults a teacher will be
expelled, and school security will be beefed up, officials decided
Tuesday after a rash of attacks on teachers.
   ``The notion you have a right to free education is assumed,''
Chancellor Richard Green said. ``Students who violate that right by
assaulting teachers or any other school personnel will forfeit that
right for the rest of the school year.''
   He said students who engage in anything ``beyond a normal fight,
will find themselves without a public education in New York City.''
   Previously, students were suspended or transferred to other
schools.
   The decision came after Green met with Mayor Edward I. Koch, the
city's district attorneys and the police commissioner about
violence in the schools.
   Koch said security measures at the schools will include metal
detectors, electromagnetic locks, listening devices and more police.
   He added later that the city was researching whether it needs
action by the state Legislature to permit expulsions.
   Just hours after the announcement, a Bronx teacher was grazed in
the leg by a stray bullet as she left her school, but the police
said the shooter apparently was not a student.
   The recent incidents include an attack with a baseball bat
against one teacher and the injury of another who was burned when
she picked up a firecracker tossed into her classroom.
   Board of Education spokesman Frank Sabrino said the number of
serious incidents, such as assault, robbery, sex crimes, weapons
possession and drug violations, is running about 10 percent ahead
of the 3,528 reported during the last school year. From July 1 to
April 30, 969 assaults included 198 against teachers, he said.
   Koch said at a City Hall news conference that the expulsion
policy was ``the first and most important action'' that came out of
the meeting of the officials.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said more police will be
assigned to patrol at schools where needed.
   ``We are committed to covering those schools at the beginning of
the school day and at the end of the school day,'' he said.
   He estimated that about 200 of the system's 932 schools will
have police officers assigned, at least until the end of the school
year.
   Koch also said the officials agreed ``to ask the Legislature for
a change in the existing law so as to make it a felony if there is
an attack upon a public official, teachers, others in the
performance of their duties.''
   Bronx District Attorney Paul Gentile said he was for greater
punishment of school thugs.
   Sandra Feldman, president of the United Federation of Teachers,
said she was satisfied at the outcome of the officials' meeting.
   ``We're going to be watching it very carefully to make sure
these commitments are carried out,'' she said.
</TEXT>
