<2ND_LINE>AM-Terminal Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0825,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemicals In Burning Terminal Cause Evacuation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with four grafs to UPDATE with fire stil burning
Tuesday night. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``Most of...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALLIANCE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters used backhoes Tuesday to dig
their way toward a warehouse containing pesticides in an attempt to
smother a blaze that forced the evacuation of 800 people.
   The fire at the Roadway Express Freight Terminal started about
12:30 a.m., and firefighters were still dealing with small fires
and hot spots Tuesday night. The terminal itself and several
tractor-trailer rigs parked at its loading dock were destroyed.
   Twenty people complaining of nausea and headaches were treated
at hospitals and released. Two firefighters were treated for
injuries from falls.
   Authorities quit spraying the building with water for about
seven hours starting at 3 a.m. to prevent runoff of possibly
contaminated water. Later, firefighters used backhoes to dig toward
the fire and smother it, Alliance Safety Service Director John
Benincasa said.
   Most of the residents evacuated from within a 10-mile radius of
the terminal were told they could return home by midafternoon
Tuesday, but authorities advised residents who lived within a few
blocks of the burning building to stay away. Alliance, a community
of 24,000, is located about 50 miles southeast of Cleveland.
   Tim Hickin of the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency said rat
poisons, ant killer, two other pesticides and an aerosal propellant
were being stored in the building.
   The terminal was used by Clem Lumber Co. and The d-Con Co. as a
warehouse.
   The blaze prompted the closing of the Alliance, Sebring, West
Branch and Western Reserve schools as a precaution against wind
carrying a dark gray cloud of smoke from the freight terminal. The
public beach at Atwood Lake, about 40 miles south of the fire, also
was closed because the wind was carrying the cloud in that
direction Tuesday morning.
</TEXT>
