<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MurderContract     05-31 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder Contract,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Face Trial In Murder, Mutilation Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors say a couple who went
on trial Tuesday for allegedly plotting to dismember their
son-in-law and his family wanted color photos and body parts to
restore the honor they lost when their daughter married against
their will.
   The alleged plot was stopped before anyone was hurt, but Saud
and Ghada Tarawneh, of Toledo, Ohio, were accused of murder
conspiracy and solicitation to commit murder. The Tarawnehs were
arrested in February in Toledo.
   The defense contends the threats of death and dismemberment were
Arabic overstatement in an attempt to frighten their daughter, who
was living in Tamarac.
   Attorneys were scheduled to deliver opening statements
Wednesday. Before a jury was selected Tuesday, defense attorney
Barry Roderman sought to suppress tapes of the couple talking to a
police informer. District Judge Russell Seay denied the motion.
   ``Preparing for trial I read a book called `The Arab Mind' and
the contention there is that the Arab mind does a lot of barking
but very little biting,'' Roderman said outside the courtroom. ``I
don't mean to say that to start an international feud, but I think,
again, if you listen to the tapes when they're played you're going
to get a different perspective on the case.''
   Prosecutors also agree there is a cultural element in the case,
the pride of the Bedouin tribe the Tarawnehs belonged to _ but they
consider the plot deadly serious.
   ``Keeping body parts as souvenirs _ I don't think is normal,''
said Assistant State Attorney William Dimitrouleas.
   The couple left Jordan 18 years ago and moved to Toledo. When
their daughter married her Syrian cousin in 1986 over their
objections and moved to Tamarac, tradition required the insult be
avenged.
   By tradition the head of a family who loses his honor is no
longer a man, and his family shares that disgrace.
   Tarawneh, 46, a gynecologist who became a U.S. citizen in 1980,
and his wife Ghada, 44, a nurse, already had arranged a marriage
for their 17-year-old daughter Raniah and refused to allow her to
marry Mouataz Abdulsalam, now 28.
   When Raniah left Jordan with her new husband, the family wanted
to send her back and sell her into a prostitution ring, according
to Mike Breece, an investigator with the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement.
   The parents then allegedly tried to set up the killings of their
daughter's new husband, his younger sister and his mother.
   The plans included instructions for the killer to hang all three
people, take photographs of the bodies, cut the mother's tongue out
and sexually mutilate the husband and his sister, Breece said.
   A private investigator the parents allegedly tried to hire told
authorities about the plot and agreed to cooperate with
investigators, Breece said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
