<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KennedyExhibit     05-31 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy Exhibit,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy Family's Friends Annoyed At Plans For Dallas Exhibit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUINCY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends of the Kennedy family are upset
with plans to make a museum out of a part of the building used in
President John F. Kennedy's assassination.
   ``Being polite, I'd describe it as either morbid or disgusting
or both,'' former Kennedy aide Charles Daly said.
   The plan entails turning the floor of the former Texas School
Book Depository building from which Lee Harvey Oswald shot the
president into a museum on the assassination.
   ``To focus on that instead of a person's life just seems to me
disgusting,'' said Daly, director of the Kennedy library in Boston.
   Another family friend who asked not to be identified told The
Patriot Ledger of Quincy that Kennedy family members also were
upset. ``They really are dismayed with this. It's such a poor idea
that I just don't believe they want to discuss it.''
   Dallas officials say thousands of tourists come to the building
every year but cannot gain access to the sixth-floor because it is
closed. The rest of the building houses government offices.
   Lindalyn Adams, president of the Dallas County Historical
Society, said the museum will contain a multimedia presentation
including news clippings about the Nov. 22, 1963, assassination and
the world's reaction to it.
   ``It's a place where history was made, a sad part of history,''
Ms. Adams said.
   Conover Hunt, an organizer of the museum project, described the
planned exhibit as ``low key'' and said it will not contain
``violent or gruesome artifacts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
