<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ecuador-Strike 1stLd-Writethru a0846 05-31 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador-Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0846,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emergency Declared, Troops Arrest Dozens on Campus in Quito</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, with updated figures,
other. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CARLOS CISTERNAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers arrested dozens of protesting
students and teachers on a university campus in Quito on Tuesday
after the government declared a state of emergency to counter a
planned nationwide strike.
   Interior Minister Heinz Moeller said troops arrested 27 people
at the National Polytechnical School, entering the school after
students threw rocks at a car carrying military personnel.
   At an evening news conference, he called the planned general
strike ``illegal and anti-constitutional.''
   Ruben Orellana, the university rector, said both students and
professors were detained. The independent station Radio Quito said
60 people were seized.
   Witnesses said troops also fired machine guns, but no casualties
were reported. Moeller did not mention any gunfire nor did he
identify those arrested.
   President Leon Febres Cordero signed a state of emergency order
that went into effect at 9 p.m. Tuesday, just hours before the
one-day, anti-government general strike was to start Wednesday.
   The strike, the seventh against the Febres Cordero government,
was called by the communist-led United Front of Laborers, Ecuador's
most powerful union.
   Fausto Durand, president of the 200,000-member union, said the
main demand is an increase in workers' wages from $31 a month to
$76.
   Labor unrest in this small Andean nation has intensified over
the past two years, because of economic woes arising largely from
depressed world prices for oil, Ecuador's main export.
   Elementary and secondary school teachers struck 11 days ago,
seeking income tax cuts and protesting public transportation fare
increases of 50 percent.
   College students have since held sporadic street demonstrations
in Quito in support of the teachers.
   The state of emergency permits the government to use troops to
maintain order, censor the news media and ban public meetings.
   During the last general strike Oct. 28, demonstrators firebombed
a Quito bank, disrupted work and transportation in several cities.
Dozens of strikers were arrested and there were several injuries in
clashes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
