<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cassini-Jovan     05-31 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cassini-Jovan,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards Oleg Cassini $16 Million in Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Designer Oleg Cassini won a $16 million award
Tuesday from a federal court jury that found in his favor against
fragrance maker Jovan Inc. in a breach of contract suit.
   The six-member civil jury took just three hours to find in
Cassini's favor against Jovan and it's former president, Richard E.
Meyer.
   Cassini, 75, who designed clothes for Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis
when she was first lady, claimed Jovan and Meyer violated a 1978
contract to make and market a fragrance line for men and women
under Cassini's name.
   In testimony during the four-week trial before U.S. District
Judge John F. Keenan, Cassini complained that Jovan was selling the
perfume in discount stores like K mart instead of limiting sales to
fashionable department stores like Bloomingdale's.
   Cassini sued in 1984 for $24 million, accusing Jovan _ now known
as Beecham Cosmetics Inc. _ of breach of contract. He also sued
Jovan and Meyer for fraud.
   The jury awarded Cassini $10 million on the breach of contract
claim against the company, $1 million on the fraud claim against
the company and $5 million on the fraud claim against Meyer.
   After the verdict, defense lawyers moved for a new trial but
Keenan did not immediately rule on the request.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
