<NOTE>For Release Tuesday, June 7</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Today is Tuesday, June 7, the 159th day of 1988. There are 207
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   Twenty years ago, on June 7, 1968, the body of Sen. Robert F.
Kennedy lay in state at St. Patrick's Cathedral in New York. That
same day, a grand jury in Los Angeles indicted Sirhan Bishara
Sirhan, a Jordanian citizen, on a charge of first-degree murder in
the assassination of Kennedy two days earlier.
   On this date:
   In 1654, Louis the XIV was crowned King of France in Rheims.
   In 1769, probably on June 7, according to Kentucky's Historical
Society, frontiersman Daniel Boone first began to explore the
present-day Bluegrass State.
   In 1776, Richard Henry Lee of Virginia proposed to the
Continental Congress a resolution calling for a Declaration of
Independence.
   In 1848, French post-impressionist painter Paul Gauguin was born
in Paris.
   In 1864, Abraham Lincoln was nominated for another term as
President at his party's convention in Baltimore.
   In 1929, the sovereign state of Vatican City came into existence
as copies of the Lateran Treaty were exchanged in Rome.
   In 1939, Britain's King George VI and Queen Elizabeth arrived in
Niagara Falls, N.Y., for a visit to the United States following a
tour of Canada.
   In 1948, the communists completed their takeover of
Czechoslovakia with the resignation of President Eduard Benes.
   In 1967, author-critic Dorothy Parker, famed for her caustic
wit, died in New York.
   In 1977, Britain celebrated the silver jubilee of Queen
Elizabeth II.
   In 1980, a better than 50-1 long shot, Temperence Hill, won the
Belmont Stakes in New York.
   In 1981, Israeli military planes destroyed a nuclear power plant
in Iraq, a facility the Israelis charged could have been used to
make nuclear weapons.
   In 1982, President and Mrs. Reagan flew to Rome for a six-hour
visit that included a meeting with Pope John Paul II, then traveled
to London for a welcome from Queen Elizabeth.
   Ten years ago: Addressing the graduating class at the U.S. Naval
Academy in Annapolis, Md., President Jimmy Carter called on the
Soviet Union to choose between ``confrontation or cooperation''
with the United States. The Illinois House of Representatives fell
short of the votes needed to approve the proposed Equal Rights
Amendment.
   Five years ago: The United States ordered the expulsion of 21
Nicaraguan diplomats and closed six consulates, one day after the
Sandinistas expelled three U.S. diplomats, charging them with
plotting to kill Nicaragua's foreign minister.
   One year ago: ``Les Miserables'' dominated Broadway's Tony
Awards, taking eight prizes, including best musical. ``Fences,'' by
August Wilson, was named best play.
   Today's Birthdays: Actress Jessica Tandy is 79. U.S. Rep. Peter
Rodino (D- N.J.) is 79. Former boxing champion Rocky Graziano is
66. Actress Delores Gray is 64. Singer Tom Jones is 48. Rock
drummer Bill Kreutzmann is 42. Singer-musician Prince is 30.
   Thought for Today: ``Two dangers constantly threaten the world:
order and disorder.'' _ Paul Valery, French poet (1871-1945).
   End Adv Tuesday Junee 7
</TEXT>
