<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv09   05-31 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv09,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adv09</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, June 9</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Today is Thursday, June 9, the 161st day of 1988. There are 205
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On June 9, 1954, in one of the most dramatic confrontations of
the Senate-Army hearings, Army counsel Joseph N. Welch assailed
Sen. Joseph R. McCarthy for his attack on a member of Welch's law
firm, Frederick G. Fisher. Said Welch: ``Have you no sense of
decency, sir? At long last, have you left no sense of decency?''
   On this date:
   In A.D. 68, the Roman Emperor Nero committed suicide.
   In 1784, John Carroll, who would become the first Roman Catholic
bishop in the United States, was appointed supervisor of Catholic
missions in the Uniteed States.
   In 1860, the first dime novel _ titled ``Malaeska: The Indian
Wife of the White Hunter'' _ was published.
   In 1870, author Charles Dickens died in Godshill, England.
   In 1892, composer-lyricist Cole Porter was born in Peru, Ind.
   In 1940, Norway surrendered to the Nazis during World War II.
   In 1953, about 100 people died when a tornado struck Worcester,
Mass.
   In 1969, the U.S. Senate confirmed Warren Burger to be the new
chief justice of the United States, succeeding Earl Warren.
   In 1973, Secretariat became horse racing's first Triple Crown
winner in 25 years by winning the Belmont Stakes in New York.
   In 1986, the Rogers Commission released its report on the
Challenger disaster, criticizing NASA and rocket-builder Morton
Thiokol for management problems leading to the explosion that
claimed the lives of seven astronauts.
   Ten years ago: Leaders of the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints struck down a 148-year-old policy of excluding
black men from the Mormon priesthood. In sports, Larry Holmes won a
split decision over Ken Norton to take the World Boxing Council's
heavyweight title.
   Five years ago: British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and her
Conservative government won re-election, gaining a 144-seat
majority over opposition lawmakers in Parliament.
   One year ago: In a second day of testimony before the
Iran-Contra committees, Fawn Hall said she had spirited secret
documents from the White House because she feared they would fall
into the wrong hands. Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr. of Delaware
announced his candidacy for the Democratic presidential nomination.
   Today's Birthdays: Former World Bank president and former
Defense Secretary Robert S. McNamara is 72. Former NBC News
correspondent Marvin Kalb is 58. Baseball player Dave Parker is 37.
Actor Michael J. Fox is 27.
   Thought for Today: ``The final lesson of history: `Let's never
go back there again!''' _ Friedrich Nietzsche, German philosopher
(1844-1900).
   End Adv Thurs June 9
</TEXT>
</DOC>
