<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Argentina-Nuclear Adv07   05-31 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Nuclear, Adv 07,0799</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, June 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Argentina Considering Shutdown of Nuclear Plant Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial shortfalls may force
Argentina, Latin America's leading user of nuclear power, to halt
construction on a third nuclear reactor and a heavy-water plant,
its top nuclear official says.
   Plans are being made to stop work on the nuclear reactor Atucha
II, which is 60 percent completed, and Arroyito, 90 percent
finished, unless financing is obtained or the government agrees to
a $800 million budget request, said Emma Perez Ferreira, president
of the National Atomic Energy Commission.
   ``We'll have to stop work on the big ones first if we don't get
enough money or obtain financing for the projects,'' Ms. Perez
Ferreira, Argentina's top-ranking female government official, said
in a recent interview.
   A shutdown could hurt Argentina's nuclear industry, which is the
most advanced in the Western Hemisphere outside the United States
and Canada, and cut into its future sales of surplus heavy water.
   Argentina has a contract to build a $100-million, 10-megawatt
nuclear reactor outside Lima, Peru. It also has contracts to build
a nuclear reactor in Algeria and to provide enriched uranium for a
small experimental nuclear reactor at Iran's Tehran University, Ms.
Perez Ferreira said.
   Argentina's nuclear technicians have mastered the entire fuel
cycle, which gives them the ability to make nuclear weapons, but
officials from President Raul Alfonsin on down deny this is in
their plans.
   At one time, the nuclear program was closely tied to the armed
forces, in particular the navy. An admiral headed the Atomic Energy
Commission until the early 1980s, and some reports at the time said
the military favored building an atomic bomb.
   Argentina mines its own uranium ore in the Andes. It prepares
its own fuel, and is capable of enriching the fuel, making fuel
elements, running nuclear reactors and reprocessing the fuel.
Enriching and reprocessing fuel are the keys to making nuclear
weapons.
   Argentina, the world's eighth-largest country geographically,
has two existing nuclear power plants. Until its economic crisis
worsened last year, it had dreams of building four power plants by
the end of the century.
   ``There's no sense in talking now even about a fourth nuclear
plant,'' Ms. Perez Ferreira said. Argentina also has an
uranium-enrichment plant, six research reactors and two
reprocessing plants.
   The nuclear program is important to Argentina, providing up to
20 percent of its electrical power, and is a source of pride to a
country whose standard of living has declined steadily since the
1950s.
   But now Argentina is the developing world's third-largest debtor
behind Brazil and Mexico, owing $55 billion. It also has a 247
percent inflation rate in addition to other severe economic
problems, including a loss of real wages for workers.
   Indeed, 22 percent of Atomic Energy Commission's 6,500-member
work force have left their jobs since 1983, many for similar posts
offering double their pay in Switzerland, Brazil and the United
States, Ms. Perez Ferreira said.
   Neighboring Brazil has a nuclear-power program but its sole
plant near Rio de Janeiro has had constant troubles. Plans to build
two other nuclear plants have been set aside for the time being.
   Ms. Perez Ferreira, a 52-year-old nuclear physicist, took over
the commission last year when her predecessor quit over budgetary
disputes with the government. As head of commission, she reports
directly to President Alfonsin.
   Although officials deny any plans for nuclear weapons, Argentina
has yet to sign the international nuclear non-proliferation treaty.
   It opposes the treaty on grounds that it interferes with
national sovereignty. The other non-signatory nations with nuclear
technology are South Africa, Israel, India, Pakistan and Brazil.
   Accidents at Argentine nuclear facilities have left three
technicians dead since 1982 but experts say Argentina is not
considered unsafe. A radioactive water spill and a burst pipe also
briefly shut down Atucha I and the Embalse plant last year and in
May.
   National reliance on nuclear-generated power became apparent in
April when power shortages caused in part by temporary shutdowns of
Atucha I and Embalse forced emergency power cutoffs in Buenos
Aires, Mar del Plata and other major cities.
   Argentina's nuclear interest stems from 1950, during the first
presidency of Juan D. Peron. Its first power plant was Atucha I, a
335-megawatt facility built with West German technology in 1974.
   The second, Embalse, outside Cordoba in north-central Argentina,
was finished in 1983. Built with Canadian technology, it has 600
megawatts of power, equal to the Connecticut Yankee plant in the
United States.
   Atucha II, if it is completed, will have 745 megawatts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, June 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
