<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Singapore-Eights Adv08   05-31 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singapore-Eights, Adv 08,0764</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, June 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Aug. 8 Makes '88 a Special Year in Singapore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The auspicious date rolls around only once a
century _ 8@8@88 _ and it has number-conscious couples in Singapore
flocking to get married on that day.
   Engaged couples have already booked all 90 available slots at
the Registry of Marriages on Aug. 8. The registry has had to put up
a sign telling couples it has no more openings.
   Those being turned away have the option of joining more than 100
other couples in mass nuptials at a theater-restaurant that will be
staffed by registry officials.
   At least four hotels and six restaurants are fully booked for
Chinese wedding dinners on Monday, Aug. 8.
   The date is auspicious because Cantonese-speaking Chinese
pronounce the number eight ``paat,'' which sounds like ``faat,''
which means prosperity.
   Hence the belief that a date made up of all eights bodes well
for the future.
   Many of those who can't marry on Aug. 8 seek propitious
alternatives.
   The Registry of Marriages, which usually averages 43 marriages a
day, reports that Aug. 1 and 2 are proving popular as second
choices.
   The local usage of numerical dates places the day first followed
by month and year. So Aug. 1 appears 1@8@88. It is pronounced ``yat
paat paat paat,'' which sounds like once prosperous always
prosperous.
   Aug. 2, or 2@8@88, is pronounced ``yee paat paat paat'' _ easy
to be prosperous.
   Some of the betrothed want to cover two special dates. They plan
to marry on Aug. 8 but delay the wedding dinner until Sept. 18,
which in the lunar year, coincides with the eighth day of the
eighth moon.
   ``Sept. 18 was fully booked in November last year,'' said
Jessica Eng of the Cathay Restaurant.
   Millions in Singapore, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Malaysia and other
parts of Asia hold a deep respect for what they perceive as the
power of certain numbers, particularly older people whose beliefs
are strongly influenced by the traditions of China.
   While 13 is unlucky to Westerners, the number four, alone or in
a combination such as 24 or 44, is bad news for many Chinese
because in Cantonese it sounds like the word for dying.
   Numbers affect many things. Municipal officials say they receive
about 10 written and many oral requests each year from people who
want to change house numbers because the ones they have are unlucky.
   Applicants get a standard reply: no change is possible ``as this
will result in a haphazard system, abuse and impropriety.''
   Real estate agents say that if Chinese have a choice when buying
or renting property, they generally shun houses or apartments with
the number four. Some developers offer discounts when selling
condominiums with unlucky numbers, especially if the market is
sluggish.
   The auctioning of license plates with lucky numbers fetched the
equivalent of about $1 million in Singapore dollars in the last
three years for the Registry of Vehicles. Plates with multiple
number eights are special favorites.
   If Aug. 8, 1988 was not auspicious enough, this is also the year
of the dragon in the Chinese astrological cycle. Following a rabbit
year in the 12-year zodiac, the dragon is considered a mighty
creature that bestows blessings.
   A spokesman for the Population Planning Unit said it expects an
increase in births this year, children who will be known as dragon
seeds.
   Not everyone agrees that popular dates have much to do with
custom or traditional belief.
   ``The couples have departed completely from the Chinese almanac
in choosing these dates,'' said Lee Siow Mong, a retired educator
and president of the China Society. ``The traditional way is to
pick the proper date and time according to the almanac,''
   ``Personally, I think all this talk about 8@8@88 being lucky is
very stupid and baseless,'' Lee said in an interview with The
Straits Times newspaper.
   Nevertheless, Maggie Tay, who was told that all the Registry of
Marriage slots were taken on Aug. 8, still wants to go by the
numbers.
   ``It is a special day that comes along only once in a hundred
years,'' she said, adding that she was considering New Year's Day
as an alternative.
   ``Yat yat paat kow'' (1@1@89) sounds like ``everyday prosper
forever.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, June 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Mexico-Illegals Adv09   05-31 0800</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Illegals, Adv 09,0828</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, June 9, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Undocumented Workers Still Taking Risks for Jobs in U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``They keep crossing the river,'' said
Mario Trejo in Ciudad Juarez on the Rio Grande.
   He was talking about Mexican laborers and how the new U.S.
immigration law wasn't stopping them from illegally crossing the
border to work in the United States.
   ``And people still are coming from the central and south of
Mexico hoping to go to the other side,'' Trejo said on the
telephone. He is the press chief for Mayor Jaime Bermudez in Ciudad
Juarez, on the other side of the Rio Grande from El Paso, Texas.
   He and other Mexican authorities believe the unwritten law of
supply and demand is winning out over the 1986 U.S. Immigration
Reform and Control Act, also known as the Simpson-Rodino law, even
though jobs are going begging in Northern Mexico.
   ``The undocumented migrants continue entering the United States
as if there never had been a Simpson-Rodino law,'' Jorge
Bustamante, director of the Tijuana-based Northern Border College
and a leading critic of the immigration law, wrote in a recent
newspaper column.
   The law's supporters say its intent is to help the United
States, ``regain control of its borders.''
   U.S. Ambassador Charles Pilliod Jr. said in mid-May, however,
that the ``law was not conceived to eliminate the movement of
Mexican workers to the United States.''
   ``The United States needs these workers _ not only in the farm
area, but also in the many service sectors such as food outlets,
hotels, etc.,'' Pilliod said in a speech to the American Chamber of
Commerce in Mexico City.
   The law gave legal status to aliens who were able to prove they
have lived in the United States at least since 1982. In doing so,
the alients ensured themselves of such rights as a minimum wage,
health care, and education.
   Those who entered the United States after 1982 without legal
documentation remain subject to deportation.
   Pilliod said, however, that predictions of mass deportations are
unfair.
   ``Granted, the Border Patrol will continue to apprehend and
return undocumented aliens to their home countries as always, but
there are no plans for mass roundups,'' he said.
   Bustamante and others contend that the United States cannot
reverse a 40-year trend with a law, because working in the United
States, without documents if necessary, has become part of the
lifestyle of thousands of Mexican families.
   Mexicans who go to work in the United States, even those taking
the most menial jobs, can earn five to 10 times what they earn at
home, where the minimum wage is the equivalent of about $3.45 a day.
   The Northern Border College estimates Mexicans working in the
United States generate about $1 billion in foreign income for
Mexico.
   The Simpson-Rodino law gave illegal aliens who met certain
requirements until May 4 to apply for legal status in the United
States. The majority of the more than 1.6 million people who
applied are Mexican.
   But U.S. immigration officials estimate that half or more of the
6 million to 7 million illegal aliens in the United States are
Mexican.
   And nobody is reporting either a mass exodus or mass
deportations of Mexicans since the May 4 deadline passed.
   ``Just as we predicted, based on investigations we do at the
Northern Border College, nothing extraordinary has happened since
May 5,'' Bustamante wrote in Excelsior of Mexico City.
   Northern Border College offices from Tijuana to Matamoros have
been studying undocumented workers for three years.
   ``For them, the main factor that determines their willingness to
run the risks is the labor market,'' Bustamante wrote. ``As long as
they keep hiring, they will continue entering.''
   A key intent of the Simpson-Rodino law is to stop the hiring of
illegal aliens by U.S. employers.
   In the toughest provision of the law, employers who knowingly
hire undocumented workers can receive stiff fines and other
sanctions. Agricultural employers have until Dec. 1 before
sanctioning begins.
   Meanwhile, the crossings continue.
   ``The majority of those who cross here are farm workers and
they've been given special considerations,'' said Mayor Ernesto
Gomez Lira of Reynosa, south of McAllen, Texas.
   Trejo and Gomez said their city governments have programs to
help returning undocumented migrants find work and housing but so
far the program have not been necessary.
   ``There's a tremendous need for workers in Juarez,'' Trejo said,
referring to the booming foreign-owned assembly operations that
have created a demand for workers.
   ``There's a real war going on. One company offers a 50 percent
discount on cafeteria food and another offers to feed them for
free,'' Trejo said.
   ``We want people to come so they can go to work.''
  
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, June 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
