<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--GoneFishing-III-Rods Adv12   05-31 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Gone Fishing-III-Rods, Adv 12,0804</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv12</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Gone Fishing-III</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>By JOHN KUGLIN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TWIN BRIDGES, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four world-class trout rivers flow
almost by the door of tiny R.L. Winston Rod Co., whose fly rods are
recognized as among the best by hard-core equipment zealots.
   Money is no object for fly fishermen who seek out the Winston
factory in this western Montana ranching town to test cast and
maybe buy a $305 gossamer-tipped graphite wand or a $900 objet
d'art in bamboo.
   ``It's a fact that fishermen sometimes get starry looks when
they first touch one of our rods. It's affection,'' says Tom
Morgan, who bought the established San Francisco rod maker in 1973
and moved it to Montana.
   ``A rod communicates with you,'' Morgan says. ``When you wiggle
a Winston rod it talks back to you with a good message.''
   He implied there's little back talk from a mass-produced rod
retailing for $19.99 in a discount store.
   ``Our goal isn't to provide everyone with a Winston rod, and
everyone can't afford them,'' Morgan says. So the factory makes fly
rods at an artistic snail's pace of about 2,000 a year.
   Morgan doubts his 59-year-old company will ever produce more
than 3,000 rods a year.
   Morgan and the other Winston employees don't blink an eye if an
angler wants to cast half a dozen fly rods on the lawn across the
street, or buy one and substitute zebra wood for the standard
walnut reel seat.
   Morgan, who guided for 14 years and fishes all over the world,
might even accompany an eager angler to one of the nearby
blue-ribbon trout rivers, the Big Hole, Beaverhead, Ruby or
Jefferson.
   He might even rig his favorite Winston, an 8-foot, 4-weight
graphite. ``I like to fish small, dry flies. It's just perfect for
that,'' Morgan said.
   Winston has no fixed working days or hours for its five regular
and seven part-time employees.
   ``If one of the trout streams beckons, they are free to go,''
Morgan says. ``This provides them with the artistic freedom and
inspiration they need to accomplish outstanding work.''
   Winston's graphite rods are considered among the world's best.
They are coated with a translucent kelly-green finish, and guides
are wrapped with matching green thread.
   Winston won't wind a rod with different color thread for a
customer or do anything else that ``makes no aesthetic sense or
technical sense,'' Morgan says.
   There are 89 models of Winston fly rods in 11 line sizes, three
actions, three materials, from 5{ feet to 10 feet long.
   Once an angler buys a basic Winston, there's an enticing array
of accouterments _ maybe a scrimshaw reel seat lovingly carved with
a kingfisher, German silver reel banks, your name engraved on the
rod.
   ``Our average customer has three to five of our rods and I've
talked to people with a dozen,'' Morgan says.
   Almost all of Winston's rods are graphite. The bamboo operation,
supervised by partner Glenn Brackett, may turn out only 75 rods
this year.
   Tonkin cane for the beautifully finished, classic rods comes
from mainland China. Anglers may have to wait four to eight months
for each custom-built rod, whose blemish-free bamboo strips are cut
within a tolerance of one-thousandth of an inch.
   ``Only 5 percent of the bamboo we get goes into our rods,''
Brackett says ``We reject the rest.''
   There are a lot of other good, expensive fly rods on the market
from companies like Sage, Powell, Scott, Teton, Thomas & Thomas, G.
Loomis and Orvis. In fact, Winston's graphite rod blanks are made
on its own tapers by G. Loomis, a larger rod maker.
   Some fly rod companies offer ``futuristic materials,''
``superior tapers,'' ``parabolic action,'' the latest
``breakthrough'' materials. Morgan says a rod's design is more
important than the material. ``It has to work for the type of
fishing you do. At Winston, we don't jump on every new material
that comes along.''
   Morgan says that ``a lot of the people who build fly rods don't
fish enough. You can't make great fly rods if you don't use them a
lot.''
   He himself fishes a great deal, in part because ``you almost
always fish in a place where you can rebuild your spirit. When I'm
steelheading at times I almost wish a fish wouldn't come to my
hook.''
   When it comes to hooking trout, he believes in catching and
releasing them. ``For the marvelous sport they give us,'' he says,
``they deserve our best treatment. You can turn the fish loose, not
like hunting when you kill the animal.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
