<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--GoneFishing-III-Outfits Adv12   05-31 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Gone Fishing-III-Outfits, Adv 12,0579</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv12</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Gone Fishing-III</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Wy. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fly fisherman doesn't have to wear
designer labels or own expensive gear to land the big ones. A trout
with a brain the size of a pea doesn't discriminate between L. L.
Bean and Levi's.
   But serious anglers nearly all agree that collecting gadgets,
perusing catalogs, and spending a snowy winter's day inside a
fishing equipment store is part of the ritual.
   Like one great beauty surreptitiously ogling another's jewels,
fly fishermen check out each other's tackle with discriminating
eyes.
   There's a genteel snobbery in showing up on opening day along
the Beaver Kill River in New York sporting an antique Hiram Leonard
split Tonkin bamboo rod, a Wheatley fly box, a few Irresistibles
tied by Harry or Elsie Darbee, and a faded but much-beloved red
shirt that's survived being stuffed into duffles from Ireland to
New Zealand, and back again by way of Patagonia and Venezuela.
   In spite of sneaking suspicions that fish get spooked by red,
fly fishermen love the color. Big Boy tomato red, American Beauty
red, Fourth of July firecracker red. They wear it in crimson felt
hats crimped at the brim, in scarlet shirts with elaborate flies
embroidered on the pocket, in cherry bandanas tied around sunburned
necks on hot days.
   To many, a splash of red is a talisman.
   ``CHOOSE ME!'' it says to the submerged fish with poor eyesight.
``See my bright hat? My bright suspenders? Of all the men mucking
about in your watery world, I'm the one who will honor you the most.
   ``You, the big one there, if you pick me I will hang you over my
fireplace, display you next to my office bar, maybe just let you go
after I take your picture.''
   Amid the brown, beige and khaki in a fly fisherman's kit bag
there is usually a treasured piece of red.
   But an angler who wants the works will need a lot of green.
   If an emperor with no clothes walked into Jack Dennis' Outdoor
Shop in Jackson, Wyo., and got outfitted in time to be on the Snake
River for lunch, this is what it could cost him:
   _Insulated waders, $100.
   _Leather boots, $85.
   _Boot liner, $30.
   _Fancy shirt, $44.95.
   _Hat (preferably red), $17.
   _Fly fisherman's vest, $60.
   _Graphite fly rod and reel, $80 to $200 and up.
   _Aluminum fly rod case, $40.
   _Leader material, $18 to $32.
   _Floating line, $10 to $30.
   _Clippers, $4.
   _Flies, $1.35 to $2.50 (need at least a dozen).
   _Fly box, $14.
   _Net (for optimists), $14 to $30.
   _Bamboo creel, $40.
   Then there are lessons: Jack Dennis' instructors charge $40 to
teach two people for two hours, while an all-day guided session on
the Snake runs $200 for two, lunch included.
   If the novice fisherman is really hooked, dreams of bonefishing
at Christmas Island begin to dance in his head. That adventure
costs $1,700, not counting air fare to Honolulu.
   Meanwhile, fish are waiting in the Laxa I Laxadalur River in
Iceland, the King Salmon River in Alaska, the Spey, the Dee, and
the Tweed Rivers in Scotland, the Bow River of Canada...
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
