<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   05-31 1019</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,1065</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Academy Award-winning actress Jane Fonda
cornered the home exercise market six years ago with the video
version of her best-selling book, ``Jane Fonda's Workout.'' As of
January, it has made $37.8 million.
   She has seven other exercise videos out, four in the Top 10
selling videocassettes, according to Billboard magazine. All are
released by Lorimar Home Video and have turned flab into fat city
for Fonda and friends.
   Fonda may be the home video exercise empress, but she's not the
only game in town.
   Also in the top selling exercise videos are MCA's
``Callanetics,'' Fox Hills' ``Kathy Smith's Winning Workout'' and
``Kathy Smith's Starting Workout,'' and JCI's ``Kathy Smith's
Ultimate Video Workout.''
   And ``The MS Workout,'' a new video produced by the New York
chapter of the National Multiple Sclerosis Society features
exercises for people with multiple sclerosis and other neurological
problems.
   Led by dancer Wendy Amos and featuring MS victims including
Jimmie Heuga, the video is divided into three sections: a warm-up
of slow neck, back, leg and arm stretches; easy calisthenics; a
slow cool-down to relax the body.
   Some of the participants sit on chairs or stools while they
exercise. A ballet barre is handy for extra support.
   ``The program was designed with the assistance of an advisory
committee which was eager to see to it that the video was sensitive
to the broad spectrum of needs of ambulatory persons with MS and
other neurological diseases, and they selected exercises that
contribute to the improvement of balance and coordination,'' said
Carol Kurzig, executive director of the New York chapter.
   MS is a chronic, often crippling disease of the central nervous
system. Its symptoms can include numbness, sexual dysfunction,
difficulty with coordination, loss of balance and weakness.
   ``The MS Workout'' cost $15 and can be ordered from the New York
MS chapter.
   Fonda exercise tapes are available in most video retail outlets.
According to Lorimar they include ``Start Up With Jane Fonda,''
which was released in March and has sold 781,659 copies; ``Jane
Fonda's Low Impact Aerobic Workout,'' with $23.3 million in sales;
``Jane Fonda's New Workout,'' with $25.2 million in sales; ``Jane
Fonda's Easy Going Workout,'' $11.1 in sales; and ``Jane Fonda's
Workout With Weights,'' ``Jane Fonda's Pregnancy, Birth and
Recovery'' and ``Jane Fonda's Workout Challenge.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Fatal Attraction'' and ``The
Principal.''
   
   ``Fatal Attraction'' (Paramount Home Video; VHS, $89.95; Beat,
$29.95; Rated R)
   
   Consummate yuppie Dan Gallagher has it all: beautiful wife,
adorable daughter, upward mobility, Volvo station wagon. He's not
looking for a one-night stand, but when it presents itself in the
person of sultry publishing exec Alex Forrest, he can't resist.
   How could he know that under those tousled blond locks and
Maybelline eyes lurks the collective anger, frustration and
vengeance of every woman who has ever been done and dumped? Tsk,
tsk, Dan. Should've kept your pants on.
   Played with schizophrenic aplomb by Glenn Close, Alex answers
Dan's rejection with a series of cruel, creepy antics designed to
make your teeth hurt right up to the last second.
   Michael Douglas' Dan elicits little sympathy; there's a distinct
feeling he deserves some of what he's getting. Anne Archer as Dan's
wife is so sweetly unknowing that the audience actually ends up
feeling guilty on behalf of her adulterous, egocentric cad of a
husband.
   Director Adrian ``Flashdance'' Lyne knows how to create and
build tension: no surprise that this slick production was last
year's second-highest grossing movie.
   As the ``R'' rating indicates, there's a little too much sex,
flesh and violence for the kiddies. Otherwise, ``Fatal Attraction''
is a peach of a psychological thriller that could make even the
most dedicated couch potato squirm.
   _ By Lisa Levitt Ryckman, AP National Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Principal'' (RCA@Columbia Home Video; VHS@Beta, $89.95;
Rated R)
   
   In ``The Principal,'' James Belushi plays a Rambo-like high
school teacher who drinks too much, smashes Porsches with baseball
bats and generally ticks off his bosses at the stuffy old board of
education.
   Instead of firing him, they decide to ``reward'' him with a
principalship. Trouble is, it's at Brandel High School, the
low-down dirtiest, most crime-infested, drug-ridden school on the
planet.
   The film misses no opportunity for gratuitous violence. The kids
don't just taunt or ignore him _ they beat him to a bloody pulp.
The teachers are assaulted. And in finest spaghetti Western
fashion, Belushi, riding his motorcycle into the very halls of
Brandel, is going to tame this here school, pard-ner.
   There is a climactic chase scene and showdown in the girl's
shower _ this film's ludicrous version of the OK Corral.
   Even a graduate of Brandel could predict the outcome of this
absurd, boring, exploitative movie.
   And even a better actor than Belushi could have done little with
such pea-brained dialogue as this sample when he tries to inspire
downtrodden teachers:
   ``Aw, come on, you people,'' says he, his voice rising
Patton-like. ``You can't pick and choose your students.''
   The film also features Louis Gossett, Jr., muttering
unintelligible cynicisms as the school's security guard.
   Tough schools lately seem to have caught Hollywood's fancy.
Unfortunately, it is only the rare film, such as the excellent
``Stand and Deliver,'' that manages not to succumb to sexploitation
or racist, blackboard jungle caricatures.
   ``The Principal,'' rated ``R,'' contains the foul,
street-language you'd expect in a film such as this. But not to
worry. The rest of the dialogue will probably put you to sleep.
   _ By Lee Mitgang, AP Education Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
