<DOCNO> AP880531-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-HomeSales     05-31 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Home Sales,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New, Single-Family Home Sales Up 4 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new, single-family homes rose 4
percent in April to the highest level in a year, the government
said today.
   In a joint release, the departments of Commerce and of Housing
and Urban Development said new single-family homes were sold at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of of 679,000 last month, up from
the March pace of 653,000.
   It was the third consecutive monthly increase and the highest
level since new homes were sold at a rate of 728,000 in April 1987.
   Despite the recent increases, sales for the first four months of
this year are still 9 percent below the same period of 1987, when
mortgage interest rates hit nine-year lows.
   The April climb came atop a modest 1.2 percent rise in March and
a whopping 11.4 percent rise in February. However, the increases
followed three consecutive declines _ in November, December and
January _ which analysts at the time said were caused by the
October stock market crash.
   Some economists had feared that the downturn in housing sales
signaled a recession, but since then the economy has proved to be
robust and the housing sector has more than recovered.
   Most analysts, though, believe that sales levels of the last few
months will drop by the fall as rising mortgage interest rates push
up the monthly cost of owning a home and discourage buyers.
   Rates on 30-year, fixed-rate conventional mortgages averaged
10.58 percent last week, more than half a percentage point higher
than levels in February and March.
   The increase in sales of new homes was accompanied by a rise in
prices. The median, or mid-point, price of new homes was $110,500
in April, up 3.3 percent from March. The average price of a new
home rose 4.2 percent in April.
   However, the increases came after two consecutive monthly price
declines, which analysts had said reflected the re-entry into the
market of first-time home buyers, who normally purchase less
expensive homes.
   Sales increased in all regions of the country in April. They
were up 5.9 percent in the Midwest, 5.5 percent in the West, 2.9
percent in the South and 2.8 percent in the Northeast.
   In a separate report last week, the National Association of
Realtors said sales of existing homes increased 4.5 percent in
April after identical increases of 2.5 percent in March and
February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0289 </DOCNO>
