<HEAD>Court Leaves $25 Million Fine Intact for Check' so</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   the summit would be a success, Petrovsky said in remarks quoted by
the news agency Tass.
   ``The American action of this kind is hardly aimed at improving
understanding between the Soviet Union and the United States,'' he
said.
   In Washington six months ago, Gorbachev reacted heatedly when he
was pressed by newspaper editors on his stand on human rights.
Soviet officials have long told Americans to mind their own
business on the issue.
   Reagan and his wife, Nancy, signed autographs during the session
at which a few children roamed around the large dining room.
   ``We are not so used to hearing such human words without any
political statement,'' said Yuri Zieman, a former computer
scientist who lost his job when he applied for an exit visa 11
years ago.
   Zieman said there was no telling whether the session with Reagan
would expedite emigration. ``How do we know?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
