   The pace of trading has been slow in recent weeks as traders
have demonstrated little conviction about the implications of
continuing strength in the economy.
   While a strong economy could bode well for corporate profits,
some observers worry that an expanding economy could also reignite
inflation.
   Larry Wachtel, a vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., said today's advance may reflect some relief that the Federal
Reserve failed to boost its discount rate after the markets closed
last week, as some traders had feared. The discount rate is the
central bank's charge on loans to financial institutions.
   Wachtel said stock prices were also helped by relative stability
in the bond market.
