<HEAD>Soybeans Open Limit Up; Grains Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices rocketed up the
30-cents-a-bushel limit for daily trading today on the Chicago
Board of Trade following a long, hot, dry weekend in the Midwest.
Grain futures also opened higher.
   ``It's all based on the weather,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader for the investment firm Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``It was
dry over the weekend and there's not much rain in the forecast.''
   Soybean prices came down slightly from their opening highs as
traders took profits. But with meteorologists predicting little
precipitation in the Corn Belt until later this week, prices were
expected to continue at four-year highs.
   As soybean planting approaching completion, fears are
intensifying that a dry summer could lead to tight supplies next
year, analysts said.
   Most soybean contracts were trading this morning above $8 a
bushel, a price not seen since the spring of 1984.
   In early trading, wheat was 11 cents to 13 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.50{ a bushel; corn was 8 cents
to 9{ cents higher with July at $2.24{ a bushel; soybeans were 6\
cents to 6} cents higher with July at $1.79{ a bushel; soybeans
were 7 cents to 30 cents higher with July at $7.97 cents a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were substantially
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .13 cent to .65 cent higher with June at 72.05
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .22 cent lower with
August at 76 cents a pound; hogs were .30 cent to .95 cent higher
with June at 54.35 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .70 cent
to 1.38 cent higher with July at 55.70 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled lower on Friday while pork futures
advanced.
</TEXT>
