<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0462</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock traders came back from the three-day
Memorial holiday weekend in a good mood, pushing prices broadly
higher in active dealings today. Analysts said the market was
cheered by the ability of the bond market to shrug off a rise in
commodity prices today.
   Volume was strong, but more than half of the shares traded on
the New York Stock Exchange involved the stocks of two utility
companies whose dividend eligibility dates are approaching.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which fell 10.31
points on Friday, was up 25.25 at 1,981.69 at noon on Wall Street.
   Gainers outpaced losers by a margin of more than 2 to 1 among
issues traded on the NYSE, with 895 up, 366 down and 468 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 157.37 million shares as of noontime,
compared with 88.35 million shares at the same point in Friday's
session.
   The pace of trading has been slow in recent weeks as traders
have demonstrated little conviction about the implications of
continuing strength in the economy.
   While a strong economy could bode well for corporate profits,
some observers worry that an expanding economy could also reignite
inflation.
   Charles Jensen, a technical analyst for MKI Securities Corp.,
said the Commodity Research Bureau's index of selected commodity
prices was up about 5 points at midday, a relatively strong advance
that might normally stir inflation fears.
   But he said when the bond market declined only slightly, traders
who had sold borrowed stocks in anticipation that they could buy
them later at lower prices ``panicked and bought stocks.''
   ``Some people saw that as a good sign _ that the market failed
to respond to bad news,'' he said.
   Eldon A. Grimm, a senior vice president at the brokerage Birr,
Wilson Securities Inc., said there is ``an enormous amount of cash
around out of the market'' due to wariness in the wake of last
October's crash.
   ``But every time we get a little rally going, people think they
will miss the boat and buy something,'' he said.
   More than half of the early activity today was in two stocks.
Ohio Edison was unchanged at 18| on volume of 55.2 million shares,
while Public Service Enterprise Group was up | at 23| on volume of
36.4 million shares.
   Also on the NYSE active list, Union Carbide was up \ at 19\,
Citicorp was up ] at 23\ and General Electric was up ~ at 40~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 1.37 at 145.03. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite
index was up 1.83 at 292.33.
</TEXT>
