<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0435</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pushed vigorously ahead today,
as traders appeared to take a more optimistic view of interest rate
prospects.
   Volume was strong as traders returned from a three-day holiday
weekend, but about half of it involved the stocks of two utility
companies whose dividend eligibility dates are approaching.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which fell 10.31
points on Friday, was up 35.56 at 1,992.00 with two hours left in
the session.
   Gainers outpaced losers by a margin of 5 to 2 among issues
traded on the New York Stock Exchange, with 980 up, 403 down and
464 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 183.21 million shares as of 2 p.m. on
Wall Street.
   The pace of trading has been slow in recent weeks as traders
have demonstrated little conviction about the implications of
continuing strength in the economy.
   While a strong economy could bode well for corporate profits,
some investors worry that an expanding economy could also reignite
inflation.
   But some analysts said traders were cheered by the Federal
Reserve's failure to raise its discount rate _ the interest it
charges on loans to financial institutions _ last week after the
market closed for the holiday.
   They said foreign traders led a surge of buying as trading
resumed today, and the market drifted even higher this afternoon.
   The analysts said the market's performance was remarkable in
view of a rise in commodity prices, which might normally stir
inflation fears.
   Jack Baker, head of block trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc., said a spate of buying in utility stocks may also signal that
some investors feel the market ``may be closer to a top in interest
rates than we are to another extension of rates or a round of
interest rate hikes.''
   About half of the activity today was in two stocks. Ohio Edison
was unchanged at 18| on volume of 55.4 million shares, while Public
Service Enterprise Group was up | at 23| on volume of 36.4 million
shares.
   Macmillan fell 1\ to 71\ after proposing to split its
information services and publishing interests into separate
companies and pay a special dividend.
   Essex Chemical rose 10 to 27[ after receiving an offer of $24 a
share for 61 percent of its stock from a Eyuroepan firm.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 1.88 at 145.54. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite
index rose 1.92 to 292.42.
