<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WeeklySteel     05-31 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Rose 0.5 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production rose to 2.019 million tons in
the week ended May 28, an increase of 0.5 percent from the previous
week's 2.009 million tons, the American Iron and Steel Institute
reported Tuesday.
   The industry's production amounted to 94.2 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 94.2 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
41.569 million net tons, a rise of 24.7 percent from the 33.343
million net tons in the previous year.
   Production so far this year used 91.0 percent of capacity,
compared with 73.2 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended May 28: Northeast
Coast, 278,000; Pittsburgh, 206,000; Youngstown, 118,000; Lake
Erie, 170,000; Detroit, 170,000; Chicago, 560,000; Midwest,
194,000; Southern, 222,000; and Western, 101,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1528EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-31 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Close Up Daily Limit; Weather Outlook Remains Dry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices soared the
30-cents-a-bushel limit allowed for daily trading Tuesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade in response to the Midwest's hot, dry
weekend and predictions for more of the same.
   Grain futures also closed sharply higher.
   ``Weather's the story, that's the whole ball game,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago
   As soybean planting nears completion, fears are intensifying
that a drier-than-normal summer could lead to tight supplies next
year, analysts said. The spring planting season has been unusually
dry.
   Wheat, corn and oat crops also would suffer during a summer of
little rain, but the rapid depletion of soybean stockpiles has made
that market particularly sensitive to growing conditions.
   Tuesday's gains brought the near-month soybean contract, for
delivery in July, to within easy striking range of $8 a bushel for
the first time since the spring of 1984.
   Eight of the nine soybean contracts were up the limit, as was
the contract for March 1989 delivery of corn, which carries a
10-cents-a-bushel limit. Some oat futures traded up their 10-cent
limit during the session but closed below those highs.
   At the close, wheat was 9{ cents to 15{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.51 a bushel; corn was 7} cents
to 10 cents higher with July at $2.24{ a bushel; oats were 9\ cents
to 9} cents higher with July at $1.82\ a bushel; soybeans were 18
cents to 30 cents higher with July at $7.98 a bushel.
</TEXT>
