<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USAir     05-31 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USAir,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USAir Reports Cancellations Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir's schedules were disrupted again Tuesday
as some flight attendants continued to refuse to work overtime in
apparent protest of an impasse in contract negotiations.
   The airline, based in Arlington, Va., canceled 24 flights in its
first eight hours of operation Tuesday, said spokesman Dave Shipley.
   ``It's a very, very small percentage of the total,'' Shipley
said. ``There's not chaos at the airports.''
   USAir schedules about 1,600 flights daily, Shipley said.
   He said USAir canceled one flight Saturday, 81 flights Sunday
and 61 flights Monday.
   An impasse in contract negotiations between USAir and the
Association of Flight Attendants apparently prompted the airline's
flight attendants to decline overtime.
   USAir has yet to complete an agreement for a new contract and
seniority list with its flight attendants and those employed by
Pacific Southwest Airlines, which was acquired by USAir last year
and merged into USAir's system April 9.
   ``Apparently there is (a protest), but it's not a
union-organized protest. I think it's a spontaneous protest. I was
as surprised as anyone else,'' said Juliette Lenoir, vice president
of the Washington, D.C.-based union and a USAir flight attendant.
   ``My best sense is that flight attendants are just very upset at
this whole issue of pay parity for the former PSA flight
attendants. That may have been the straw that broke the camel's
back,'' she said.
   Ms. Lenoir said USAir also has been asking attendants to do more
work, such as serving travelers before takeoff, without a raise in
pay since at least 1985.
   Shipley said most passengers booked for the canceled flights
were accommodated on USAir flights or on other airlines. He said
two classes of about 40 new flight attendants each were assigned to
flights to help.
   Shipley said flight attendants' overtime is governed by federal
regulations which limit them to 85 hours per month. He said flight
attendants may fly five extra hours per month as overtime at the
request of airlines, but they are not required to do so.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
