<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     05-31 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0249</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted one of its strongest
advances of the year today as traders went on a post-Memorial
holiday buying spree.
   Analysts said there was no single piece of economic news to
account for the surge, but said traders appeared to be betting that
interest rates are approaching a peak for the time being.
   The pace of trading has been slow in recent weeks as traders
have demonstrated little conviction about the implications of
continuing strength in the economy.
   While a strong economy could bode well for corporate profits,
some investors worried that an expanding economy could also
reignite inflation.
   But analysts said the market was heartened that the Federal
Reserve had failed to raise its discount rate _ the interest on its
loans to financial institutions _ last week after the markets had
closed.
   Some of the buying in today's session, they said, came from
traders who had speculated that the Fed would push interest rates
yet higher and had sold borrowed stocks last week in anticipation
that they could buy them back later at cheaper prices.
   Once stock prices began rising today, analysts said some of
these traders bought stocks to cover those positions and other
investors climbed aboard.
   The analysts said the market's performance was remarkable in
view of a rise in commodity futures prices, which might normally
stir inflation fears.
</TEXT>
