<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NewspageStocks 1stLd-Writethru   05-31 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspage Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Turns in One of Year's Best Days</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to add dropped word `rate' to make it `interest
rates.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices shot up Tuesday in a post-holiday
weekend buying spree that pushed up the Dow Jones industrial
average nearly 75 points.
   Analysts could not point to any specific developments to account
for the rally, but they said sentiment seemed to have grown that
interest rates are near a peak for the time being. Anxiety over
rising interest rates had weighed heavily on the market in recent
weeks.
   Prices began rising as soon as trading resumed after the
three-day break for the Memorial Day holiday and gathered momentum
as the day wore on.
   The Dow industrials rose 74.68 points to close at 2,031.12. That
was the widely followed barometer's best gain since a 76.42 rise on
Jan. 4 and the sixth biggest increase ever.
   Four stocks rose in price for every one that fell on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   The pace of trading has slowed in recent weeks as investors have
shown little conviction on the implications of continuing strength
in the economy. While a strong economy could be a boon for
corporate profits, some investors have worried that the expanding
economy could also reignite inflation.
   But analysts said Tuesday that traders were heartened the
Federal Reserve had not increased the interest rate it charges on
loans to financial institutions. There had been speculation it
would do so after the markets closed Friday.
</TEXT>
