<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BankProbe     05-31 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Probe,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank of Boston Probes Corporate Trust Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bank of Boston said Tuesday it has suspended
three employees and launched an investigation of record-keeping in
its corporate trusts division.
   Bank spokesman Wayne Taylor said the investigation began about
two weeks ago after a new management team took over the division,
which administers interests payments for corporate and municipal
bonds.
   ``To preserve the independence of that review, the bank last
week suspended three members of the corporate trust division
management team,'' Taylor said.
   Taylor said new managers in the division noticed problems in
bookkeeping when they took over recently. However, he said, there
was no evidence of impropriety or wrongdoing.
   Taylor said the Securities and Exchange Commission, the Federal
Reserve and the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency have been
notified of the review, which is looking into the accuracy of
account information and other operations in the division.
   He said the review is expected to take several weeks.
   The three employees, who were suspended without pay for two
weeks, were not identified.
   The probe is being conducted by members of the bank staff and
its auditing firm, Cooper and Lybrand of Boston.
   The Bank of Boston, which owns banks in Massachusetts, Maine,
Rhode Island and Connecticut, reported first quarter assets in
excess of $33 billion.
</TEXT>
