<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-31 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar's Strength Builds, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened in foreign exchange
trading Tuesday amid a rally on Wall Street and speculation by
investors that interest rates were approaching a short-term peak.
   Gold prices also rose. Republic National Bank said gold bullion
was bid at $454.30 a troy ounce at 4 p.m. EDT, up from $451 late
Friday.
   Traders in the currency markets, returning from a long weekend,
said the dollar was drawing its strength from firm interest rates
in the credit markets. Although rumors of an imminent move to
tighten credit by the Federal Reserve did not materialize, traders
remained encouraged by the U.S. interest rate environment.
   The federal funds rate, representing the charge for overnight
loans between banks, traded at 7| percent, up from 7\ late Friday.
   ``The general sense of the market is that while interest rates
are firm, the dollar will put in a better performance,'' said James
T. McGroarty, a vice president with Discount Corp.
   The dollar proved resilient enough to withstand an early move by
the West German central bank to sell dollars to keep it in line
with other currencies, traders noted. The Bundesbank sold $7.4
million as the dollar moved above the psychologically important
level of 1.72 West German marks.
   Some investors had been counting on the Fed to push interest
rates higher at the end of last week by raising its discount loan
rate to member banks. When that didn't happen after the close of
the financial markets Friday, some traders became convinced
interest rates might be peaking. The result was a post-Memorial Day
rally in stock prices and the dollar.
   The moves were unusual, traders said, because they came against
a backdrop of rising commodity prices, including gold, and a drop
in the yield of long-term government bonds.
   The dollar closed in Tokyo at 124.80 Japanese yen, down from
Monday's 124.98 yen. In later London trading it rose to 125.50 yen,
and in New York, it was quoted at 125.235 yen, up from 124.925 late
Friday.
   The dollar also gained against the British pound in London,
where it was quoted late Tuesday at $1.8385, compared with $1.8478
in Europe on Monday and $1.8570 in London late Friday. London
financial markets also were closed Monday for a national holiday.
   In New York, the pound fetched $1.8353 Tuesday, compared with
$1.85735 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday,
included: 1.73265 West German marks, up from 1.7178; 1.44525 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4358; 5.8300 French francs, up from 5.7770;
1,284.00 Italian lire, up from 1,273.13; and 1.2333 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.23915.
   Late dollar rates in London, compared with late Monday's rates,
included: 1.7292 West German marks, up from 1.7270; 1.4437 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4415; 5.8215 French francs, up from 5.8025;
1.9333 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9335; 1,279.95 Italian lire,
down from 1,280.00; and 1.2357 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2378.
   Gold prices around the world got a boost from big gains in the
platinum market. The late bid price in London was $454.80 a troy
ounce, up from late Friday's $452. In Zurich, gold closed at a bid
$455, up from late Monday's $452.50.
   Earlier, gold closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $455.80, up from
$454.31.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold bullion for current
delivery was quoted at $455 a troy ounce, up from $450.80 late
Friday.
   Silver bullion traded in London late Monday at a bid $6.65 a
troy ounce, up from $6.59 in London late Friday and $6.57 in Zurich
on Monday.
   On the Comex, silver bullion for current delivery was quoted at
$6.600 a troy ounce, up from $6.530 late Friday.
</TEXT>
