<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   05-31 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0823</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Rally in Big Post-Holiday Gain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock traders celebrated their return from the
three-day Memorial holiday on Tuesday with a buying spree that
pushed the Dow Jones industrial average to its second biggest gain
of the year.
   Analysts said there was no single piece of news to account for
the surge, which came on the heaviest daily volume since late
January, but they said the market's pessimism had grown so
pervasive that a rebound was inevitable.
   ``Sometimes it's better just to enjoy and not analyze things
like this,'' said John L. Manley Jr., a portfolio strategist for
Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. ``It's been a bad May.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell 10.31 points
last Friday, climbed 74.68 to 2,031.12, its highest level since it
closed at 2,036.31 on May 4.
   It was the biggest one-day advance in the market's most
widely-followed index since a 76.42-point gain on Jan. 4, the first
trading day of the year, and the sixth biggest rise ever.
   The gain in the Dow Jones industrials was so strong that a
voluntary limit on computerized program trading was triggered when
the Dow's rise swept past 50 points in the last hour of trading.
   But even after the so-called ``collar'' went into effect for the
rest of the day, the blue-chip average extended its gain. It was
the third time the collar had gone into effect since it was adopted
in the aftermath of the Oct. 19 market crash in a bid to curb
market volatility.
   Gainers outpaced losers by nearly 4 to 1 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 1,211 up, 333 down
and 401 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 247.61 million shares,
up from 133.59 million in the previous session and the highest
since 275.25 million shares were traded there on Jan. 25.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market,
totaled 271.55 million shares.
   The pace of trading has been slow in recent weeks as traders
weighed the implications of continuing strength in the economy.
While a strong economy could bode well for corporate profits, some
investors worried that an expanding economy could also reignite
inflation.
   While analysts were unable to pinpoint why the market surged
Tuesday, they said several factors may have contributed to the big
gain.
   They cited stability in the dollar and the bond market's
resilience in the face of a new surge in commodity futures prices.
   They also cited relief that the Federal Reserve Board had failed
to boost its discount rate _ its interest charge on loans to
financial institutions _ as some feared it would after the markets
closed last week.
   Eldon A. Grimm, a senior vice president at the brokerage Birr,
Wilson Securities Inc., said there is ``an enormous amount of cash
around out of the market'' due to wariness in the wake of last
October's crash.
   ``But every time we get a little rally going, people think they
will miss the boat and buy something,'' he said.
   Peter DaPuzzo, manager of retail equity trading for Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc., said the warm weather over the holiday may have
prompted investors to reevaluate the market's prospects and put
some cash to work.
   ``You've got to start a summer rally sometime, and Memorial Day
is usually the threshold to the summer,'' he said.
   Two utility stocks that have a deadline soon for dividend
eligibility accounted for more than a third of the trading activity
on the NYSE.
   Ohio Edison was up [ at 18} on volume of 55.7 million shares,
while Public Service Enterprise Group rose ~ to 23~ on volume of
36.8 million shares.
   Among the blue chip issues, American Telephone & Telegraph rose
1[ to 27[, General Electric rose 2 to 42, International Business
Machines rose 4{ to 112{ and Eastman Kodak rose 1{ to 42.
   Macmillan fell 2\ to 70\ after proposing to spin off its
information services company and pay a special dividend to its
shareholders.
   Essex Chemical rose 10} to 27~ after receiving an offer of $24 a
share for 61 percent of its stock from a unit of Gurit-Heberlein AG.
   According to Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively-traded stocks, the market rose $69.66 billion, or 2.75
percent, in value.
   The NYSE index rose 4.38 to 148.04.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 10.12 to 302.67, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 8.74 at 262.16.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 3.69
to 294.19. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 370.34, up 3.68.
</TEXT>
