<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1823EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Boeing-737Incidents     05-31 0821</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing-737 Incidents,0845</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Similarities Between Far Eastern, Aloha Planes Only Coincidence,
Boeing Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT cycle designator.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is only coincidence that a Taiwanese Boeing
737 that disintegrated and crashed in 1981 and an Aloha Airlines
737 that lost part of its fuselage over Hawaii in April were built
one after the other, Boeing officials said Tuesday.
   On April 28, a 20-foot section of the Aloha jet's forward upper
fuselage ripped away at 24,000 feet. A flight attendant fell to her
death and 61 passengers were injured, but the flight crew landed
the plane safely.
   The Aloha plane was the 152nd 737-200 produced by Boeing. Plane
No. 151 was a Far Eastern Air Transport jet that disintegrated and
exploded at 22,000 feet over central Taiwan on Aug. 22, 1981,
killing all 110 people on board.
   The cause of the Aloha accident is still under investigation.
However, the Federal Aviation Administration has ordered U.S.
airlines flying older 737s to reinspect the aircraft.
   Boeing believes the Far Eastern crash was caused by maintenance
problems, spokesman Jack Gamble of Boeing Commercial Airplanes
said. Any similarities between that crash and the Aloha accident
are ``a series of coincidences,'' Gamble said.
   At the time of the planes' manufacture in 1969, Boeing was
turning out between two and three 737s a month, Gamble said. He
said he knew of no other problems involving 737s made around that
time.
   In an article Tuesday in the Wall Street Journal, Benjamin
Cosgrove, Boeing Commercial Airplanes vice president and general
manager for engineering, also said the consecutive aircraft numbers
were coincidence. Cosgrove said that while both accidents involved
a section of the fuselage that Boeing refers to as ``Section 43,''
there was nothing inherently wrong with that portion of the
aircraft.
   Cosgrove told the Journal the Far Eastern 737 repeatedly was
used to ship fish in open containers, and corrosive salt water may
have gotten into the cargo hold. The newspaper said Far Eastern
officials denied that charge and said fish were shipped only in
non-leaking containers.
   National Transportation Safety Board spokesman Michael Benson in
Washington, D.C., said Tuesday NTSB investigators also believe
leaking salt water from fish shipments was the cause of the Far
Eastern jet's corrosion.
   Gamble said Boeing had issued a series of service bulletins on
older 737s, including one in March 1978 recommending aircraft
owners make additional inspections of fuselage skins for possible
corrosion. On July 1, 1981, the FAA issued an airworthiness
directive requiring U.S. carriers to inspect older 737s.
   Boeing had supplied kits to airlines to allow them to replace
corroded skin on planes, Gamble said.
   A kit was delivered to Far Eastern in April 1980, ``which means
they had those in their spare parts inventory considerably before
that crash,'' but apparently was never used on the plane, he said.
   Cosgrove was in Washington, D.C., to attend a conference on
problems with aging aircraft and was not available for comment
Tuesday, Gamble said. The three-day conference was called by the
FAA after the Aloha incident to study safety issues involving older
aircraft.
   T. Craig Martin, director of public relations for Boeing
Commercial Airplanes, noted the FAA also issued an airworthiness
directive following the Far Eastern crash requiring inspections of
737 cargo holds.
   Milton Goto, spokesman for Aloha Airlines, said that as a result
of the directive, Aloha made extensive repairs in 1983 to the 737
subsequently involved in the April incident. He said the work done
on the wings and lower portion of the plane might have helped it
stay together long enough to land.
   The twin-engine 737, which entered service in 1968, is the
world's most popular commercial aircraft, with more than 2,000
ordered in five different models.
   One of the FAA airworthiness directives issued after the Aloha
accident focuses on early models of 737s in which Boeing used a
cold-bonding process, in which structural parts of the fuselage
were laminated together using an adhesive that cured at room
temperature.
   Martin said he found a number of differences between the two
accidents. The Far Eastern plane, for example, was 12 years old and
had approximately 33,000 landings, while the Aloha jet was 20 years
old and had about 90,000 landings.
   ``As best we know,'' the Far Eastern accident was caused by
corrosion in the plane's cargo hold, while the Aloha accident
involved the top of the plane, he said.
   ``But again, the appropriate thing is to see what the NTSB and
the FAA conclude before drawing all these analogies and
comparisons,'' Martin said.
   Martin said Boeing issues service bulletins on its aircraft to
customers whenever it learns of a problem or the potential for one.
The FAA and other appropriate regulatory agencies also are
notified, he said.
   He said the NTSB believes the issues presented in the Far
Eastern case ``were known and addressed and adequately so'' by the
FAA airworthiness directive.
</TEXT>
