<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-FreddieMac     05-31 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Freddie Mac,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freddie Mac Announces Big Jump in Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. said
Tuesday that earnings rose 50 percent to a record $93 million in
the first three months of this year.
   The corporation, known as Freddie Mac, buys mortgages and
repackages them into securities for sales to investors. Corporation
officials attributed the earnings increase to a widening in the
difference between what it pays to the investors and what it
receives from the mortgages.
   Also, income taxes were reported at a lower rate because of a
drop in the corporate tax rate.
   For the first quarter, net income was $93 million, or $5.65 per
share of preferred stock and $83.06 per share of common stock, up
from $62 billion, or $3.81 per share of preferred stock and $52.31
per share of common stock, for the same period in 1987.
   Freddie Mac was created by Congress in 1970 to increase the
amount of money available for mortgages. Its preferred stock is
owned by 3,000 savings institutions who are members of the 12
Federal Home Loan Banks. Its common stock is owned by the home loan
banks.
</TEXT>
