<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Delta-YoungFlyers     05-31 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta-Young Flyers,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta Expands Youth Flyers, Inaugurates Program For Kids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines is going after kiddie flyers,
announcing Tuesday an expanded youth fare program for the summer to
go along with a previously announced prize program for children to
fly along with ``Delta Air Lion.''
   The reduced fare will be in effect systemwide, Delta said, more
than doubling the number of markets in which the fare is available.
Delta already had matched youth fares announced May 16 by Eastern,
Continental and United airlines in areas where it competed with the
three.
   Delta, the nation's fourth largest airline, said the youth fares
and a ``Fantastic Flyer'' program take effect Wednesday.
   The fares give children ages 2 through 17 who travel through
Sept. 11 a special price when accompanied by adults who have
purchased a non-refundable fare. One child may accompany each
adult, following the same advance purchase and minimum stay rules
in force with the adult's fare.
   The airline, which already has a marketing tie-in with Walt
Disney World near Orlan, Fla., expects most of the fares to include
Florida. For example, round-trip fares from cities east of the
Mississippi River to Florida will be $97 on weekends and $77 for
midweek travel.
   For travel from cities west of the Mississippi to Florida, or
between two cities outside the state of Florida, the fares will be
limited to midweek and are based of a mileage formula ranging from
$58 to $198.
   Under the Fantastic Flyer program announced last week, Delta
will give prizes and other rewards to children between 2 and 12
years old.
   Calling Delta ``The Official Airline for Kids,'' Delta senior
vice president Whit Hawkins said, ``On every Delta flight, children
will receive a complimentary Mickey Mouse visor ... a copy of the
Fantastic Flyer Magazine featuring games, puzzles, stories and
prizes created just for them.''
   Delta spokesman Jim Lundy said the airline is after two groups
of travelers, with its lower fares and Fantastic Flyer gambits:
vacationers making trips with their children and unaccompanied
children.
</TEXT>
