<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Allied-Federated     05-31 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allied-Federated,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allied-Federated Appoints Top Two Executives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two veteran executives with Federated
Department Stores Inc. have been hired to head the combined
operations of Federated and Allied Stores, Campeau Corp. announced
Tuesday.
   John W. Burden III will serve as chairman and chief executive
officer of Federated and Allied and James M. Zimmerman as president
and chief operating officer, Campeau chairman Robert Campeau said
in a statement.
   Allied and Federated will be run as one operation, but it is not
yet known if the assets of the two will be merged after Campeau
completes his acquisition of Federated.
   The operations and top Allied-Federated executives will be based
in Cincinnati, company spokeswoman Carol Sanger said.
   Robert Campeau has served as chairman of Allied and Federated
since his company acquired control of Federated in early May as the
result of a $6.6 billion buyout. Campeau now becomes chairman of
the combined corporation's executive committee, the company
announced.
   Campeau Corp. bought Allied Stores Corp. in December 1986.
   Burden, 51, formerly served as a vice chairman of Federated, a
position he held from February 1985 until recently resigning with
other top Federated executives when Campeau took control. Burden
was elected to Federated's board of directors in July 1985.
   Zimmerman, 44, has served as chairman of Federated's
Atlanta-based Rich's department store division since January 1984.
Prior to that, he was president of the division since March 1980.
   Burden's appointment fills the vacancy created when veteran
retail executive Robert Morosky resigned, four days after Campeau
took control of Federated. Morosky reportedly resigned over
differences he had with Campeau.
</TEXT>
