<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Texaco-Icahn     05-31 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texaco-Icahn,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Icahn Charges Texaco Managers `Blundered'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Carl C. Icahn, whose bid for Texaco
Inc. was rejected last week, on Tuesday charged the oil giant
``engaged in a continuing series of damaging managerial blunders.''
   In an amended counterclaim in response to a lawsuit filed by
Texaco, Icahn contends Texaco ``deliberately concealed information
(and) made false and misleading statements to its stockholders.''
   Texaco said in a statement from its White Plains, N.Y.,
headquarters that the counterclaim was ``utterly groundless.'' The
company said it would respond in detail through the normal
litigation process.
   Icahn, who offered to acquire Texaco for $60 a share in a bid
that values the company at $14.6 billion, complained that the
company did not tell shareholders it offered him greenmail, which
he has said he rejected. He also charged that Texaco condoned the
misuse of corporate assets in a California real estate venture.
   Icahn said Texaco approached him with a third-party buyer
willing to pay $50 a share for his stake in the oil giant, and said
he rejected the offer because it ``smacked of greenmail.''
   In the original counterclaim, Icahn and his affiliates claimed
that Texaco and four directors made misleading statements in proxy
material distributed to shareholders.
   The counterclaim charges the acts are ``part of a management
scheme to entrench itself to the detriment of the stockholders.''
   Icahn has launched his own proxy fight in an attempt to win five
seats on Texaco's board of directors and has extended his tender
offer until Texaco's annual meeting on June 17.
   Texaco President and Chief Executive Officer James Kinnear, who
is cited in Icahn's counterclaim along with three others, has been
skeptical of Icahn's ability to finance the buyout.
   As Texaco's largest shareholder, Icahn controls 14.8 percent of
the oil giant's outstanding shares.
</TEXT>
