<DOCNO> AP880531-0320 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DeficitCommission     05-31 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deficit Commission,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commission Hears Recommendations On Congressional Budget Process</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The complex procedures by which Congress
approves spending and tax plans are badly in need of reform
including adoption of a two-year budget cycle, witnesses told a
national commission Tuesday.
   The National Economic Commission, created by Congress to
recommend ways to solve the government's budget woes, heard a
variety of recommendations ranging from decreasing the number of
congressional committees involved in budget writing to giving the
president authority to refuse to spend money appropriated by
Congress.
   But all of the witnesses cautioned the commission against
spending too much time looking into the budget process, saying this
was not the main flaw which has led to record federal deficits
during the Reagan years.
   ``Creation of the deficit was the result of a series of policy
mistakes and miscalculations, both economic and political, that
process changes probably would not have prevented,'' said Alice
Rivlin, former head of the Congressional Budget Office.
   ``Fixing the deficit requires having the political courage to
face up to the problem and agree on a package of spending cuts
and-or tax increases that will correct it,'' she said.
   The 12-member commission, headed by Washington attorney Robert
Strauss and former Transportation Secretary Drew Lewis, was holding
its second public hearing with a goal of coming up with a set of
recommendations for the new president and Congress by Dec. 21.
   The witnesses Tuesday all recommended switching from the current
annual budgets, which have tied up Congress in unending debate, to
a two-year budget cycle.
   ``A two-year budget approved in the first year of each
congressional term would substantially reduce the current burden of
preparing and approving budgets in both the administration and
Congress,'' said William Niskanen, former member of President
Reagan's Council of Economic Advisers.
   Niskanen also suggested that Congress had gone too far in
restricting presidential power when it passed the Impoundment
Control Act of 1974. That law prevented President Nixon and his
successors from simply refusing to spend money appropriated by
Congress. Any such ``impoundment'' of funds would have to be
specifically approved by a positive vote in both the House and the
Senate.
   ``In effect, appropriations are now both a ceiling and a floor
on spending and there is no way to run a complex organization under
these constraints,'' Niskanen said. ``The restrictions on
impoundment authority should be recognized as an overreaction to
the abuses of presidential authority during the Watergate era.''
   Stephen Bell, former executive director of the Senate Budget
Committee, said he believed the government would have a
``substantially smaller deficit'' currently if the president still
had authority to refuse to spend appropriated money.
   Bell said that any reforms should seek to make the process more
understandable to the general public.
   ``The present process has descended into almost a cult of
mysteries, reminiscent of the pagan cults of 2,000 years ago,'' he
said. ``We need to change that so that more Americans can
participate intelligently in this critical debate on fiscal policy
and national priorities.''
   Bell recommended combining many of the budgeting functions now
shared by numerous congressional committees, restricting the types
of amendments that can be offered to budget bills in the Senate and
giving the president the ability to veto individual items in a
spending bill, a proposal long sought by President Reagan.
   Ms. Rivlin suggested that the administration should consider
consolidating its own budget functions now scattered between the
Office of Management and Budget, the Treasury Department and the
Council of Economic Advisers into a single Cabinet agency
responsible to the president for overall economic policy-making.
   ``The creaky, over-burdened budget process badly needs
simplification,'' Ms. Rivlin said. ``The commission could do a
major national service by emphasizing this fact and pointing the
parties in a constructive direction.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0321 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 2210EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HuntBrothers     05-31 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hunt Brothers,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nelson Bunker Hunt Tells His Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nelson Bunker Hunt testified Tuesday that
inflation and world political events _ and not a plot by him and
his brothers to corner the world silver market _ led prices to
rocket in the late 1970s.
   In his first day of testimony in a multi-million dollar civil
trial at federal court, Hunt essentially repeated assertions made
by defense lawyers in their opening statements last February.
   Hunt, 62, his brothers William Herbert Hunt, 58, and Lamar Hunt,
55, are being sued by a South American silver concern that claims
the Dallas, Tex. brothers conspired to corner the world silver
market between September 1979 and January 1980.
   Lawyers for Minpeco SA, a mineral marketing company owned by the
Peruvian government, claim the Hunts and several co-defendants were
responsible for the sharp rise in silver prices from about $9 an
ounce to more than $50 an ounce.
   Minpeco claims the skyrocketing prices caused it to lose more
than $100 million when the world silver market collapsed in March
1980, with prices falling back to about $10 an ounce.
   But the rotund elder Hunt brother claimed he began investing in
silver bullion and silver futures because of ``continuing inflation
and certain political events.''
   Hunt, who said he began investing in silver in 1973, said that
by the fall of 1979 he was still telling people that ``silver was
an overall good investment.''
   But 1979 was ``a very unsettling year politically,'' said Hunt,
in a low Texas drawl, noting the Iranian revolution that ousted the
shah and took American diplomats hostage in Teheran; a continuing
increase in oil prices; the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan and the
seizure of the Grand Mosque at Mecca by Islamic radicals.
   Hunt, whose legendary father, H.L. Hunt, made the family fortune
in oil, said as oil prices began climbing _ to about $30 a barrel
in late 1979 _ he bought more and more silver.
   But he claimed new commodity exchange rules limiting the number
of futures contracts that could be held as well as increasing the
amount to be put down on margin accounts ``was a difficult thing
for the market.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
