<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Producers, Writers Meet to Settle 12-Week Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with talks ending for day with
no agreement. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``The talks...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking scriptwriters and television and
film producers failed to reach an agreement Tuesday to end the
11-week work stoppage that has shut down most Hollywood production,
but they agreed to meet again Wednesday.
   A negotiating session with a federal mediator present began at 9
a.m. and ended shortly before 7:30 p.m., said to Cheryl Rhoden, a
spokeswoman for the 9,000-member Writers Guild of America.
   Ms. Rhoden declined to characterize the session.
   ``We had sidebar sessions and caucuses, but there was no full
committee negotiations _ although everyone was present,'' Ms.
Rhoden said. The WGA spokeswoman had said earlier that full
committee bargaining had been expected to begin Tuesday afternoon.
Both sides agreed to resume their meeting at 3 p.m. Wednesday.
   Ms. Rhoden added that picketing in the strike that opened March
7 would resume Wednesday morning at the Paramount studios in
Hollywood.
   The sessions are being conducted under the auspices of
Commissioner Leonard Farrell of the Federal Mediation Service at
the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers
headquarters in suburban Sherman Oaks, 20 miles northwest of
downtown Los Angeles.
   The talks followed a Memorial Day holiday weekend break during
which both sides studied the impact of last week's overwhelming WGA
ratification of a model contract with 73 independent producers.
   The talks followed a Memorial Day holiday weekend break during
which both sides studied the impact of last week's overwhelming
ratification by the writers' guild of a model contract with 73
independent producers.
   The independent contract, which permits immediate employment of
an estimated 400 writers, covers such programs as ``The Cosby
Show,'' and ``The Tonight Show with Johnny Carson.''
   The three-year waiver contracts grant the writers' key demand:
retention of the present formula for the residual payments that
writers get for syndication of one-hour television shows.
   The union touted a split in management ranks, but alliance
spokesman Herb Steinberg said the 73 independent contracts cover
only a few guild members and none of the concerns involved were
major companies.
